<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugShip     04-07 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Ship,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>5 Tons Of Marijuana, 4 Boats Seized In Gulf Of Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents seized a tugboat ``mother ship''
loaded with at least five tons of marijuana and three speedboats
that fled at up to 90 mph in a smuggling ploy out of style since
the early 1980s, officials said Thursday.
   The mother ship carrying the marijuana from Mexico was spotted
on radar Wednesday night about 100 miles southwest of Fort Myers on
Florida's Gulf Coast, and 14 people had been detained by late
Thursday, said Coast Guard Lt. Jeff Karonis.
   A new Customs Service plane designed for night surveillance was
in the area by chance on a shakedown training flight and for about
six hours its crew filmed the 105-foot, Honduran-registered mother
ship and six speedboats that rendezvoused with it.
   ``Once the Coast Guard cutter comes in, the speedboats scatter
like a bunch of bees,'' Roger Garland, air branch chief for the
U.S. Customs Service, said as he explained the videotape at a news
conference.
   The sophistication of the operation was almost as surprising to
drug agents as the outmoded mother-ship smuggling method.
   ``From a communications standpoint, when you have an operation
like that, you have a big network,'' Karonis said at the news
conference. ``That's a lot of people willing to stick their necks
out to be involved in some pretty bad activities.''
   In recent years, the most common marijuana smuggling at sea has
been on freighters docking in the Port of Miami, yachts with secret
compartments docking most anywhere and small boats picking up bales
dropped by aircraft.
   ``Something like this is what we had back in the early '80s. It
kind of breaks the trend here,'' said Karonis.
   Garland noted that most recent attention has been focused on
cocaine smuggled through the Bahamas and Haiti.
   In this case, the mother ship, the tugboat Turtola, made its
last port of call in Coatzacoalcos, Mexico, about 120 miles
southwest of Veracruz, before entering the Gulf of Mexico bound for
Tampa.
   Surveillance teams noticed several speed boats leaving Gulf
Coast ports late Wednesday when the Turtola neared Florida. The
Coast Guard moved in when four speedboats were gathered at the
mother ship, and six had been spotted at various times.
   The Coast Guard boarded the tug while the crew was working below
deck to sink it, Karonis said. The flooding was brought under
control, the South American crew of five was arrested, and the
Coast Guard counted 165 bales on board. He estimated the total load
was 10,000 to 15,000 pounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BoatShow     04-07 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat Show,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Fanciful Boat That's Easy to `Bale'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Powerboat and sailing enthusiasts may get that
sinking feeling when they enter the Renwick Gallery's new ``boat
show.'' They are greeted by a 28-foot vessel whose hull is woven
from eight bales of sweet-smelling alfalfa hay.
   This is art, folks.
   Sixteen contemporary American artists are inviting viewers to
join them on a voyage of the imagination in vessels of wood, glass,
ceramics, metals, textiles, hay and straw, back to antiquity and
forward to the unknown.
   Voyages depart daily free of charge from the Renwick, a gallery
of the Smithsonian's National Museum of American Art just down
Pennsylvania Avenue from the White House. The show opens today and
runs through Aug. 6.
   ``The show will be a surprise and astonishment,'' said the
Renwick's Jeremy Adamson, curator of the exhibition. ``These are
not pleasure boats or pirate ships or sailing yachts. These are
boats of mythology and fantasy and archaic symbolism.''
   Artist Michael Shaughnessy built his ``Hayboat'' with a wood
frame, a warp of twine and handfuls of alfalfa hay trucked in from
rural Virginia and his native Maine, where he is a teacher at the
University of Southern Maine.
   The humble stuff of animal fodder and primitive huts is his
favorite sculptural material, Shaughnessy says, because hay
symbolizes the bond between man and nature and is as ``near the
truth as any material I have ever found.''
   John Roloff, an artist from Oakland, Calif., fashioned the
jutting bow prow of a glass-paned ship resembling a greenhouse,
which appears to be sinking into the gallery floor.
   Inside the vessel are rocks and misting waters taken from
Pyramid Lake, what's remaining of an ancient sea called Lake
Lahontan which covered a vast area in northern Nevada during the
Ice Age. Roloff said the sinking ship represents his lament for the
lost purity of the Western wilderness.
   Another dramatic boat is Robert Hubany's ``Valhalla Vertical
Triptych,'' an ascending complex of glowing coals, bubbling lights,
ceramic corn stalks, snake-covered ladders and recorded drumbeats,
with fish at the bottom and carved birds circling overhead.
   Hubany says the boat ``suggests a symbolic passage to
self-discovery or enlightenment.''
   Ann McCoy's ``Barque with Lion Goddess III'' employs the
religious imagery and feminine deities of ancient Egypt, Greece and
Rome _ plus her sleep therapy with a psychoanalyst _ to suggest ``a
voyage through the night and the dream world of the subconscious.''
   Robert Shay, a potter, ceramics teacher and chairman of the Ohio
State University art department, contributed a pockmarked ceramic
boat with glassy deck, but says he prefers pots over boats.
   ``I hate boats,'' Shay says. ``They make me seasick.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
