<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     04-07 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Partial Pullout To Start April 25</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will begin a partial
withdrawal of its 62,000 troops in Hungary on April 25, Budapest
Radio reported.
   Government spokesman Gyoergy Marosan told the radio Thursday
that the partial pullout will end by late June.
   Defense Minister Col. Gen. Ferenc Karpati announced in January
that preparations for the withdrawal were almost complete and that
an armored division would be among the major units leaving.
   In a speech Dec. 7 to the United Nations, Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev promised a unilateral reduction of 500,000
Soviet troops over two years, including withdrawing 50,000 Red Army
men and 5,000 tanks from East Germany, Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
   Hungarian officials said Soviet armed forces stationed here
would be cut by at least 25 percent.
</TEXT>
