<FIRST>r w PM-US-ClimateAuthority     04-07 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Climate Authority,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Against Supranational Climate Authority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, saying it is
premature to consider a sweeping ``law of the air,'' opposes the
idea of an international authority to protect the world against
changes in climate.
   William A. Nitze, deputy assistant secretary of state for the
environment, told members of Congress on Thursday that some
countries seek an international agreement and it will be discussed
at meetings of existing international bodies.
   It may also come up when President Bush goes to Paris this year
for the annual summit meeting of heads of government of Western
nations and Japan.
   ``We believe it is premature, however, to be considering a
sweeping `law of the air' or supranational authorities to deal with
climate change, as some have recently advocated,'' Nitze said.
   A world climate conference is scheduled next year.
   A French-organized meeting of 24 governments in The Hague in the
Netherlands, including France, West Germany, Norway and the
Netherlands, issued a statement May 11 suggesting the possibility
of a supranational organization but not endorsing it. The United
States was not invited to the meeting.
   A ``law of the air'' might be similar to the ``law of the sea,''
a treaty that was negotiated through the United Nations. The United
States has opposed it, and it has not gone into effect. The
Canadian government has suggested an international law of the air.
   Nitze was testifying before the House Foreign Affairs
Committee's subcommittee on human rights and international
organizations.
   He said the United States will have to evolve its domestic
strategy and then develop an active international strategy to deal
with changes in climate.
   He forecast a 50 percent chance that by the year 2100 average
temperatures will be 2.7 to 8.1 degrees Fahrenheit higher than they
are today.
   Such a change could affect all nations and every human activity,
he said _ winds and current would be altered, some areas would get
more rain and some less, the sea would rise and threaten what has
been built on shores.
   But he added that the predictions are uncertain because they do
not take into account the impact of cloud cover, the reactions
between air and ocean and other variables.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
