<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Butter-Brazil     04-07 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Butter-Brazil,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>5,000 Tons of Butter, Oil Sold to Brazil at Bargain Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has sold 5,000
metric tons of surplus butter and butteroil to Brazil for $9.85
million, a fraction of what the government paid for it under the
dairy price support program.
   Richard W. Goldberg, acting undersecretary, said Thursday that
the 2,000 tons of butteroil and 3,000 tons of butter were sold by
the department's Commodity Credit Corp. to Petrobras Comercio
Internacional S.A.-Interbras, a Brazilian state trading company.
   Deliveries of the surplus products are scheduled through
September. No credit arrangements were involved.
   Federal laws, including last year's Hunger Relief Act, mandate
the export sale of 150,000 tons of dairy products annually through
September 1990. So far this fiscal year, sales have totaled 15,763
tons, Goldberg said.
   According to a recent report on CCC holdings, surplus butter as
of Jan. 31 totaled about 155,000 metric tons and butteroil, 1,640
tons. A metric ton is approximately 2,205 pounds.
   The report showed that CCC had an investment of about $1.46 per
pound in the butter and $1.64 in the oil. The price charged to
Brazil was about 84 cents per pound for the butter and 98 cents for
the butteroil.
   Sales are made to foreign buyers at approximately the prevailing
world market prices so as not to undercut other foreign suppliers.
   The CCC buys surplus dairy products to support the price of milk
paid to farmers.
</TEXT>
