<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0415EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial-Testimony 1stAdd   04-07 0880</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Testimony, 1st Add,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: did so.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SULLIVAN: Now, sir, in the spring of 1984, you had been at the
NSC for about three years, correct?
   NORTH: Three years too long, yes, sir.
   SULLIVAN: And that was a time when an officer would normally go
back to normal uniformed Marine duties, correct?
   NORTH: Yes, sir.
   SULLIVAN: What happened that prevented you from going back to
the Marine Corps at the end of your three-year tour at the NSC?
   NORTH: I probably learned a little bit about it right here in
this courtroom because I didn't know all of what you have come to
know about that. I, a number of times, had discussions with Mr.
McFarlane, who was my boss, with Don Fortier who was my immediate
superior, to the effect that I had orders and was going to go back
to Camp Lejeune. At one of the meetings I had with Director Casey
about the time all of this is being set up down south, he told me
that, look, there is more important things than being the battalion
commander, which is what I wanted to be. ... I expressed to him my
reservations about staying at the NSC, and he said well, we will
take care of that. And, indeed, he did, or someone did, because I
was called by the commandant of the Marine Corps and told that I
would not be detached from the NSC and wasn't given a chance to _ I
guess Marines shouldn't be _ whine about it. ...
   SULLIVAN: Now, once the CIA is out and the freedom fighters are
left on their own, how did they function at that time period in
October 1984? What were the problems?
   NORTH: ... Everything that they had from the little tents that
they lived in to the homes that they had for their children, to the
food they ate, the weapons they carried, the bullets that they had,
everything had come from the CIA. All of the intelligence, all of
the operations planning. ... through the summer ... slowly but
surely more and more of that CIA responsibility had been, I
suppose, passed on to me. ... basically, what we would call a hand
off, just like in basketball, I suppose, you got the ball, go on
with it. ...
   SULLIVAN: Did you understand your assignment to be directly from
the president with his words that Mr. McFarlane uttered here in
court about keeping them together body and soul?
   MR. KEKER: Objection, your honor. Leading. ...
   SULLIVAN: What did you understand your assignment to be?
   NORTH: I understood it very clearly to be that I would be the
one to replace the CIA for each of these activities.
   JUDGE GESELL: Who told you that?
   NORTH: Mr. McFarlane told me. Admiral Poindexter told me.
Director Casey told me. On a number of occasions, I was told not to
tell other people, not to talk about it, to keep my operational
role very, very secret, that it should not be something that others
came to know about. I was particularly admonished that this should
never, ever be revealed, the fact that another country was
providing millions of dollars to help the resistance.
   SULLIVAN: Now, colonel, part of your responsibilities at the NSC
were very public in terms of briefings and things that you would
give, is that correct?
   NORTH: ... Many of us did briefings on our respective areas of
responsibility to the American people. ...
   SULLIVAN: You have heard evidence in the court about the fact
that some of the donors, like Mrs. Garwood and Mrs. Newington,
attended those briefings at functions organized by Mr. Channell's
organization, NEPL, correct?
   NORTH: Yes, sir.
   SULLIVAN: About how many briefings would you have given over the
course of the time you were at the NSC on the subject of Nicaragua
and its needs?
   NORTH: I would guess I probably gave, ballpark, 75 to 100
briefings total, in the period of time 1983 through the time I left
the NSC in 1986. ...
   SULLIVAN: Now, sir, Colonel North, focusing on the time period
in 1984 when money is no longer being provided to the CIA to
provide support to the resistance and you have had a hand off, so
to speak, what were the ways that the administration looked out to
help the resistance fighters?
   NORTH: ... The first steps that were taken were to get financing
from foreign countries. That was initiated by, as I described it,
Mr. McFarlane and Director Casey giving me the person to be in
touch with.
   SULLIVAN: Now, this was called third country support?
   NORTH: I would call it third country financial support. Yes.
   SULLIVAN: ... How was money raised from other countries?
   NORTH: Initially by Mr. McFarlane contacting directly the
ambassador of Saudi Arabia. ... Money went in I think at the rate
of about a million dollars a month which turned out to be not
enough, and so I went back to Mr. McFarlane and said we need more
money and at some point later on in either late '84 or early '85
the president asked the king for more and the king chipped in a
total, I think, of 32 million over that period of time.
</TEXT>
