<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial-Testimony 2ndAdd   04-07 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Testimony, 2nd Add,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: of time.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SULLIVAN: Now, what was your understanding regarding the
confidentiality of that kind of relationship between Saudi Arabia
and the United States in giving that kind of money?
   NORTH: ... I was told point blank by Mr. McFarlane not to reveal
that to anyone, that that was the direction of the president of the
United States, that I would not, could not reveal it. In fact, was
chastised for letting Director Casey know that this whole thing was
proceeding as it was. ...
   SULLIVAN: Were there other countries that assisted the United
States when the Congress wouldn't give money?
   NORTH: Yes, there were, there were other countries that provided
$2 million in the case of Taiwan. There was eventually $10 million
from _ the country of Brunei made an effort to submit but due to a
numerical error in the account it never arrived. ...
   SULLIVAN: Now, aside from money, once you get friendly nations
providing some money to support the freedom fighters did you also
establish what was called Project Democracy?
   NORTH: ... as the money began to flow Director Casey and then
the people from the Central Intelligence Agency, others individuals
... pointed out the need to expand the activities, to basically try
to replace the CIA's full service, if you will, to the resistance
and I went back to Director Casey. ... I asked him for the name of
a person who would be able to do these things and he gave me the
name of General Richard Secord. ... and so I went to General Secord
and he basically set up to provide those kinds of services to the
resistance that the CIA had provided before but to do it outside
the U.S. government.
   SULLIVAN: Did you talk with Mr. Casey about the applicability of
the Boland Amendment to the National Security Council?
   NORTH: I talked to Director Casey. I talked to Mr. McFarlane. I
talked to the NSC lawyers ... none of them thought that it applied
to the NSC.
   SULLIVAN: When Secord was brought into the picture and he
developed these companies was that an effort to comply with the law?
   NORTH: Well, precisely because what General Secord did was to
set up a series of organizations that would do what the CIA had
done before ... he basically created a mirror image outside the
government of what the CIA had done.
   SULLIVAN: What kind of projects was he working on particularly?
   NORTH: Well, he started out basically delivering munitions. ...
it got to the point where when a southern front became an absolute
necessity, he was the one who contracted to build that airfield in
Costa Rica. I guess the other part of that that's not real clear is
that we had ... to work with the neighboring countries. ...
   SULLIVAN: Now, sir, when Secord is operating out of these
neighboring countries, is it necessary for high level American
officials to have permission from the officials of those countries?
   NORTH: Yes. ... it would be impossible to do these things
without the permission of the highest levels of their governments.
I mean, it would be a disaster if you tried to do it without their
help. ... In some cases I even had to meet with the presidents of
those countries so that those people would agree to the kinds of
support and the kinds of measures that we were taking. ...
   SULLIVAN: Now, whenever you had such a contact with an official
of a neighboring country in Central America, would you always have
the permission of your superiors?
   NORTH: Yes, sir. I never made a single trip down there, whether
it was an official trip that was paid for by the NSC or whether it
was a trip that was paid for out of the resistance funds, never
made a single trip, never made a single contact with anybody down
there without the permission, express permission, of either Mr.
McFarlane or Admiral Poindexter, and usually, when I could, with
the concurrence of Director Casey.
</TEXT>
