<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial-Testimony 3rdAdd   04-07 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Testimony, 3rd Add,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: Director Casey.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SULLIVAN: During the time that you were acting in the capacity
of trying to keep the freedom fighters alive, did any of your
superiors, McFarlane or Poindexter or the president or anyone else,
say to you, Ollie, the Boland Amendment precludes you from engaging
in these activities?
   NORTH: Never.
   SULLIVAN: Such as airstrips?
   NORTH: Never.
   SULLIVAN: Or shipping weapons or doing one thing or another?
   NORTH: Never.
   SULLIVAN: Never heard that?
   NORTH: No, sir, not from the people I worked with. ... none of
the people I worked for ever told me that anything we did was
illegal. It was specifically done to avoid breaking the law.
   SULLIVAN: Did the president himself act to facilitate help for
the freedom fighters, for example, by calling the presidents of
foreign countries?
   NORTH: Yes, sir.
   SULLIVAN: Now, we have three ways you have talked about: third
countries, Project Democracy, the neighbors in the area, and would
there be a last one, the private citizens in America such as Mrs.
Garwood that the jury met, who would contribute to this effort?
   NORTH: Yes, sir. ...I was authorized to go and brief these
people. I was told specifically that I could not personally, me
Ollie North, ask them for money; that I was a government official.
   SULLIVAN: What did you understand that to mean, Colonel North?
   NORTH: I understood that I wouldn't ask people for money, and I
didn't ... My role was simply to be one of explaining what the
threat was to the United States ... but that I would not ever say,
now, Mrs. Jones, or, Mrs. Smith, or, Mr. so and so, would you
please give money. And I never did that.
   SULLIVAN: You are accused in this case, Colonel North, of
conspiracy to commit a tax fraud. Did you do so?
   NORTH: No, sir, I did not.
   SULLIVAN: Did you ever talk with any of the donors about their
taxes or how they should give to get deductions?
   NORTH: Never.
   SULLIVAN: With respect to these areas of activity, did you
regard or were you told that your activities in this area should be
kept covert, secret, especially with respect to activities in
Central America and neighboring countries, third country support?
   NORTH: Yes. Specifically, the first one, on third country,
particularly the financial support ... I was told never to reveal
that to anybody. ... The people I was dealing with ... were high
level officials in those governments. They had political opponents
in their own governments, and they had people trying to kill them,
from the communist side.
   SULLIVAN: Now, sir, focusing on the time period in which you are
involved with these four aspects of work to support the freedom
fighters, did you have an operational account which you used in the
NSC?
   NORTH: Yes. ... I got approval from Mr. McFarlane in person, to
set up a fund that I could dispense to support resistance leaders
when they came to the United States. ...eventually, that was
broadened to include a hostage recovery initiative, and it was to
remain very secret. ...
   SULLIVAN: And over the course of running this special mission
for hostage release, would you have expended several tens of
thousands of dollars out of the operational fund?
   NORTH: Certainly that, yes, sir. ...
   SULLIVAN: Colonel North, approximately how many people over the
years would you have paid out of the operational fund that you
maintained in the office?
   NORTH: ... the total number of people that _ who had _ I don't
want to use the word paid because that isn't accurate, who had
their expenses reimbursed or who were paid would probably be in
excess of 40 people. ...
   SULLIVAN: Did you yourself have reimbursements of expenses out
of these funds?
   NORTH: Yes, sir, I did.
   SULLIVAN: Would you explain to the jury how that worked?
   NORTH: ... There were times when I would do things that it was
not either appropriate or timely or secret to bill it back through
the government. ... The traveler's checks that I signed and that
I've been charged with were _ When I wrote those traveler's checks
that was my money. It was my money because I had reimbursed myself
for expenses I had out of my own pocket.
</TEXT>
