<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0410EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NATOReductions     04-07 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO Reductions,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former NATO Commander Calls for 50 Percent Troop Reduction in Alliance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former NATO commander wants to reduce the
alliance's active conventional forces by 50 percent, with the
Warsaw Pact cutting its strength to the same number of troops.
   Calling NATO's current proposal only a starting point for
negotiations with the Warsaw Pact nations, retired Army Gen. Andrew
J. Goodpaster on Thursday told the Senate Armed Services Committee
his plan amounts to a ``radical restructuring'' on both sides.
   The current NATO proposal calls for a 5 percent to 10 percent
cut in battle tanks, heavy artillery and armored troop carriers.
The offer came in response to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's
proposal last December to cut the Red Army by 10 percent with a
reduction of 5,000 tanks and 50,000 troops in Eastern Europe.
   ``I do not think the interests of the West would be served if
that's as far as we went,'' said Goodpaster, who served as supreme
Allied commander in Europe from 1968 to 1969.
   Goodpaster, 74, said his proposal calls for ``parity, with total
active forces on each side at no more than 50 percent of present
NATO strength.''
   The proposal surprised the members of the Senate Armed Services
panel with Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., interrupting Goodpaster's
testimony to clarify what the retired general had suggested.
   ``Do you think it's a mistake to focus in isolation on the
current NATO proposal?'' Nunn asked.
   ``I do indeed,'' responded Goodpaster, the onetime aide to
former President Eisenhower who helped him organize NATO's military
arm in the early 1950s.
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the
committee, described Goodpaster's proposal as ``history in the
making, a bold initiative.'' Nunn called the plan a ``bold
proposal.''
   After the hearing, Nunn said Goodpaster's plan, coming from a
``stalwart supporter of the alliance,'' would cause a considerable
stir.
   Goodpaster is telling NATO officials, ``Get your thinking caps
on,'' Nunn said.
   Goodpaster is chairman of The Atlantic Council of the United
States, a NATO support group.
   The panel also heard from Phillip A. Karber, a defense
consultant with a subsidiary of the Ford Aerospace Co., who argued
against 50 percent reductions in NATO forces, and Stan Sloan, a
former CIA analyst on NATO affairs who serves as a senior
specialist in international security.
   Sloan told the committee that French officials had expressed
concerns about NATO's proposed cuts and favored unilateral
reductions if there had to be any agreement.
   Meanwhile, House Armed Services Chairman, Rep. Les Aspin,
D-Wis., said NATO should accept the Warsaw Pact's offer and stop
refusing to include aircraft in the first round of negotiations.
   ``We should take a leaf from Mikhail Gorbachev's book and accept
our opponent's first offer,'' Aspin told an audience in the Hague,
Netherlands. ``It would do us more good militarily and politically
than if we prevailed with NATO's go-slow position.''
   Aspin has criticized NATO's position since negotiations began
last month in Vienna between Moscow and the Warsaw Pact nations and
NATO.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
