<FIRST>r w PM-Obit-Shaw     04-07 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Shaw,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marine General, Cuban Missile Crisis Adviser, Dies at 78</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Marine Corps Brig. Gen. Samuel Robert
Shaw, a former adviser on the Cuban missile crisis and the Vietnam
War, has died at a hospital in Fort Belvoir. He was 78.
   Shaw died April 4 at DeWitt Army Hospital in suburban Virginia
after suffering a heart attack.
   Shaw served as an adviser to President John F. Kennedy during
the 1962 Cuban missile crisis. For six years during the Vietnam War
era, he was an adviser to the Senate Armed Services Committee and
traveled to Vietnam 13 times.
   In 1972, he was named the chief legislative liaison with the
Selective Service System. He retired for the second time in 1977
and was presented the Distinguished Civilian Service Medal by
President Jimmy Carter.
   Born in Cleveland, he graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy in
1934. During World War II, he served in the Pacific and had
assignments with the 6th Marine Division in China.
   He also served in Korea during the war there and later commanded
the Marine Corps' Landing Force Amphibious Training Unit in
Coronado, Calif. He retired from the Corps in 1962. His decorations
include the Legion of Merit and two Bronze Stars.
   Survivors include his widow, Joyce Phillips Shaw of Alexandria,
Va.; two sons, Mike Shaw of Merced, Calif., and William Shaw of
Alexandria; a brother, William H. Shaw II of Fort Myers, Fla.; a
sister, Margaret Shaw Roberts of San Diego, and two grandchildren.
</TEXT>
