<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0403EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-North'sNotebooks     04-07 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North's Notebooks,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>North's Decision to Testify Means He Must Produce Notebooks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-North Trial Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's decision to testify in his
trial also means he must turn over his notebooks, which prosecutors
may use to prove North shredded documents during the Iran-Contra
affair.
   ``We are prepared to produce'' the notebooks, North attorney
Barry Simon said toward the close of Thursday's court session. The
notebooks cover the period from October 1984 to Nov. 25, 1986, the
day North was fired from the National Security Council.
   North's decision to take the stand takes away any privilege he
may have to refuse to produce documents in his possession.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell had ruled earlier in the
North trial that he didn't have to surrender his notebooks, based
on his constitutional right against self-incrimination.
   At a hearing Jan. 25, Simon suggested that prosecutors might try
to use the notebooks in the portion of the case alleging
destruction of documents by North in November 1986 as the
Iran-Contra affair was unfolding.
   In arguing against production of the notebooks, Simon said
prosecutors might try to link references in the notebooks to
documents that North allegedly destroyed before leaving the NSC.
   North made daily entries in the spiral-bound notebooks while he
worked at the National Security Council. The office of independent
counsel Lawrence Walsh obtained a subpoena for them March 3 and now
wants that subpoena enforced.
   Simon wants to limit the use of the notebooks to those entries
around the time periods of the alleged crimes North is accused of
committing. Gesell said some of the entries may be classified
material and should be censored.
   The judge said he would issue an order today addressing those
questions.
   Portions of the notebooks that were turned over earlier to
Congress and have been made public contain a wealth of information.
   One charge against North is that he obstructed Congress by
helping prepare a false chronology that said no U.S. official
learned before January 1986 that Hawk missiles had been shipped to
Iran in November 1985.
   The notebooks show North's participation in helping arrange the
shipment.
   In notebook entries for Nov. 20, 1985, North detailed a plan for
transporting the Hawks to Iran in exchange for a four-phase release
of hostages. Several days later, the shipment was made aboard a
CIA-controlled airline.
   North's notebooks confirm Contra leader Adolfo Calero consulted
with him on weapons needs and purchases.
   North's notebooks describe successful efforts in obtaining false
certificates from Guatemalan officials stating that arms which were
in fact destined for the Contras were for the exclusive use of the
Central American country to which they were being sent. The false
certificates enabled one of North's co-defendants, Richard Secord,
to ship more than 90,000 pounds of East European munitions by
chartered aircraft from a European arms dealer to the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
