<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan-Dissident     04-07 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-Dissident,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Publisher Burned To Death In Clash With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident publisher accused of printing
seditious articles burned to death in his office today after
firebombs he hurled at police sparked a 90-minute blaze in the
building, police said.
   Taipei Police Chief Wang Chun said Cheng Nan-rong, publisher of
opposition Freedom Era magazine, tossed the firebombs from his
third-floor office at riot police who had come to arrest him for
printing articles that advocated an independent Taiwan.
   At least 12 policemen were injured, some with serious burns,
Wang said. Police said several residents in the seven-story
building were also injured by the fire.
   Wang said Cheng, a member of the Democratic Progressive Party,
the main opposition to the ruling Nationalist Party, was found dead
in the office after firemen extinguished the blaze.
   About 400 police cordoned off the building, and witnesses said
eight staffers of the magazine were arrested.
   Chen Yao-nan, a prosecutor at the Taiwan High Court, said he
issued a warrant for Cheng's arrest Thursday after the publisher
had twice refused to appear for a court hearing on sedition
allegations. Cheng could have been sentenced to death if convicted
of sedition.
   In addition to advocating independence for Taiwan, Cheng also
had published articles that called for a new constitution for this
island, officials said.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a
civil war in China, continue to maintain they are the legitimate
government of all China and that Taiwan is a Chinese province.
   Both Taiwan and China are opposed to an independent Taiwan, and
China has indicated it would use force to prevent the establishment
of an independent Taiwan.
</TEXT>
