<DOCNO> AP890407-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0409EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-North-Noriega     04-07 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Noriega,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Document Says Noriega Offered To Sabotage Targets in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega met
with Oliver North in 1986 and offered to sabotage Nicaraguan
targets including an airport and oil refineries, according to
evidence presented at North's trial.
   The information is contained in a U.S. government ``admission of
facts'' focusing on the Reagan administration's secret assistance
to the Contra rebels at a time when Congress had cut off military
aid to the rebel force.
   In late September 1986, North reported to his boss,
then-national security adviser John Poindexter ``on his London
meeting with Noriega,'' said a portion of the 42-page admission.
   ``Noriega would try to take immediate actions against the
Sandinistas and offered a list of priorities including an oil
refinery, an airport and the Puerto Sandino off-load facility,''
said the admission.
   In late August, according to the admission, North told
Poindexter that a representative of Noriega had said the Panamanian
leader ``would assassinate the Sandinista leadership for the U.S.
government.''
   A Panamanian military spokesman on Thursday denied the
allegations. Maj. Edgardo Lopez called them ``another cock-and-bull
story of the United States to continue strangling the Panamanian
people and intensify its defamation campaign against the chief of
our Defense Forces.''
   According to the court document, the assassination offer came
``in exchange for a promise from the USG (U.S. government) to help
clean up Noriega's image and a commitment to lift the USG ban on
military sales to the Panamanian defense forces.''
   North told the representative that ``U.S. law forbade''
assassinations of foreign leaders and the representative responded
by saying Noriega ``could accomplish many essential things.''
   Noriega, said the representative, ``had helped the USG the
previous year in blowing up a Sandinista arsenal,'' said the
admission of facts.
   British individuals who had run the operation against the
arsenal had used a Panamanian civilian ordnance expert, North told
Poindexter, according to the admission.
   North told Poindexter that the cost of any operations ``could be
borne by Project Democracy,'' the covert private aid network that
North had set up with Richard Secord and Albert Hakim, now
co-defendants in the Iran-Contra case.
   Poindexter responded that if Noriega had assets in Nicaragua, he
could be helpful. The national security adviser also said that the
U.S. government could not be involved in assassination, but
Panamanian assistance with sabotage ``would be another story,''
according to the admission.
   Both the prosecution and North's lawyers have agreed to the
wording in the admission of facts. The document was assembled to
avoid a protracted legal battle over classified information which
North's lawyers want to present in his defense.
   The admission is a summary of highly sensitive classified
material which the government refuses to allow into the courtroom.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
