<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0407EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Tribals     04-07 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Tribals,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike By Tribal Separatists Leaves 16 Dead, 35 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-day strike called by tribal
militants demanding autonomy in the northeastern state of Assam has
left at least 16 people dead and 35 injured, according to news
reports.
   Since the strike began March 27, there have been 25 cases of
arson, 31 attacks on police patrols and 25 bombings, United News of
India said Thursday.
   The agency said disrupted transportation services had cost the
government nearly $1.5 million in lost freight charges.
   Passenger rail services in the region, about 1,000 miles east of
New Delhi, resumed Thursday after a 10-day suspension.
   Those killed in the violence included an army doctor and four
police officers, United News said. The agency said 25 police
officers were injured in bomb blasts and ambushes.
   The Bodo tribespeople are demanding a separate homeland on the
northern bank of the Brahmaputra River in Assam, a remote, hilly
state bordering Bangladesh and Bhutan.
   The proposed Bodoland would cover about one-third of Assam's
territory of 24,512 square miles, most of which is prime forest and
cultivable land.
   The Bodos, mostly farmers, were animists before they converted
to Hinduism and Christianity earlier this century. They make up
about 30 percent of Assam's 20 million people.
   The government has refused to consider their demand for a
separate state. Bodos say that migration to their traditional
homelands by non-tribal people has reduced farm sizes, causing
economic and social turmoil.
   Migration has been an issue for more than 20 years, but there
were few reports of violence until about two years ago.
   Bodo militants have called for more strikes. The next one is set
for April 18 and is to last for 20 days.
   According to government figures, at least 114 people have been
killed in separatist violence since February.
   Most of the victims have been non-tribal villagers in the
Bodo-dominated Kokrajhar and Udalgiri districts of Assam.
</TEXT>
