<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0259EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-UN-SovietRights     04-07 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Soviet Rights,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Experts Say Soviets Ready To Allow Appeals On Human Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two human rights experts affiliated with
the United Nations say Moscow is ready to sign an accord allowing
Soviet citizens to take complaints of rights abuses directly to
international investigators.
   Soviets would be able to bring cases against their government
involving allegations of torture, inhumane or degrading treatment;
forced labor; arbitrary arrest or detention; and restrictions on
emigration, among other abuses.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the General Assembly in
December that human rights should be given new emphasis in
international affairs, and this would be in line with that policy.
   The Soviet Union intends to sign the Optional Protocol to the
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, rights
officials said Thursday.
   Rajsoomer Lallah of Mauritius, chairman of the Human Rights
Committee, and Fausto Pocar of Italy, another committee officer,
told reporters the notice was unofficial and the Soviets had not
specified when the protocol will be signed.
   Their committee is an international body of U.N.-affiliated
legal experts with the power to order compensation.
   Pocar said he received the Soviet assurances while in Moscow in
November.
   Lallah said he also received unofficial confirmation from
Moscow, and noted, ``In October, we are going to examine the third
periodic (human rights) report of the U.S.S.R., and it is possible
that by then the decision will have been taken, or in process of
being taken.''
   The Soviet Union said last month it would accept World Court
jurisdiction in cases brought under the Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights and five other human rights treaties.
   The International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights
guarantees the individual's right to life; freedom from torture,
inhuman or degrading treatment; freedom from slavery, forced labor;
freedom from arbitrary arrest or detention; freedom of movement;
freedom of thought, conscience, peaceful assembly, and free
association, among other provisions.
   However, individuals do not have the right to approach the World
Court with allegations of rights violations, only governments.
   By signing the Optional Protocol, Moscow will be granting its
citizens the right to appeal directly to the Human Rights Committee.
   Hungary ratified the protocol last year, joining 40 other
nations that recognize it.
   Pocar and Lallah are two of the 18 human rights experts who
conclude a three-week session of the Human Rights Committee today.
The experts examined human rights reports filed by Uruguay, the
Philippines, Togo and New Zealand.
   Soviet acceptance of outside scrutiny of its human rights
practices should help Moscow's campaign to be host city for a human
rights conference in 1991.
   In January, Washington changed its position and said it would
accept a Moscow conference, citing the Soviet release of political
prisoners, easing of emigration and more tolerant views on free
speech and freedom of religion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
