<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionMarchRdp     04-07 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion March Rdp,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Activists Begin Converging On Capitol</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Abortion March, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   By plane from the West and train and bus from the East, tens of
thousands of pro-choice activists will converge on the nation's
capital for a march Sunday aimed at keeping abortion legal.
   ``The silent majority is mobilizing,'' said Betty Crowe,
president of Planned Parenthood of Central Indiana, at a news
conference Thursday in Indianapolis.
   About 200 Indiana residents will leave Saturday on buses bound
for Washington to join pro-choice activists from around the
country. Organizers are reluctant to predict the size of the
demonstration, but they expect it will be far larger than a March
1986 rally of about 90,000 in the capital.
   ``One thing I've noticed from going to the march two years ago _
the feeling is very different this time,'' said Janet Callum,
director of administrative services at the Feminist Women's Health
Center in Atlanta.
   ``Two years ago, it wasn't as urgent a situation. Now, people
feel we need to show the Supreme Court and the president and the
elected representatives that the majority of the people in this
country are pro-choice,'' she said.
   The march comes a few weeks in advance of oral arguments
scheduled before the U.S. Supreme Court on a Missouri case that
could reverse or severely limit the high court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade
decision that legalized abortion.
   The march also follows a demonstration by 65,000
anti-abortionists at the White House in January. President Bush has
continued the Reagan administration's push to overturn Roe vs. Wade.
   Among the pro-choice activists going to Washington will be a
plane load of celebrities from Los Angeles, including Donna Mills
and Morgan Fairchild. Other Hollywood stars who plan to attend are
Glenn Close, Kelly McGillis, Cybill Shepherd, Susan Sarandon, Marlo
Thomas, Polly Bergen, Ellen Burstyn, Teri Garr, Veronica Hamel and
Valerie Harper.
   The celebrities plan to have breakfast with members of Congress
on Sunday before joining the march.
   About 25,000 New Yorkers are expected at the rally, including
10,000 from New York City, organizers said.
   ``I do believe the sheer size of it will provide an impact and
send an important message ... that a majority of people in this
country are pro choice,'' said Mimi Grinker, a spokesman for
Planned Parenthood of New York City.
   Planned Parenthood in New York City has chartered a plane, a
train and 10 buses to carry demonstrators to Washington. The New
York City chapter of National Organization for Women has chartered
160 buses.
   About 2,500 people are expected to board more than 50 buses in
Boston for the march.
   ``We want to participate in showing ... the pro-choice position
is supported by mainstream Americans, men and women from all walks
of life,'' said Boston YWCA President Tyra B. Sidberry.
   Win Johnson, march organizer with the Minnesota Pro-Choice
Coalition, said at least 1,000 people from Minnesota are traveling
by bus, plane and train to the demonstration.
   ``Pro-choice people have been silent too long. We need to come
out of the closet and into the streets. We've played nice girl too
long,'' she said.
</TEXT>
