<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-07 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Marginally, Nikkei Up 189 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
Friday, while share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar ended trading at 132.08 yen, down 0.07 yen from
Thursday's close of 132.15 yen. It opened at 132.10 yen and stayed
in a tight range of 132.07 yen to 132.15 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
365.01 points Thursday, the second largest decline this year,
recouped 189.27 points, or 0.57 percent, closing at 33,185.05.
   Currency traders said trading was quiet as market participants
awaited the release of U.S. jobless figures for March, due out
later Friday.
   But there was demand for the dollar in the Tokyo market, mainly
because of higher U.S. interest rates and recent political
uncertainties in Japan, said one trader at a commercial bank in
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The higher U.S. interest rates make the dollar more attractive
for foreign investors.
   Market participants, however, also were concerned about possible
Bank of Japan intervention if the dollar rises above 133 yen,
traders said.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the market's key index rose
as speculative investors bought issues that became cheaper in
Thursday's plunge.
   Individuals actively bought issues such as chemical and
construction shares, while institutional investors hesitated to
make major moves amid political uncertainties and the release of
the U.S. unemployment figures, said one dealer with a major
securities firm in Tokyo.
   Opposition parties have been demanding the resignation of Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita and his Cabinet because of politicians'
links to a widening stock-profiteering scandal.
   It was disclosed this week that Takeshita received $380,000 in
contributions to 1987 fund-raising parties from Recruit Co., a
services conglomerate that offered bargain-price unlisted shares in
its real estate subsidiary to some 160 influential political and
business figures.
   Prosecutors have arrested 14 people on bribery and securities
law violation charges, and three Cabinet members have resigned in
connection with the scandal. In public opinion polls, support for
Takeshita has dropped as low as 9 percent.
</TEXT>
