<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-Otters     04-07 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Otters,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Rescued Otter Dies At Sea World</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third of five otters pulled from the
Alaskan oil spill has died, too weakened from ingesting crude oil
to respond to treatment at Sea World, a spokesman for the marine
park said.
   Blood samples from the remaining two otters were being analyzed
to determine if they were responding to efforts to draw the toxins
from their blood, said park spokesman Dan LeBlanc.
   ``Whether the animals are healthy enough to be stabilized
remains to be seen,'' LeBlanc said. ``We feel that if we had
started this early on, even in the field, we might have had a shot
at saving them.''
   One of otters died Tuesday; a second died Wednesday; the third
on Thursday.
   Tests showed that ingested oil apparently caused liver and
kidney damage in the otters, caught with other wildlife in the
10-million gallon oil spill from the Exxon tanker Valdez, which ran
aground March 24 in Alaska's Prince William Sound.
   The nation's worst oil spill has killed thousands of animals and
has resulted in millions of dollars in losses to fishermen. The
spill now covers more than 2,600 square miles.
</TEXT>
