<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0328EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Gorbachev-Reax     04-07 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev-Reax,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachevs Take London By Charm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev-Britain, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his wife
worked the crowds of London, kissing some schoolchildren and
shaking a sea of outstretched hands.
   Gorbachev visited a high-tech factory, asked workers about the
size of their paychecks and made an impromptu stop on a London
street.
   His wife, Raisa, went to school and visited a church, gave
chocolates to a child and viewed a museum exhibit about Karl Marx.
   At each stop, they left behind grinning crowds and good feelings.
   ``I was the first person to shake his hand,'' said Tim Haggarty
of Londonderry, Northern Ireland, after Gorbachev hopped from a
limousine outside Westminister Abbey to chat with cheering
onlookers.
   He called Gorbachev ``a hero,'' saying, ``This is the best day
in my entire life.''
   Gorbachev also visited a factory Thursday, asking surprised
workers not only about quality control but whether they were happy.
   ``He even asked me my salary, which was a bit embarrassing
because I think us English like to keep our salaries to
ourselves,'' said Michael Smith, a 43-year-old worker at the Case
Communications Ltd. plant 18 miles northwest of London.
   The factory produces systems that enable computers to talk to
each other. The company said the Soviets invited themselves last
week because Gorbachev would be interested in its technology.
   Gorbachev spoke with particular friendliness to Smith, a senior
designer of printed circuit boards.
   ``He was a very friendly chap, I thought,'' Smith said.
   ``He was more interested in my private life. He asked where I
was educated, what sort of school I went to, where I lived, what
size of house I had. He wanted to talk about my family, my wife and
children, where they went to school.''
   Employee Angela Dawkins, 42, told Gorbachev she had worked at
the factory ``for six happy years.''
   Gorbachev fixed her with a stare and said: ``Are you saying this
because the bosses are listening?''
   ``No, I really mean it,'' she said.
   ``Ah yes, I can see from your eyes,'' she said Gorbachev replied.
   Mrs. Gorbachev, meanwhile, did not seem to mind trading the
tropical heat of Cuba, the couple's previous stop on their
three-nation tour, for London's chilly rain.
   ``I feel quite fresh after Havana,'' she told reporters at Tower
Bridge during a five-minute stop at the misty River Thames.
   Visiting Prior Weston primary school, she received a bouquet of
red carnations and urged the children to ``tell your grown-up
brothers and sisters, your parents and your friends, that we spoke
about flowers growing throughout the world.''
   Mrs. Gorbachev sealed this wish with a kiss, leaving 9-year-old
Benjamin Robinson embarrassed and adorned with two red lipstick
marks on his cheeks.
   ``I didn't dislike it. But I didn't like it either,'' Benjamin
said.
   ``You have got a bit of history on your cheek,'' teacher Mary
Caven told him.
   ``Eventually Mum will make me wash it off,'' Benjamin replied.
   Mrs. Gorbachev also toured the Museum of London, where she
watched a few scenes from a Punch and Judy show and saw an exhibit
commemorating Marx, communism's founding father, who lived in
London.
   Mrs. Gorbachev also visited St. Paul's Cathedral, where
4-year-old Emma Scott presented her with flowers. Mrs. Gorbachev
gave her a kiss and presented her with a box of Russian chocolates.
   In Moscow, Soviet media painted a generally glowing picture
Thursday of Gorbachev's first day in London.
   The nightly news program ``Vremya'' devoted more than 20 minutes
to the visit and reported no disagreement with Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher beyond Gorbachev's friendly correction of her
estimate of how long they had talked.
</TEXT>
