<FIRST>r a PM-HudsonSuit     04-07 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hudson Suit,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Hudson's Lover May Accept Lower Award</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents. Hearing scheduled to begin 1 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Rock Hudson's lover may accept less
than the $21.75 million a jury awarded him in the landmark AIDS
case, his attorney said.
   Marc Christian would be inclined to accept a reduction as long
as it doesn't go below $9 million in actual damages and $3 million
in punitive damages, said his lawyer, Harold Rhoden.
   ``It's important to preserve the message that was sent,'' Rhoden
said, ``and to do that we must preserve the punitive damages.''
   The case was to return to court today in the wake of sexual
accusations and lie detector tests, and Rhoden said he would not be
surprised if Superior Court Judge Bruce Geernaert reduced the award.
   ``I'm going to ask him to let the verdict stand, but I've got to
concede he probably won't,'' Rhoden said Thursday.
   The attorney for the Hudson estate, James Parker Mills, said
Thursday he wants a new trial, citing new evidence from a man who
claims he had sex with Christian after his lawsuit was filed.
   That man, Gunther Fraulob, took a polygraph exam and passed,
Mills said. But Rhoden said Christian, who adamantly denies having
sex with Fraulob, also passed a lie detector test.
   Christian, who won his huge judgment against the Hudson estate
because the actor failed to tell him he had AIDS, contended he was
so traumatized by learning about it that he has remained celibate
ever since. Fraulob said they had sex shortly after Christian filed
his lawsuit in November 1985.
   Neither man's lie detector test is admissible in court.
   Christian, 35, has maintained that he lived in fear of
developing AIDS after learning of Hudson's affliction shortly
before the actor died.
   The jury found that Hudson engaged in ``outrageous conduct'' by
concealing from Christian that he had AIDS. The jurors, who had
heard seven weeks of often lurid testimony about the dead star's
sex life, said in separate verdicts on Feb. 15 and Feb. 17 that
Christian should receive $14.5 million in actual damages and $7.25
million in punitive damages.
   Christian's case is seen as precedent-setting because he did not
develop AIDS and has tested negative for the disease. In previous
lawsuits, only those who contracted a sexually transmitted disease
were able to win damages.
   Hudson's estate and his personal secretary, Mark Miller, were
co-defendants in the civil lawsuir. Only Millers was named in the
second phase, for punitive and exemplary damages, because state law
prohibits such damages being awarded from an estate.
   Compensatory damages are intended to compensate for loss of
income, pain and suffering and actual damages. Punitive damages are
intended to punish, while exemplary damages would set an example
for others.
   Hudson, 58, the handsome leading man in such movies as ``Pillow
Talk'' and ``Giant,'' died on Oct. 5, 1985, three months after the
public learned that he had the disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0721EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Namibia     04-07 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Namibia,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non-Aligned Nations Condemn U.N. Namibia Chief, Ask 7,500 Peacekeepers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading the 101-member Non-Aligned
Movement in a scathing denunciation of the top U.N. official in
Namibia, black African nations have asked the world body to send
7,500 peacekeepers to the territory.
   They accused the world body Thursday of contributing to the
fighting in Namibia by being ``wholly unprepared to assume its
responsibilities'' of protecting the population and containing
South African forces.
   The Security Council, meanwhile, scheduled private consultations
this afternoon on Namibia.
   Namibian officials say at least 252 guerrillas of the South-West
Africa People's Organization have been killed this week in combat,
along with 24 members of the South African-led security forces.
   The violence has threatened the U.N.-sponsored plan for the
territory's independence.
   U.N. investigators in the field have concluded up to 1,000 SWAPO
guerrillas crossed the Angolan border into Namibia last weekend,
sparking bloody reprisals by Namibian territorial police.
   The Coordinating Bureau of the Non-Aligned Movement, a committee
that meets in New York and consists of U.N. diplomats from 101
countries, severely criticized Martti Ahtisaari, the U.N.'s special
representative for Namibia.
   The Non-Aligned nations were ``outraged to note that the murder
squads of Battalion 101 and Koevoet were operating with the full
authority of the Special Representative of the United Nations
secretary-general, Mr. Martti Ahtisaari,'' said a communique from
the group.
   ``The Bureau judged Mr. Ahtisaari's action to be ill-conceived
and a violation of Security Council Resolution 435 (1978),'' the
U.N. plan for Namibia's independence.
   South African troops of Battalion 101 were supposed to be
confined to barracks under U.N. independence transition plans for
Namibia, but they were allowed to reinforce security forces after
fighting broke out.
   Koevoet _ the Afrikaans word for crowbar _ is the name of a
special unit of black Namibian policemen, commanded mainly by white
South African officers.
   ``The Bureau called upon the Secretary-General of the United
Nations to confine the South African forces to their bases without
delay in compliance with Resolution 435 and to effect the immediate
full deployment of the 7,500 military (observer) component of UNTAG
in Namibia ... in order to ensure free and fair elections without
intimidation,'' the statement said.
   ``Furthermore, the Bureau expressed concern at the poor judgment
shown by the Special Representative of the Secretary-General in his
handling of the present crisis in Namibia and called on the
Secretary-General to ensure that the same does not happen in
future,'' said the Non-Aligned communique.
   The Security Council authorized 4,650 military observers for
UNTAG, but said it could deploy up to 7,500 soldiers if necessary.
   The Non-Aligned countries called on the United Nations to let
the SWAPO guerrillas battling the Namibian territorial police be
confined to bases in Namibia, on the same basis that 1,500 South
African troops are to be confined to barracks in the country.
   The size and cost of the Namibia operation has been a
contentious issue since December, when the Non-Aligned nations
sought 7,500 peacekeepers at a cost of up to $700 million annually.
   The five permanent Security Council members _ the United States,
Soviet Union, Britain, France and China _ sought a reduced force
that would cost less.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar recommended a
compromise in which 4,650 military observers were dispatched, but
up to 7,500 could be authorized if needed. That plan was budgeted
at $416 million.
   The Non-Aligned nations said that was too few peacekeepers, and
the dispute delayed the dispatch of the force. About 920
peacekeepers are in Namibia.
</TEXT>
