<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--ChangedCrucifix     04-07 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Changed Crucifix,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bishop Appoints Panel To Study Claims That Jesus Statue's Eyes Closed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic Bishop Donald W. Wuerl has
appointed a committee of four clergymen to evaluate claims that a
figure of Jesus Christ closed its eyes during a Good Friday service
in Ambridge.
   Wuerl said Thursday the committee will study reports by the Rev.
Vincent Cvitkovic, pastor of Holy Trinity Roman Catholic Church,
and five other people, who said they have evidence that the Jesus
figure changed in appearance.
   The statue appears to have its eyes closed to slits, while
church officials say that before Good Friday they were about
one-third of the way open.
   Thousands of people have visited the church to see the crucifix,
which is 15 feet above the altar.
   The Diocese of Pittsburgh said the reports are accompanied by a
videotape which shows the rehanging of the refurbished crucifix in
January and more videotape taken Good Friday, March 24.
   Committee members are Auxiliary Bishops John B. McDowell and
William J. Winter; the Rev. Lawrence A. DiNardo, diocean
chancellor; and the Rev. Robert L. McCreary, chairman of the
diocean Theological Commission.
   The committee has no deadline for its work.
</TEXT>
