<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0619EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Docks     04-07 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Docks,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dock Strike Looms Over Proposal To Change 42-Year-Old Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it will abolish a 42-year-old
law that guarantees jobs to nearly 10,000 British dockworkers, but
labor leaders say they will paralyze the country's ports with
strikes to block the change.
   Employment Secretary Norman Fowler told the House of Commons on
Thursday that the National Dock Labor Scheme was an anachronism.
   ``As long as the scheme continues to operate, it will remain the
biggest obstacle to a modern and efficient ports industry,'' he
said.
   A total of 1,700 dockworkers immediately walked off the job
Thursday at Tilbury east of London in protest.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative administration,
which has sharply restricted trade union powers, plans to write a
parliamentary bill to abolish the law by July.
   The bill is guaranteed passage through Parliament because of the
Coservative majority in the House of Commons.
   The current law regulates employment conditions in the 46 ports
it covers. It guarantees jobs to 9,400 dockworkers there by
ensuring staff levels can be cut only when workers quit voluntarily.
   Even an employee who loses a job when his or her employer goes
out of business is guaranteed a job with another employer.
   To soften the change, the government has agreed to pay about
$59,500 to each of the 1,000 dockworkers expected to lose their
jobs when the new law goes into effect.
   The 1.3 million-member Transport and General Workers Union
represents most of the 9,400 dockworkers involved. The union's
docks officer, John Connally, predicted a nationwide strike would
be called to protest the scheme.
   Britain has another 29 newer ports that employ 4,000 dockworkers
who are not covered by the National Dock Labor Scheme. But Connally
said he believed they would also walk off the job in sympathy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
