<DOCNO> AP890407-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0405EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia     04-07 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Guerrillas Criticize Vietnamese Pullout Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Khmer Rouge today denounced
Vietnam's plan to withdraw troops from Cambodia and called instead
for a pullout supervised by the United Nations.
   Resistance leaders also expressed doubt Vietnam would honor its
pledge to remove its remaining 50,000 to 70,000 troops from
Cambodia by Sept. 30.
   Vietnamese troops entered Cambodia in December 1978 and ousted
the communist Khmer Rouge, under whose rule an estimated one-fourth
of Cambodia's 8 million people died from famine and execution since
1975.
   But the clandestine Khmer Rouge radio, in its first public
statement on Vietnam's withdrawal plan, said ``the entire Cambodian
people absolutely cannot accept the announcement of a unilateral
troop pullout of the Hanoi Vietnamese aggressors.''
   The broadcast, monitored in Bangkok, also denounced Vietnam's
proposal that India, Canada and Poland oversee the withdrawal along
with a representative of U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar.
   Resistance officials oppose Vietnam's choices for the monitoring
force because of Poland's ties to the Soviet Union and India's
recognition of the Vietnam-backed government in Cambodia.
   ``Without genuine supervision by the United Nations, there would
be no genuine withdrawal of Vietnamese troops,'' the radio said.
   China, the main arms suppliers to the Cambodian resistance, also
has insisted that any monitoring force be established by the United
Nations and not Vietnam.
   The Khmer Rouge is the strongest of the three groups in the
resistance coalition headed by Prince Norodom Sihanouk. Fears that
the Khmer Rouge would regain power has been a major stumbling block
to a settlement of the political crisis brought on by Vietnam's
military presence.
   On Thursday, Vietnam's official Hanoi Radio reaffirmed that it
would withdraw its troops by Sept. 30 deadline and urged the
international community to prevent the brutal Khmer Rouge regime
from regaining power.
   Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia has been a major stumbling
block to establishing relations with the United States in the wake
of the Vietnam war and improving economic ties with non-communist
Southeast Asian nations.
   China also has refused to resume normal relations with the
Soviet Union as long as Vietnamese troops remain. Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev is to visit China next month for the first
Chinese-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   In the statement, the Khmer Rouge accused Hanoi of announcing
the unilateral withdrawal to avoid U.N. supervision so it could
secretly maintain troops in Cambodia.
   The statement, attributed to Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan,
said the move also was aimed at maintaining the pro-Vietnamese
Cambodian administration of Prime Minister Hun Sen.
   Resistance groups have called for disbanding the Phnom Penh
government and establishing a four-party coalition administration
under Sihanouk that would include Hun Sen's followers.
   The Khmer Rouge, in its statement, also called for the
four-party coalition government.
   In a written statement issued Thursday in Beijing, Sihanouk, the
former Cambodian ruler, rejected ``all decisions, all conditions,
and all accords'' announced by Vietnam regarding Cambodia.
   He urged Vietnam to pull out of Cambodia as soon as possible
under supervision of the United Nations, which would supervise new
elections.
   Indonesia, meanwhile, said it would sponsor a meeting between
Sihanouk and Cambodia's Vietnam-backed prime minister, Hun Sen,
next month. A spokeswoman for Sihanouk said he planned to meet with
Hun Sen on May 2 in Jakarta.
</TEXT>
