<HEAD>Senate Approves Letting Judges Tote Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges in Tennessee would be allowed to
carry guns in court for protection under a bill approved in the
state Senate.
   ``We have found incidents in our court in Shelby County and
across the state where members of the judiciary came under attack
and fear for their lives,'' said state Sen. James Kyle, sponsor of
the bill, which passed 23-2 on Thursday and now goes to the House.
   Kyle said judges already are eligible for the ``special deputy''
status needed to legally carry a handgun in Tennessee.
   ``You'll find most all of the judges at your criminal justice
center are armed, quite frankly,'' he said. ``If we trust these
people with administering the law, we ought to trust them with how
they will protect themselves.''
</TEXT>
