<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-07 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Tokyo Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar slipped slightly against the
Japanese yen today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index
rebounded after the previous day's sharp decline.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
365.01 points Thursday, its second-largest decline this year,
recouped 189.27 points, or 0.57 percent, finishing the week at
33,185.05.
   The dollar closed at 132.08 yen, down 0.07 yen from its
132.15-yen finish on Thursday. The U.S. currency opened at 132.10
yen and ranged 132.07 to 132.15 yen.
   ``The dollar-yen exchange rate stayed around the 132-yen level
all day. There were no major moves, mainly because participants
stayed on the sidelines because of the upcoming announcement of
U.S. unemployment figures,'' said a trader with Mitsubishi Bank,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. jobless rate for March was to be announced later today
in Washington.
   On the stock exchange, ``The Nikkei index recovered mainly
because the market still expects prices to go higher despite the
setback yesterday (Thursday),'' said Manji Ueda of Nomura
Securities.
   ``Japan's economic fundamentals and buying interest at the
beginning of the new business year are both strong enough to
overcome concern over political instability, which, however, is a
discouraging factor, of course,'' he said.
   For most Japanese companies, the fiscal year begins April 1.
   Trading was active, with volume on the market's first section
estimated at 1.3 billion shares, up from 1.2 billion shares on
Thursday.
   The government of Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita has been
rocked by a stock-profiteering scandal that surfaced last summer.
Opposition parties are calling for Takeshita's resignation
following reports he received large donations from Recruit Co., the
company at the center of the scandal.
   News reports today said Takeshita received a $190,000
contribution from the information conglomerate in 1986 in addition
to the previously disclosed $380,000 he received at two 1987
fund-raising parties.
   In the stock scandal, Recruit offered hundreds of thousands of
bargain-priced unlisted shares in a real estate subsidiary to about
150 influential political and business figures. The recipients then
profited handsomely when the stocks were publicly traded and rose
quickly in value.
   Prosecutors have arrested 14 people on bribery and securities
law violation charges, and three Cabinet members have resigned in
connection with the scandal. Support for Takeshita has dropped as
low as 9 percent in recent public opinion polls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
