<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern-Glance     04-07 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Glance,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Acquisition At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are key elements of Texas Air Corp.'s agreement to sell
Eastern Airlines to a group led by Peter Ueberroth, the former
baseball commissioner and Los Angeles Olympics organizer, in a
transaction valued at about $464 million.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OWNERSHIP STRUCTURE:
   Management: 30 percent
   Unionized and non-contract employees: 30 percent
   Private investors: 40 percent
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FINANCING SOURCES:
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and Ardshiel Inc., two New York
investment banks.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PAYMENT TO TEXAS AIR:
   _$200 million in cash
   _$185 million in debt securities
   _$79 million in Eastern assets, including a New York-Montreal
route and eight landing slots and one gate at New York's LaGuardia
Airport.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WHAT BUYERS WILL RECEIVE:
   _Eastern's fleet of jetliners and a route structure serving more
than 100 cities with major markets in South Florida, the Caribbean,
the East Coast and Latin America.
   _19.99 percent interest in System One, the Texas Air
computerized airline reservation service.
   _Other automated management information systems.
   _Texas Air authority to operate a Miami-London route.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CONDITIONS:
   _Approval of a reorganization plan by Eastern creditors and the
U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   _Long-term union agreements by April 11 to end their strike.
</TEXT>
