<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0646EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     04-07 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippines Court Clears Way For Civil Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Philippines court has cleared the
way for the trial of more than a dozen lawsuits aimed at recovering
billions of dollars allegedly stolen by former President Ferdinand
Marcos and his wife, Imelda.
   In a decision made Thursday and released today, the Philippines
anti-graft court said the couple had repeatedly ignored summonses
to answer the civil suits. The court also rejected claims that
Marcos was too ill to respond to the allegations.
   In New York, however, U.S. attorneys agreed Thursday to
temporarily separate Marcos from its $345 million racketeering case
because they said he was in too poor of health to stand trial
anytime soon.
   The U.S. government's action means only the case against Imelda
Marcos and others will proceed for now.
   The decision by the Philippines court clears the way for at
least 13 civil suits to go to trial. They are among 40 suits filed
by the government in July 1987 against Marcos, his wife and about
300 associates to recover up to $10 billion they allegedly
plundered during his 20-year rule.
   The suits claim a total $112 billion dollars in damages.
   Thursday's ruling means the trial can proceed even if the
Marcoses are not represented by attorneys.
   The Marcoses have been living in Honolulu since the February
1986 civilian-military revolt that ended his rule and swept Corazon
Aquino to power.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow the Marcoses to return for
security reasons.
   Thursday's ruling noted repeated efforts by Filipino officials
to serve the summonses on the Marcoses in Honolulu. It said all of
the summonses were ignored and the couple was declared in default.
   Under Philippine law, defendants in civil suits who are outside
the country may be served summonses at their last known address or
through publication in a newspaper in that area. A court may
declare a defendant in default if he fails to answer the summons in
60 days.
   For the Marcoses, that deadline lapsed Jan. 9, the ruling noted.
   The court's decision also said: ``The claim that defendant
Ferdinand E. Marcos has been seriously ill and hospitalized several
times as to make him incompetent to be put on notice ... is
absolutely devoid of merit. Such a claim is incredible and has no
legal bearing in the case at point.''
   Marcos, 71, is in guarded condition in Hawaii at St. Francis
Medical Center, where he has been confined since Jan. 15 for
treatment of heart and respiratory problems.
   In New York, the Marcoses are accused of siphoning more than
$100 million from their homeland's treasury and using the money to
buy art and real estate. Mrs. Marcos has pleaded innocent and is
free on $5 million bail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0647EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     04-07 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Say Marcos Too Ill To Stand Trial Now, Imelda Vows to Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imelda Marcos vowed to fight alone, if
necessary, against federal racketeering charges after her ailing
husband was temporarily severed from the case because of his poor
health.
   Prosecutors conceded that former Philippine President Ferdinand
E. Marcos is too ill to stand trial for now and agreed on Thursday
to separate him temporarily from the massive racketeering case.
   But his wife, who still faces trial in New York, remained
defiant.
   ``I look forward to defending myself. You don't have to be a
doctor to see how sick the president is,'' the former first lady
told The Associated Press in Honolulu. ``If I have to face the
court alone, so be it. I will walk into the courtroom with my head
held high.''
   Prosecutors wrote to the judge presiding over the case,
acknowledging that Marcos' health has deteriorated since a medical
examination by a government doctor last fall.
   ``Based upon Mr. Marcos' repeated bouts of pneumonia and his
susceptibility to other infection since January 1989, the
government is no longer able to represent to the court that Mr.
Marcos is now able to stand trial,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Debra
Livingston wrote to U.S. District Judge John F. Keenan in a letter
dated April 5 and disclosed Thursday.
   Marcos, 71, is in guarded condition at St. Francis Medical
Center in Honolulu, where he has been confined since Jan. 15 for
treatment of heart, kidney and respiratory problems.
   ``It's about time and I'm not surprised,'' said Richard Hibey, a
Marcos lawyer in Washington, D.C. ``I think there is ample and
uncontradicted medical evidence that he is in a grave and
deteriorating physical condition from which he is not likely to
survive.''
   Marcos was examined during the weekend by Francis Weld, a
court-appointed physician from New York, who examined Marcos last
October and determined that he was fit to travel to New York.
   But according to Ms. Livingston's letter, after his latest
examination Weld concluded that Marcos' health had deteriorated.
   The Marcoses are accused of siphoning more than $100 million
from their homeland's treasury and using the money to buy art and
real estate in New York. Mrs. Marcos has pleaded innocent and is
free on $5 million bail posted by a friend, tobacco heiress Doris
Duke.
   The Marcoses, eight associates _ including Saudi Arabian
businessman Adnan Khashoggi _ and a California bank were indicted
last October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
