<DOCNO> AP890407-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0654EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SnubbedSoviets     04-07 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Snubbed Soviets,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toronto Says Nyet To Soviet City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspicious city council members, resisting the
popularity and charm of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, have
rejected a proposal to form a sister-city relationship with the
Soviet city of Volgograd.
   After a spirited three-hour debate Thursday, the council voted
9-8 against a proposal to establish formal cultural ties with
Volgograd, formerly called Stalingrad. Volgograd is 600 miles
southeast of Moscow.
   Councilman William Boytchuk, who is of Ukrainian descent, led
the campaign against the proposal, saying the Soviets are not to be
trusted.
   ``Do not be fooled by his colorful rhetoric and undeniable
charm,'' Boytchuk said, referring to Gorbachev.
   Most of the 300 people who packed the city council chambers for
Thursday's debate seemed to agree. Boytchuk got thunderous applause
from the audience when he said: ``Volgograd _ Nyet, Nyet, Nyet.''
   But some city politicians were disappointed, having hoped the
move might foster international peace and understanding.
   ``It's a retrograde step in the pursuit of world peace,'' said
Councilman Jack Layton. ``It sends out a message that we still
believe in the mentality of the Cold War.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
