<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     04-07 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Rain in South and East, Heat in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across the South and
East today and snow was forecast as far south as Virginia, while a
heat wave continued to grip much of the West Coast and Arizona.
   Rain and thunderstorms fell in the lower Mississippi and
Tennessee valleys, the southern Appalachians and the southern Ohio
Valley.
   Storm winds gusted to 41 mph at Birmingham, Ala., Thursday
night, and power outages were reported around New Albany, Miss.
   A low pressure system over Alabama was expected to drop snow on
parts of the Appalachians today, with up to 3 inches expected in
the mountains of southwest and west-central Virginia.
   Rain was scattered across parts of New England and New York
state. A flood warning was in effect for Maine's Kennebec River,
which was expected to crest slightly above flood stage at Augusta
today.
   Flooding was significant in parts of eastern North Dakota and
northwest Minnesota. The Wild Rice River was forecast to crest 14
feet above flood stage at Abercrombie, N.D., and 12 feet above
flood stage at Hendrum, Minn. The Buffalo River was cresting at 11
feet above flood stage at Dilworth, Minn.
   In Ohio, the Scioto River was forecast to crest 2 feet above
flood stage at Piketon.
   Thursday was a very hot day across California with temperatures
above 90 degrees, and readings above 100 in parts of Southern
California. Record highs for April were established at Los Angeles,
San Diego, San Francisco, San Jose, Santa Maria and Riverside.
   El Toro was the nation's hot spot with a scorching 112 degrees.
   Temperatures remained in the 60s and 70s across California and
Arizona this morning, with some readings still in the 80s in
southern parts.
   At least twenty-three cities in Oregon, California, Nevada and
Arizona set or tied record highs Thursday. Los Angeles' reading of
106 degrees was its hottest April day on record, exceeding the
previous mark of 100 set in 1910.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
across the southern Atlantic Coast states, rain along the
mid-Atlantic Coast, snow in the Appalachians and showers from
Montana across much of the northern and central Plains to the
middle Mississippi Valley.
   Highs were expected to be in the 30s and 40s from the Dakotas
across the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and most of
the Ohio Valley to the Appalachians; 70s and 80s from inland areas
of the Pacific Northwest across much of Idaho, Utah, Nevada,
northern Arizona, New Mexico, the southern Plains, the central Gulf
Coast and Florida; 90s in most of California; and 100 to 105
degrees in southern Arizona and California.
   Elsewhere, highs were expected to be in the 50s and 60s.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 18 degrees at Warroad,
Minn., to 88 at El Toro, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 51 cloudy; Boston 42 windy; Buffalo 36 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 52 cloudy; Cincinnati 40 foggy; Cleveland 35
foggy; Detroit 36 partly cloudy; Miami 68 fair; New York 44 windy;
Philadelphia 43 fair; Pittsburgh 34 fair; Portland, Maine 41 windy;
Washington 44 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 35 cloudy; Chicago 43 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
64 fair; Denver 48 fair; Des Moines 41 fair; Indianapolis 35 foggy;
Kansas City 37 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 32 fair; Nashville 42
rain; New Orleans 61 fair; St. Louis 40 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 66 fair; Anchorage 30 fair; Las Vegas 74
fair; Los Angeles 83 fair; Phoenix 82 fair; Salt Lake City 55
partly cloudy; San Diego 73 fair; San Francisco 68 fair; Seattle 50
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 rain; Toronto 36 showers.
</TEXT>
