<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0721EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HirohitoAutograph     04-07 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hirohito Autograph,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auctioneer: Emperor's Name Worth More Than All U.S. Presidents Combined</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese buyers drove bidding at an auction of
famous signatures to more than $40,000 for the late Emperor
Hirohito's name on a simple courtesy letter, proving ``you can't
measure love,'' an auctioneer said.
   ``Hands started coming up everywhere,'' said Herman Darvick of
the moment bidding began on the 1934 document that was expected to
bring up to $3,000 at an auction where Abraham Lincoln drew $1,540
and Indira Gandhi, $1,500.
   Bidders quickly boosted the value of what was described by
Herman Darvick Autograph Auctions as an ``exceedingly rare early
manuscript Letter of State in Japanese.''
   ``I was standing. I could feel my knees buckling when it got
past $20,000,'' Darvick said.
   Several bidders Thursday kept their hands up right through the
$30,000 point. The gavel finally came down at $42,000 to loud
applause.
   ``You can get a complete autograph collection of all the U.S.
presidents from Washington to Bush for under $42,000,'' Darvick
said.
   The auctioneer's 10 percent commission at the sale at a
Manhattan hotel for 100 enthusiasts raised the price to $46,200.
   ``It's going back to Japan, where it should be,'' said Darvick.
   ``This is unique. I can't think of any other autograph going
like this one did,'' he said, adding that the enthusiasm seemed
based on emotion rather than investment value.
   Darvick said he misjudged ``the nation of Japan and their love
for their emperor.''
   Masayuki Miyamoto, who placed the winning bid on behalf of a
Japanese bank which was representing a client in Japan, declined to
say anything about the buyer.
   The letter was consigned by Carmen Mendieta Garcia-Velez,
daughter of Carlos Mendieta Y. Montefur, to whom Hirohito sent it
after Montefur was elected provisional president of the Republic of
Cuba on Jan. 18, 1934.
   The letter, signed boldly by Hirohito and K. Hirota, minister of
foreign affairs, said in part that the leaders ``send our sincere
wishes for the personal success of your excellency, in the same way
for the prosperity of his nation.''
   Hirohito, who was buried Feb. 24 in an elaborate funeral, was
worshipped by his people as a living god and branded a war criminal
in the later half of his 87-year life.
   Norio Murai, a New York resident who was one of the last bidders
to drop out, said it was very rare for a signature of Hirohito to
come up at auction and would only occur outside Japan.
   ``If he writes a letter to people, do you think somebody would
put it up for auction? People wouldn't think of it. It would be a
family treasure,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
