<DOCNO> AP890407-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0907EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ArmsPact     04-07 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Pact,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Bush Backing Off 1988 Arms Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush Administration does not plan to
modernize the nation's surveillance satellites despite a promise
last year by President Reagan, according to a report published
today.
   The New York Times quoted the chairman of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, Sen. David L. Boren, D-Okla., as saying
failure to improve the satellites ``would seriously jeopardize''
the national security.
   Improving the satellites was a condition for last year's Senate
approval of a treaty eliminating medium-range missiles.
   The Times noted that the Bush administration had presented its
intention not to improve the satellites ``as a proposal, not a
final decision.''
   Boren declined to discuss specifics of the program, the Times
said, but some experts described it as a multibillion dollar effort
to provide more KH-11 and LaCrosse surveillance satellites as well
as more personnel to analyze photographic and radar data.
   The KH-11 takes high resolution photographs and the LaCrosse
uses radar for surveillance at night and through clouds.
   Boren told the Times that if the Bush administration continues
with the plan not to improve satellite surveillance, it could
greatly damage the president's relationship with the Senate.
   Boren, chairman of the Intelligence Committee, also said that if
the administration fails to improve the system it ``would seriously
jeopardize our own near-term national security interests and could
slow down completion of a strategic arms reduction treaty.''
   The Senate Intelligence Committee last year extracted a promise
that the surveillance system would be modernized after threatening
to hold up approval of the treaty on Intermediate Range Nuclear
Forces, which bans medium- and short-range missiles on land.
   The treaty was signed by President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev at a Moscow summit meeting in June 1988.
</TEXT>
