<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Europe, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was steady at lower levels in thin
European trading late this morning as the market awaited the
release of the U.S. unemployment figures for March later in the day.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Traders said the dollar was almost certain to stay locked within
a narrow range until after the unemployment figures were released
this afternoon.
   ``The dollar has been trading sideways for three days and now
the dollar has virtually come to a standstill,'' one Rome trader
said.
   But he noted that the market was waiting for the unemployment
figures to give it direction.
   Economists were expecting the unemployment rate to rise to 5.2
percent in March from 5.1 percent in February.
   If the report turns out to be as expected, the dollar likely
would decline gradually, a trader said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.07 yen to a closing 132.08 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 131.95 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8690 West German marks, down from 1.8700
   _1.6410 Swiss francs, down from 1.6415
   _6.3075 French francs, down from 6.3125
   _2.1085 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1090
   _1,371.25 Italian lire, down from 1,371.75
   _1.1925 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1935
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7030, compared with
$1.7035 Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $384.50 a troy ounce,
down from $384.75 bid late Thursday. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$384.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $384.40, up from $384.35 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 59 cents to close at a bid
$386.15.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $5.82 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Friday.
</TEXT>
