<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Libya 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0507,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Admit Sending Fighter Jets To Libya</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with Britain criticizing Soviet explanation;
no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets have confirmed they sent fighter jets
last month to the radical North African Arab state of Libya but
insist the planes do not have the range to threaten Libya's
neighbors or Israel.
   Britain today rejected the Soviet explanation as frivolous, but
said the dispute will not spoil the the visit of Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov, in London
with Gorbachev, first told a news conference he did not know about
the sale. Later, however, Gerasimov went on television to confirm
elements of the report while seeking to minimize its significance.
   Gerasimov insisted during interviews Thursday on Channel 4 News
and BBC-TV that the number of jets sent was ``around half a
dozen,'' not 12 to 15 as reported by U.S. administration officials.
   U.S. Defense Department sources have said the aircraft are Su-24
Fencers, which can fly an 800-mile radius without refueling, enough
to reach Egypt and possibly Israel. They say Soviet transports
carried the dismantled jets to Libya in crates.
   Washington reports of the warplanes' sale were headlined in
Britain, dimming the glow emanating from Gorbachev's talks with
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   The prime minister's spokesman said Mrs. Thatcher asked
Gorbachev for an explanation and got none.
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe also raised the issue with
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze. When Shevardnadze
brought up British arms sales to Saudi Arabia, Howe replied that
Britain was concerned because Libya is a terrorist state, the
British spokesman reported.
   Gerasimov did not specify the type of aircraft sold in his TV
interviews. He said the planes were supplied to Libya under a 1986
deal _ ``an old contract'' _ and that not more than six were sold.
   ``This is not a long-range bomber,'' Gerasimov said. ``This is a
bomber that you can use for closer activities. Its operational
range is 300 miles.
   ``It's a frontline bomber. It's for defense only. You cannot
really use it for offensive purposes.''
   The interviewer noted that the planes could reach Israel if
refueled in the air, to which Gerasimov replied: ``Theoretically
maybe, but Libya has no refueling capacity at all.''
   He said on BBC-TV that the warplanes were delivered in March and
suggested they would not be operational for some time because they
were delivered ``in crates ... You must put them together. It takes
time and know-how to do it.''
   Foreign Minister William Waldegrave was critical of the Soviet
explanation.
   ``It's a rather odd style for a major arms deal, to say that the
planes do not really work and will stay in their boxes,'' he said
in a radio interview. ``Why sell them in that case?''
   Waldegrave said Gerasimov's argument that the planes were
defensive was `` slightly frivolous.'' He also rejected comparisons
to the British arms sale to Saudi Arabia.
   ``If you want to say the Saudi regime, in its behavior
internationally, is comparable to the Libyan regime in its behavior
internationally ... I think he is pulling our leg a little,''
Waldegrave said.
   But Waldegrave said the deal ``won't sour the talks, in the
sense that the whole of this relationship we now have with the
Soviet Union is one where we can build trust.''
   Gerasimov told the news conference he suspected the report was
leaked ``just to ruin the atmosphere'' of the Gorbachev-Thatcher
summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0942EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d e BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0417 04-07 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0417,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Forbidden City' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of playwright in lead and last graf. No PMs
planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early in ``The Forbidden City,'' the late
playwright Bill Gunn draws a realistic picture of a troubled black
family in 1936 Philadelphia. But the play runs into trouble as he
turns from realism to the bizarre.
   The acting in the play, which opened Thursday at the
off-Broadway Public Theater's LuEsther Hall, is exemplary. Joseph
Papp directed, and Loren Sherman created an elaborate, solid,
two-story interior, possibly too upscale for 1936.
   Gloria Foster plays the most fully drawn character, Molly
Hoffenburg. She's a rather elegant matron, who dusts her carefully
displayed figurines, dresses tastefully, and is generous with food
to men put out of work by the Depression.
   She's disappointed with her 16-year-old son, who wets the bed
and is considered a learning problem at school, and she gets
hysterical when he mentions his older brother, who died young in
the South after no doctor would see him.
   Eventually, Molly is revealed to have dreamed of becoming a
movie star and to have wanted her father to kill a white man for
her because she can't realize her dream. With those feelings
unfaded, she finally lets herself be picked up by a rich white man,
hoping he'll take her to expensive places. He takes her to a cheap
hotel.
   Frankie R. Faison plays her adoring husband. Even after he finds
out about her assignation, he sympathizes with her shame. He runs a
garage and also works another job, to provide for his family.
Everything he dreamed of, he says, he has.
   The son, Nick, seems almost retarded but can recite poetry and
has won a prize for creative writing. His dead brother appears to
him from time to time, played by Dimitri Corbin.
   Instead of this being chilling, it's puzzling. Is he meant as a
figment of Nick's imagination or a supernatural being?
   Nick provokes the violent end of the play by saying his brother
enters his body and tells him to kill a white person and put the
blood in his mother's brandy as reparation for her loss. The play's
tone turns decidely odd.
   The farther the playwright travels from reality, the less his
writing can handle it and the less the audience understands either
the story or the intended message.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0722EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan-China 1stLd-Writehtru   04-07 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China, 1st Ld-Writehtru,a0514,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>China, Taiwan Sign Accord For Taiwanese Athletes To Compete In China</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to ADD Taiwanese government delegation also
scheduled to visit China. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan and China have signed an agreement
that will allow Taiwanese athletes to compete in mainland China for
the first time in four decades, officials said today.
   The announcement came one day after Taiwan agreed to send an
official delegation to China for the first time. The 12-member
Taiwanese government delegation, led by Finance Minister Shirley
Kuo, will attend the annual meeting of the Asian Development Bank
in Beijing next month.
   The decisions were regarded as steps in a Nationalist inititive
to counter Communist China's efforts to isolate Taiwan
internationally.
   The agreement for the athletes' visit was signed Thursday in
Hong Kong after two months of negotiations, Chang Feng-hsu,
chairman of the Taiwan Olympic Committee, told a news conference.
   Officials said the agreement would permit Taiwan to send a team
to the Asian Junior Gymnastics championship, which begins in
Beijing on April 21.
   Taiwan also plans to compete in next year's Asian Games in
Beijing, and 10 other international sports competitions in China
later this year, officials said.
   Ho Zhen-liang, deputy chairman of China's Olympic Committee,
signed the agreement for China.
   Chang said the Chinese also withdrew an earlier demand for
Chinese teams to compete in sports meets in Taiwan.
   ``They understood that it would take some time before we could
agree to their visits here,'' Chang said.
   In Beijing, the Chinese Olympic Committee Vice President He
Zhenliang said, ``This is a major development in the sports
exchanges between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits. It will give
a great impetus to the promotion of brotherhood and mutual
understanding.''
   The decision to send the government delegation did not signal a
change in government policies toward China, said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Chen Yu-chu. He said Taiwan would continue to oppose
official contacts with the rival Communists, who won a civil war in
1949.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan, claim they are the sole
legitimate government of all China.
   Chang Chung-tung, history professor at the National Taiwan
University, described the government's decision as ``a major
breakthrough'' and said it was probably intended to pressure the
Chinese Communists to accept de facto Nationalist rule over this
island.
   In 1987, the Nationalists adopted a more flexible policy on
private contacts with the Chinese communists, but the government
continues to refuse to deal directly with the Beijing government.
   The new policy has led to an exchange of visits, trade and
cultural ties between Taiwanese and Chinese.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0848EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HazardousMaterials     04-07 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hazardous Materials,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release at 9 a.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Propose Stricter Regulation of Hazardous Materials Shipments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers from Missouri and Kansas proposed
legislation today to tighten regulation of interstate shipments of
hazardous materials, including radioactive wastes.
   Citizens ``have a right to expect that hazardous materials will
be transported through their state as safely as possible,'' said
Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., one of the measure's sponsors.
   In remarks prepared for delivery when the legislation is
introduced today in the Senate, Danforth said it was partly
prompted by concerns over the shipment of spent nuclear fuel by
railroad through the Midwest from the damaged Three Mile Island
nuclear plant in Pennsylvania to a federal laboratory in Idaho.
   Also sponsoring the measure were Sens. Christopher Bond, R-Mo.,
and Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.
   Bond said the bill would plug ``dangerous loopholes'' in current
regulations.
   The legislation would require:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Rail shipments of high-level radioactive materials to move only
by ``dedicated trains,'' which means their sole purpose is to carry
the nuclear materials. Currently, shippers can transport such
materials on ``mixed'' trains carrying other freight. The TMI
materials are moved by single-purpose trains but that is not
required by law.
   ``We cannot take the risk of mixing hazardous materials such as
the Three Mile Island wastes with cars full of everything from
grain to dangerous chemicals,'' Bond said.
   _The Transportation Department to establish standards to guide
shippers in selecting routes for transporting high-level
radioactive wastes or spent nuclear fuel. Danforth said ``decisions
on modes and routes for nuclear shipments now are made at the whim
of the shipper, who often is more concerned about cost-cutting than
safety.''
   _The Nuclear Regulatory Commission to certify the safety of all
shipping packages for transporting nuclear materials. Currently the
Energy Department approves the containers used for its shipments,
such as the TMI materials, while the NRC standards apply to other
packages.
   _Trucking companies carrying hazardous materials to obtain a
permit from the Transportation Department. The permit requirement
would apply to motor carriers carrying radioactive materials, some
explosives and those materials ``extremely toxic by inhalation.''
   The legislation also would prohibit a motor carrier from
carrying hazardous materials if DOT auditors gave it a
``unsatisfactory'' rating for having too many safety violations.
The ratings are assigned now under the agency's safety auditing
system and Danforth said about 1,110 hazardous materials carriers
have unsatisfactory safety ratings.
   _All hazardous materials warning labels and placards to remain
on shipping packages or vehicles until the materials have been
removed. The provision is to prevent accidents such as one that
killed six Kansas City firefighters last year at a construction
site.
   There was no warning placard on a trailer containing tons of
blasting agent and it exploded after catching on fire. Firefighters
have said they were unaware of the hazardous materials.
   The bill also calls for the government to provide for 20
Transportation Department inspectors for shipments of radioactive
materials, and require that all high-level radioactive shipments be
inspected at their starting point.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0849EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TrainsDerail     04-07 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trains Derail,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nearly 100 People Slightly Injured in 3 Separate Train Accidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 100 people suffered minor injuries and some 1,000
children had to be evacuated in three separate train accidents, but
an official in one case said ``it was a miracle no one was killed.''
   A truck driver ignored crossing signals and drove around
railroad gates, driving his semitrailer into the path of a commuter
train and causing a collision that injured at least 68 people, said
Will County Sheriff John Johnsen in Lemont, Ill.
   An Amtrak passenger train that derailed near the Virginia-North
Carolina border injured 28 people.
   And in Princeton, Ind., liquid nitrogen and herbicides that
spilled from storage containers prompted the evacuation of children
from two nearby schools. One injury was reported.
   State's Attorney Edward Burmila said a decision would be made
today on whether to charge truck driver James R. Krueger with the
Illinois accident.
   The gate was down and red warning signals were flashing when the
collision occurred Thursday, Johnsen said.
   Most of the injuries appeared to be minor, officials said. The
rush-hour commuter train carrying 98 people had picked up
passengers in Joliet and Lockport and was en route to Chicago.
   ``It was a miracle no one was killed,'' Johnsen said.
   The engineer, James Mullin, saw the truck going around the
crossing and knew it would be impossible to avoid impact, and
immediately slammed on the brakes, said Chris Knapton, a spokesman
for the commuter rail line in Chicago.
   The engineer ``wheeled around, opened the door, plunged into the
walkway and held on for dear life. If he had not done that, he
would be dead,'' Knapton said.
   All four passenger cars derailed and the engine was knocked
nearly on its side.
   Six cars and both engines of Amtrak's Silver Star derailed near
Skippers, a Greensville County town six miles south of Emporia, Va.
The train, with 519 passengers aboard, was traveling from Tampa and
Miami in Florida to New York.
   Lt. D.W. Robertson of the Virginia State Police said the train
had two engines and 18 cars. He said the cause of the derailment,
which occurred on CSX Corp. tracks, has not been determined.
   In Indiana, a CSX train slipped off a railway spur and caused a
chain reaction that toppled the storage tank at a fertilizer
company, authorities said.
   Police dispatcher Tom Perry said the chemicals involved were not
volatile and gave off no fumes.
   ``When they finally evaluated the chemicals that were on the
ground, there was very little of anything other than liquid
nitrogen,'' he said. ``There was nothing that was harmful other
than to the touch.''
