<FIRST>r w PM-Alimony     04-07 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alimony,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alimony Rates Higher for White, College Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The likelihood of alimony being awarded
divorced or separated women is twice as high if they are aged 40 or
over than it is if they are under 30, a new Census Bureau study
shows.
   The study also showed that alimony was twice as likely for white
women than for blacks.
   And college graduates are significantly more likely to win
alimony than women who failed to finish high school, said the study
released Thursday.
   ``They know how to use the system, it's as simple as that,''
said Census statistician Mary Henson of the higher alimony rates
for white and more educated women.
   According to the study, alimony was awarded to 15.8 percent of
white women whose marriages had broken up, compared to only 8.0
percent of blacks. The alimony rate for Hispanic women, who can be
of any race, was 11.0 percent.
   The report, ``Child Support and Alimony, 1985,'' also repeated
figures, detailed by the Census Bureau last August, showing a
significant decline in child support payments received by women
between 1983 and 1985.
   The new version adds details on alimony and property settlements
when couples are divorced or separated.
   In addition to alimony, white women were more likely than blacks
to receive property settlements, and the share receiving a cash
settlement was higher for college-educated women.
   As to the greater likelihood of women over age 40 receiving
alimony, Ms. Henson commented that court awards were more common in
past years, while more younger women either receive voluntary
payments from former spouses or do not seek support payments.
Studies have shown that alimony awards were more common prior to
the mid-1970s than they have been since then.
   The new analysis showed a drop in average alimony payments from
$4,293 in 1983 to $3,733 in 1985. That paralleled the decline,
reported last August, in child support payments, which fell from
$2,528 in 1983 to $2,215 in 1985.
   In addition to the racial and ethnic differences found in the
1985 alimony payments, the study found the highest rate amomng
women with four years of college or more _ 17.7 percent receiving
alimony.
   Next were high school graduates at 15.3 percent, nearly the same
as the 15.2 percent for women who had attended but not finished
college. Only 11.8 percent of women who failed to complete high
school had been awarded alimony.
   By age, 18.5 percent of divorced or separated women aged 40 and
over had been awarded alimony payments, compared to 10.9 percent in
the 30-to-39 age group and only 7.7 percent aged 18 to 29.
   The overall alimony rate was 17.1 percent for divorced women,
13.8 percent for remarried women whose previous marriage had ended
in divorce and 10.0 percent for women who were separated.
   The report noted that 20.7 percent of women who had not been
employed for five years before their separation were awarded
alimony, while the rate fell to 11.8 percent for women who held
full-time jobs when their marriage ended.
   Property settlements were much more common than alimony awards,
the study found.
   For example, 74.2 percent of women had won a settlement
involving the house, car or other property, and 21.6 percent
received a cash settlement.
   Racially, 75.2 percent of white women and 66.0 percent among
blacks had settlemets involving goods such as real estate,
furniture or cars. Hispanic women led in this category, however, at
76.1 percent.
   Turning to cash settlements, white women had a 22.1 percent
rate, compared to 19.0 percent among Hispanics and 14.6 percent for
black women.
   Rates of non-cash settlements were very close among age groups _
74.8 percent for those 30 to 39, 74.0 percent over age 40 and 73.4
percent under age 30. The cash settlement rates were 24.7 percent
for the youngest group, 23.2 percent between 30 and 39 and 20.4
percent over age 40.
   By education, the non-cash settlement rate was highest for women
with the least schooling. Those who had not finished high school
won a non-cash property settlement in 76.1 percent of separations.
But they were least likely to get cash, 18.6 percent.
   For high school graduates, 74.7 percent received non-cash
settments and 20.8 percent got money.
   The non-cash rate was 73.9 percent for women who had attended
college, while 22.1 percent of them obtained cash. Of women with
degrees, 70.4 percent got a non-cash settlement and 27.4 prcent got
cash.
</TEXT>
