<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-07 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEAT RIDGE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine-year-old Bobby Rupp was playing
with some friends on the school playground when he caught a falling
star.
   The find substantiates numerous reports Monday of a rare daytime
meteorite spotted from Denver to Salida in south-central Colorado
to Garden City and Salinas in Kansas.
   Just after noon Monday Bobby and some friends at the Prospect
Valley Elementary School in Wheat Ridge caught a glimpse of a
meteor above them.
   ``It was red, blue, yellow, orange. ... And it was on fire,''
Bobby said. ``I was by the fence and looked up ... and I saw a
black piece coming down toward the school.''
   Bobby ran about 50 feet to the corner of the playground where he
thought the object landed. He found a small lavalike rock that was
``hotter than heck.''
   After school, Bobby called his mother, Ingrid Rupp, who said she
doubted her son at first. But on Wednesday, a Colorado School of
Mines geology professor confirmed that the rock was a meteorite.
   ``This little fella saw something very rare,'' said Professor
Robert M. Hutchinson.
   ``There are just a handful of cases (like this) throughout
history,'' said Larry Sessions, an astronomer at the Denver Museum
of Natural History.
   Hutchinson said he believes the rock was a ``stony type''
meteorite that may have come from an asteroid. He has taken a
sample of it to his lab for closer examination.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To help celebrate Washington state's
centennial this year, a company has introduced a pasta in the shape
of the state and its evergreen trees.
   One of the owners of Aunt Patsy's Pantry, Jill Smith, says until
now there have been few centennial food products.
   The first package of the Centennial Celebration Macaroni _ a mix
of spinach and plain varieties _ went to Gov. Booth Gardner.
   Starting this week the centennial macaroni will be sold at
specialty food outlets and some grocery stores. Can salmon salsa
and walla walla relish be far behind?
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sooner or later almost every motorist tries to
talk his or her way out of a traffic ticket, and Colorado's Gov.
Roy Romer is no exception.
   Romer's car was in the shop Thursday, and he needed to get out
on the Oatmeal Circuit _ early morning campaigning at restaurants
to promote the proposed new airport in next month's special city
election. So he borrowed a car from his son, Mark, who was in
Virginia on business.
   He was on his to his next meeting after the breakfast
appearances when a Denver police officer noticed the license tags
on the car had expired in March and pulled the governor over.
   Romer explained to the unidentified officer that he had no idea
that the tags had expired, press spokeswoman Cindy Parameter said
later.
   The governor used his portable phone to make inquiries and
established that renewal stickers had been delivered although his
son hadn't been home to put them on the car.
   That much established, the officer let the governor go, with a
warning.
   ``It proves I'm human,'' Romer said.
</TEXT>
