<FIRST>r a PM-Visitor-AIDS     04-07 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Visitor-AIDS,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>INS Recommends Freeing Dutch Visitor With AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch traveler with AIDS will remain in
jail, despite a recommendation by regional federal immigration
officials that he be allowed to attend an AIDS conference in San
Francisco.
   Hans Paul Verhoef won't be released until the recommendation is
certified by immigration officials in Washington, said Tom
Schiltgen, district director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
   Verhoef was taken into custody Sunday at the Minneapolis-St.
Paul International Airport by Customs officials who discovered the
AIDS drug AZT in his baggage and then questioned him about the
disease. Verhoef, an AIDS prevention worker, told authorities he
had AIDS and was en route to the conference.
   Schiltgen said Thursday a decision on certifying the waiver
would be made prior to a hearing scheduled for today. INS spokesman
Greg Leo in Washington confirmed that the recommendation had been
received and would be reviewed.
   ``The INS has established that Mr. Verhoef is an excludable as a
person who is afflicted with a dangerous communicable disease,''
Schiltgen said.
   Schiltgen said earlier that to grant a waiver, the INS must
verify that Verhoef's disease does not pose a health threat and
that the U.S. government would not incur expenses for Verhoef's
care.
   Verhoef, 31, said in an interview from prison that he still
hopes to attend the final days of the National Lesbian and Gay
Health Conference in San Francisco, which ends Sunday.
   But he said his detention may have had some positive benefits.
   ``This morning a woman said to me that I did more things for the
cause being here than being in San Francisco,'' Verhoef said. ``And
I think that's true, because the U.S. government is forced to
revise their policy on having people with AIDS in the country or
not.''
   Jonathan Burris, Verhoef's Minneapolis attorney, said the case
will set ``a national precedent relative to whether or not people
with AIDS will be admitted into the country freely and in what
fashion.''
   Verhoef's incarceration touched off a wave of criticism of
immigration policies and protests in the Twin Cities, San Francisco
and elsewhere.
   San Francisco Mayor Art Agnos declared Thursday ``Hans Verhoef
Day.''
   ``As this room is full today, there is still someone missing,''
Agnos told attendees at the conference. ``He is Hans Paul Verhoef,
an official representative of the City of Delft, Holland.''
</TEXT>
