<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Dissident     04-07 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Dissident,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissidents Appeal to Thatcher on `Political' Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev-Britain, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Soviet political activists today gave the
British Embassy a letter asking Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher to
protest the trial of a political dissident.
   A British diplomat said the letter would be forwarded to London
today but it would arrive too late for Mrs. Thatcher to discuss the
case with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who was ending his visit
to London.
   The letter says the trial of Sergei Kuznetsov in the Ural
Mountains city of Sverdlovsk was called for political reasons
although ``authorities are trying to present it as the usual
criminal trial.''
   Kuznetsov, 35, the Sverdlovsk correspondent for the Moscow-based
underground journal Glasnost, was arrested Dec. 10 while protesting
the detention of political prisoners, said one of the activists,
Tamara Grigoryants.
   Kuznetsov was sentenced to 15 days in jail for administrative
law violations, Mrs. Grigoryants said.
   He was beaten by police in prison, but authorities called the
charges false and accused him of slandering the regional party
chief, the KGB chief and head of a regional police office, Mrs.
Grigoryants said.
   Kuznetsov was put on trial Monday and faces a minimum three-year
jail sentence if convicted, said the woman, the wife of Moscow
dissident Sergei Grigoryants, the editor of Glasnost magazine.
   Kuznetsov began a hunger strike Feb. 22, drinking only water,
but authorities are threatening his ``direct physical
destruction,'' the letter said.
   Another of the political activists, Andrei Mironov, said the
trial was one of the first under Gorbachev of a dissident, and
marked a ``continuation of old political repressions'' and a
``turning point in perestroika,'' the Soviet leader's reform
process.
   Tony Longrigg, the political counselor who met with the group,
said Britain knew about the case. ``Our government takes a strong
line on human rights, and it was reiterated during Mr. Gorbachev's
visit,'' Longrigg said.
   Along with Mrs. Grigoryants and Mironov, the dissident
delegation included Valery Senderov, Kirill Popov and Asya Lashiver.
</TEXT>
