<DOCNO> AP890407-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0944EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Hayes     04-07 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Hayes,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Esquire Editor Who Helped Found `New Journalism' Dead at 62</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Hayes, the author and editor who
helped make Esquire magazine the clarion of ``The New Journalism''
in the 1960s with writers like Norman Mailer and James Baldwin, has
died. He was 62.
   Hayes, who suffered a brain tumor, died Wednesday at
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, said Paula Correia, a hospital
spokesman.
   As editor of Esquire from 1963 to 1973, Hayes helped many
notable writers establish themselves, including Gay Talese, Tom
Wolfe and Michael Herr.
   He and then-managing editor Clay Felker laid the foundation for
what would become known as ``The New Journalism'' by asking such
literary titans as Mailer, Baldwin and William Styron to report and
write on contemporary social and political events.
   ``Esquire magazine was saved in the 1960s by its constituency of
writers,'' Hayes wrote in 1979. ``In our best moments those of us
who worked there clung to the faith that a writer's conciousness,
in whatever direction it is beamed, is the only thing truly
interesting about a magazine.''
   Hayes wrote a book in 1977 called ``The Last Place on Earth,''
which described the ecology of East Africa and the Serengeti Plain.
At his death he was working on a biography of gorilla researcher
Dian Fossey, whose life was portrayed in the movie ``Gorillas in
the Mist,'' said Tom Christie, who was helping Hayes with his
research.
   In addition to his wife, Judy Kessler, Hayes was survived by two
children from a previous marriage, a granddaughter; his brother,
James M. Hayes Jr. of Winston-Salem, and sister, Phyllis Johnson of
Rock Hill, S.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
