<FIRST>r i PM-Gulf-Ship     04-07 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf-Ship,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freighter Sinks, 20 Crew Feared Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers today searched for 20 sailors
missing and believed drowned when their Maltese-flagged freighter
sank in the Persian Gulf, maritime officials said.
   One body floated to the surface today near where the freighter
Rahim III sank off the United Arab Emirates. The body was airlifted
to Abu Dhabi and not immediately identified.
   The ship's agent, Fathi Khalil, told the Qatar News Agency that
all crew members were believed drowned.
   In addition to the Indian captain, the crew of the 2,958-ton
vessel included seven Indians, four Burmese and eight Filipinos.
   Col. Abdallah Mullah, head of the United Arab Emirates coast
guard, said he ordered divers to search for bodies when the sunken
ship was found Wednesday 60 miles from Abu Dhabi. Rough weather has
hampered the search, he said.
   Shipping excutives said the vessel, owned by the Hong Kong-based
United Ship Management Co. and carrying a load of scrap metal from
Qatar to Bombay, India, might have run into a storm or hit a
floating mine. It was reported missing Saturday.
   During the eight-year Iran-Iraq war at least 540 neutral
commercial ships were damaged in attacks or by mines. Shipping
officials fear as many as 200 mines remain in gulf waters.
</TEXT>
