<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0952EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FamilyShooting     04-07 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Shooting,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Shot Family, Believing They'd Forgot Father's Day, Goes Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EATON RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly man who mistakenly
believed he'd been forgotten on Father's Day and shot six
relatives, killing two of them, now lives in an adult care home
with no restrictions on his movements.
   Melville Henwood, 81, killed his daughter and son-in-law,
Elizabeth and John Flory, and wounded his wife and three of his
grandchildren on June 8, 1986. He apparently didn't realize
Father's Day was a week away.
   Henwood was found innocent by reason of insanity in the
shootings on Oct. 26, 1987, and placed in a psychiatric hospital.
   However, he went free in February after administrators at a
second hospital to which he had been transferred allowed him to
sign a voluntary commitment order, ending what had been stringent
court control of his case. The administrators said they concluded
that he was well enough to handle a less-restrictive setting.
   ``It's one of those things that went wrong. He's as free as you
are. We don't have any control over him,'' said Dr. Lynn Blunt,
clinical director of the Michigan Center for Forensic Psychiatry in
Ypsilanti.
   Henwood shot his relatives after they had gathered for Sunday
dinner in the Florys' home, where his ailing wife, Edna, was
living. In a tape recording made the night before the shootings,
Henwood complained about being lonely and forgotten on Father's Day.
   Mrs. Henwood was critically wounded but recovered, as did his
grandchildren, Michael Flory, then 9; Christine Flory, then 12; and
Gayle Scott, then 15. Two other grandchildren, Christopher Scott
and Audra Scott, weren't at home. The Scotts are Mrs. Flory's
children by a previous marriage.
   The children still live in the house where their parents were
shot. Christopher Scott said none of them would discuss their
grandfather's release.
   Eaton County Prosecutor G. Michael Hocking started asking
questions when a sheriff's deputy gave a ride home to an old man he
met March 24 in an Eaton Rapids market. The man introduced himself
as Mel Henwood.
   ``It's kind of scary. It's especially scary when you think that
Father's Day is getting closer,'' Hocking said.
   Under Michigan law, people who sign voluntary commitment papers
void their court-ordered treatment. That's what Henwood did, Blunt
said, adding, ``We were very surprised when they allowed him to
sign the voluntary order.''
   However, Tom DeLoach, a spokesman for the state Department of
Mental Health, said Ypsilanti Regional Psychiatric Hospital
staffers determined that Henwood was ready to go into a community
program. He's still getting outpatient mental health care, DeLoach
said.
   Given the verdict, Henwood's mental health treatment must be
viewed as entirely separate from his criminal trial, DeLoach said.
   An employee at the facility where Henwood is staying refused to
let him be interviewed, saying it would upset him.
   Hocking can't prosecute Henwood on the same 12 felony charges
that stemmed from the shootings but is looking into his release. If
there's no legal recourse, he said, he wants the law changed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0957EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0524 04-07 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Parliament Legalizes Solidarity, Approves Constitutional Changes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Parliament lifting ban, approving reforms.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today lifted the seven-year ban
on the Solidarity trade movement and enacted constitutional changes
to give Poland the first freely elected legislative body in the
East bloc.
   The Sejm, or parliament, passed a package of six bills that
enact into law a historic agreement on political, economic and
trade union reforms reached Wednesday between the Solidarity-led
opposition and communist authorities.
   Polish leader Wojciech Jaruzelski, who suppressed the Soviet
bloc's only independent labor movement when he imposed martial law
in December 1981, looked on as the votes were taken.
   In a surprise move, independent Deputy Ryszard Bender proposed
that the Sejm restore the state's official name to ``The Republic
of Poland'' instead of ``The Polish People's Republic'' adopted
when communists took over after World War II. ``If we don't pass
this change today, the next Sejm ... will,'' said Bender, saying
the present name had been ``imposed'' during the Stalinist era.
   After a recess in which he consulted with parliament leaders,
Bender agreed to withdraw his motion and let it be referred to a
special commission to consider further changes in the constitution.
   Then the Sejm passed the constitutional changes 384 to 4, with
17 abstentions, and the new law on trade unions 339 to 4 with 43
abstentions.
   Also passed in short order was the new law on elections to the
Sejm, by 371-3 with 15 absentions; elections to a new Senate, by
358-7 with 25 abstentions; on the right to form associations,
304-14 with 71 abstentions; and on legalizing farmers' unions,
enabling the existence of Rural Solidarity, 326-8 with 53
abstentions.
   The accord signed by the Solidarity-led opposition and the
government resulted from two months of intense talks.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Thursday called the agreement a
``political victory'' but warned it could be disastrous if Poles do
not quickly use it to improve the economy and elect effective
representatives.
   The approval came with the blessing of Gen. Jaruzelski, who
threatened to resign as party leader in January if the party did
not restore the union.
   The general argued that legalization will culminate his policy
of national reconciliation and open the way to a united effort to
combat Poland's pressing economic and social problems.
   The new laws also provide for elections in June that will be the
freest ever held in the communist country.
   The 460 Sejm seats will be divided into two groups, with the
Communist Party and its allies guaranteed 65 percent. The remainder
go to independent candidates.
   Also, a democratically elected Senate with 100 members will be
created. For the first time, communist candidates will face direct
electoral competition from anti-communists.
   Anyone who collects 3,000 signatures can run for one of two
seats from each of the 49 provinces, with one extra seat apiece for
Warsaw and Katowice cities.
   The Senate will be able to veto legislation of the Sejm, and the
Sejm must muster a two-third majority to override the veto.
   Senate and Sejm together will form a National Assembly that will
select a president with executive and veto powers who can dissolve
parliament during a constitutional crisis. The new post seems to
have been designed for Jaruzelski as a guarantee that Poland will
stay in the Communist bloc.
   Walesa said he expected Solidarity to attract 5 million to 7
million members, but would like at least three competing unions.
   Authorities proposed talks with the opposition in August during
the year's second nationwide wave of strikes.
   Both sides hope the agreement will help repair an economy
debilitated by a $39 billion foreign debt and revive the dispirited
population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0958EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-Dissident 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Dissident, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0538,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Leaves China After Being Held By Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs with background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese dissident arrived in Hong Kong today
after being held by police for nearly two days, and his wife said
he had in effect been expelled from the country.
   ``They said it was voluntary but it amounted to (expulsion),''
Jenny Holdaway, a British citizen, said in Beijing. She said her
husband, Chen Jun, had no Hong Kong visa and was being held in
transit at the Hong Kong airport.
   A Hong Kong government spokesman said Chen arrived in Hong Kong
today on his way to the United States.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified further under official
practice, declined to give any more information on Chen, saying it
was not government policy to comment on the movement of passengers.
   Ms. Holdaway said Chen was taken into police custody on
Wednesday when he arrived in Shanghai on a visit from Beijing. He
was allowed to call her this morning to say he was flying to Hong
Kong.
   ``I asked what the reason was, and he said he'd tell me later,''
she said. ``He said he was in the police station.''
   She said Chen, who holds a U.S. residency permit, had planned to
leave for the United States in several weeks. But she said he would
not have chosen freely to leave so abruptly.
   An official at the Shanghai Foreign Affairs Office, who
identified himself only as Mr. Fu, said Chen left voluntarily.
   But, he added, ``If (Chen) wants to come back to China it will
have to be approved by the relevant departments.'' Fu said he did
not know if Chen would be allowed back.
   Chen, 31, part owner of a Beijing bar, was one of the organizers
of a petition circulated in Beijing that called for an amnesty for
political prisoners.
   The petition, sent in February to the legislature and the ruling
Communist Party, was signed by 33 intellectuals, including some of
China's most famous writers and thinkers.
   The petition inspired more than 100 other intellectuals in China
and thousands of ethnic Chinese in Hong Kong, Taiwan and the United
States to sign similar appeals. Seven Hong Kong intellectuals
brought one petition with 24,000 signatures into the country in
March but it was seized by customs officials.
   Authorities have said China has no political prisoners and that
there is no need for any amnesty. They also have denounced the
petitions as efforts to arouse foreign public opinion to bring
pressure on China.
   Chen also helped publish a pro-democracy magazine in Shanghai in
1978. While in the United States from 1984 to 1987, he contributed
articles to the New York-based magazine China Spring while studying
in the United States.
   The Chinese government considers China Spring reactionary and
has jailed several other people connected with it.
   Fu said he did not know if Chen's sudden departure was related
to his political activism. Asked if Chen had commited political
offenses, Fu said, ``You should ask him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
