<FIRST>u w PM-Wright-Contras     04-07 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Contras,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Says Revelations About Bush Role Should Not Damage Bipartisanship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Revelations about President Bush's role in
covert support for the Nicaraguan Contras should not be allowed to
damage evolving bipartisan cooperation on foreign policy between
Congress and the White House, House Speaker Jim Wright said today.
   ``We're not going to permit anything that happened in the past
to interfere with what happens in the future,'' Wright, D-Texas,
told reporters following a speech in which he extolled
bipartisanship in U.S. policy toward Central America.
   ``That does not imply approval, or sanction'' of Bush's role as
a go-between in supplying the Nicaraguan rebels, disclosed in a
document released Thursday at Oliver North's Iran-Contra trial,
Wright said.
   But he added: ``I don't think it's productive ... to allow
anything to prevent our going forward and building a basis for a
truly bipartisan approach in the future.
   ``I am determined that I'm going to proceed on the basis of
trust in what President Bush and Secretary (of State James) Baker
say to me. It's a new day, and we've turned a new leaf, written a
new chapter. We mustn't allow it to be poisoned by what we read in
the last chapter.''
   In his speech to a Democratic policy group, the Center for
National Policy, Wright described the bipartisan accord on policy
toward Nicaragua announced at the White House two weeks ago, and
said legislation extending ``humanitarian'' aid to the rebels would
be passed by the House before the end of the month.
   The new aid package, totaling $58 million, includes $49 million
to maintain the current flow of food, medicine and clothing to the
rebels through February 1990, when national elections are scheduled
in Nicaragua. Details of the measure were still being worked out,
but it was scheduled to be introduced next week.
   Some snags remained to be worked out, as well, in the language
of a proposed letter from Baker to congressional leaders giving
four key committees on Capitol Hill the right to shut off the aid
after November if it is not being administered according to what
Wright called ``a gentlemen's agreement'' between Baker and
Congress.
   In his speech describing the aid package, Wright emphasized that
some of the money can be used to repatriate or relocate the roughly
11,000 rebels from their Honduran jungle camps along the Nicaraguan
border, and that no money would flow to any group which undertakes
offensive military action or human rights violations.
   And the speaker hailed the Bush administration's efforts to
develop ``mutual understanding and mutual trust,'' contrasting it
with President Reagan's tenure.
   ``We have confidence that in the Bush administration there will
be no covert mining of harbors, no publishing of assassination
manuals and no lying to Congress,'' Wright said.
   Reagan's approach o Nicaragua, including covert aid to the
rebels, ``so poisoned the well of public discourse that it made an
enormous emotional impact both at home and throughout the world,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
