<FIRST>r a PM-BlackMayors     04-07 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Mayors,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Mayors Back Drug Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two dozen black mayors gathered for a
national convention urged random drug testing of public workers and
officials, including themselves.
   One of the 24 mayors, Callie Mobley of Allerton, Ill., said at a
news conference Thursday that she was tested last year along with
her city's 16 employees.
   ``We must step out front by taking drug tests ourselves to let
our constituents know that we're really against drugs,'' Mobley
said.
   She said Allerton, a city of 3,000, has a new policy calling for
drug testing. All the test results were negative, she said.
   There are 306 black mayors in the nation; 200 are attending the
meeting of the National Conference of Black Mayors.
   Atlantic City Mayor James Usry, president of the conference,
said all city officials should be required to take drug tests on a
random basis.
   ``We need to stop sending the message to young people that
because you're poor it's all right to sell drugs,'' said
Philadelphia Mayor W. Wilson Goode. ``That's nonsense.''
   Also Thursday, a panel of health care experts said black mayors
and church leaders should do more about fighting AIDS in the black
community by pushing for more education, treatment and research
money.
   ``I don't know where we'll bury all of them,'' Dr. Beny Primm, a
New York City addiction specialist who served on the federal AIDS
commission, said of AIDS victims.
   ``I don't think we as ... African-Americans have done very much
to turn this thing around in our communities,'' Primm said. ``We do
not have a blitzkrieg of information, a bombardment of our
community with information.''
</TEXT>
