<FIRST>r i PM-Gorbachev-Painting     04-07 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev-Painting,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sotheby's Presents Mrs. Gorbachev With Missing Portrait of Czar</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev-Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raisa Gorbachev argued with Sotheby's chairman
today about who really painted a portrait of the Russian Czar Peter
III which was presented it to her as a gift to the Soviet Union.
   But it was a friendly disagreement between the wife of the
visiting Soviet president and Lord Gowrie, chairman of the fine art
auction house over whether the long-missing 18th century painting
was by the court artist Alexander Rokotov. ``It really doesn't
belong to Rokotov himself, it's from the school of him,'' Mrs.
Gorbachev said during the presentation at the Soviet embassy.
   Gowrie said Sotheby's had been assured by a Soviet museum the
painting was by Rokotov. Mrs. Gorbachev replied: ``Sometimes it's
difficult for experts to establish firmly.''
   But she said she was delighted anyway at receiving the picture,
the only painting of the czar that the Russians do not have.
   ``Thank you Lord Gowrie for the presentation, that is from the
bottom of our hearts. We take it as a sign of respect for our
country, our nation and our national culture,'' said Mrs. Gorbachev.
   The czar, born in 1728, was the father of Catherine the Great.
He was assassinated in 1762 by two of his imperial officers.
   The portrait, which Sotheby's experts said showed the czar at
the age of 19, was missing for nearly 50 years. It surfaced in
London, and Sotheby's bought the picture for 7,000 pounds ($12,000)
in April.
   The original 1861 manuscript of the novel ``Fathers and Sons''
by Ivan Turgenev also was handed over to the Soviets today,
Sotheby's said.
   The Soviets bought it for roughly 500,000 pounds ($850,000)
through a private sale arranged by the auction house. The
unidentified British seller's wish had been that the manuscript
should return to its own country.
 
</TEXT>
