<FIRST>u a PM-ScarfoTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0561 04-07 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scarfo Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0561,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scarfo, 7 Other Defendants Get Life Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with formal sentencing completed.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `I just...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today sentenced mob boss Nicodemo
``Little Nicky'' Scarfo and seven associates to life in prison
instead of death for killing a fellow gangster.
   Judge Eugene Clarke took the sentencing decision away from the
jury Thursday after ruling that prosecutors failed to show there
were enough aggravating circumstances for a death sentence.
   The eight men, all convicted Wednesday in the July 1985 slaying
of Frank ``Frankie Flowers'' D'Alfonso, were formally sentenced
today. With death ruled out by the Thursday ruling, the only choice
available to the judge was to give the eight life in prison with no
chance of parole.
   Friends and relatives of the eight broke out in applause as the
judge announced his decision Thursday.
   Scarfo, 60, who is the head of organized crime in the
Philadelphia and southern New Jersey area, already is serving a
14-year sentence in a $1 million extortion case. He also faces at
least 40 more years for his conviction last November in a federal
racketeering case.
   While expressing relief that their clients were avoiding the
death penalty, defense lawyers said they would appeal the murder
convictions. Clarke set a hearing on post-trial motions, including
requests for a new trial, for July 26.
   ``I just feel like I've been pulled out the grave,'' said Robert
Simone, Scarfo's lawyer. ``There is not doubt in my mind that this
jury, a runaway jury, would have brought in the death penalty. They
were champing at the bit to put them in the electric chair.''
   But juror Arthur Trimble, 60, said the jury totally supported
Clarke's sentencing decision.
   ``We were so happy, as a group, that the judge took it out of
our hands,'' he said. ``We were not after the death penalty.''
   During the sentencing phase of the trial Thursday, police
firearms examiner John Finor testified that bystanders were
standing nearby when D'Alfonso was gunned down on a Philadelphia
street corner.
   But Clarke ruled the situation did not constitute an aggravating
circumstance necessary for the death penalty under Pennsylvania
law. He also decided not to allow prosecutors to bolster their case
for the death penalty by telling the jury about the November
racketeering convictions of Scarfo and five co-defendants.
   The jurors took only three hours Wednesday to convict Scarfo and
the others of first-degree murder, conspiracy and the possession of
an instrument of crime.
   Government witnesses said D'Alfonso was murdered because he
failed to show Scarfo proper respect.
   Besides Scarfo and Nicholas ``Nicky Whip'' Milano, 27, the
others convicted were Joseph Ligambi, 48, and Philip Narducci, 26,
identified as the shooters; Francis ``Faffy'' Iannarella, 32,
accused of supplying the two murder guns; Salvatore ``Chuckie''
Merlino, 47, and his brother, Lawrence ``Yogi'' Merlino, 32; and
Frank Narducci Jr., 31, Philip's brother.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
