<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--Cuba-WarningShots     04-07 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Cuba-Warning Shots,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cubans Fire Warning Shots At Florida Fishing Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban gunboat fired warning shots at a Florida
fishing boat and then seized the vessel early today at the edge of
international water off the northeastern tip of the island nation,
officials said.
   A Jacksonville marine company monitoring radio reported hearing
a mayday call from the 66-foot Don Pepo before it was boarded at
4:50 a.m., said Coast Guard Petty Officer Luis Diaz.
   The boat's crew said by radio that the Cubans had fired warning
shots when the Don Pepo was about 12 miles off the coast. No
injuries were reported.
   Crew members Mike Frye and Claude Pawell of St. Augustine said
they were headed from Tampa to Cartagena, Colombia, when the boat
was boarded and that they were ordered to follow the gunboat to the
Cuban port of Cayo Moa.
   The Coast Guard said it received no response from the Cuban
government about the incident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Baker     04-07 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Baker,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Announce Date for Baker Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said today that U.S. Secretary of
State James A. Baker III will visit Moscow on May 10-11.
   The official Tass news agency announced the dates of Baker's
first visit to Moscow as secretary of state in a one-sentence
statement.
   ``It has been officially announced here that under an agreement
that has been reached U.S. Secretary of State James Baker will pay
an official visit to Moscow on May 10-11, 1989,'' Tass said.
   That will be just days before President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
goes to China for the first Soviet-Chinese summit in 30 years.
   The Soviet Ambassador to Washington, Yuri Dubinin, announced in
early March that Baker would visit Moscow this spring. During a
meeting in Vienna five days later, Baker and Shevaradnadze said the
visit would take place in May but did not announce a date.
   Baker and Shevardnadze said in Vienna that one reason for the
trip would be to discuss a possible summit meeting between
Gorbachev and President Bush, but Baker said then the United States
was not prepared to set a date for a summit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
