<FIRST>u w PM-US-Gorbachev     04-07 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Gorbachev,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Takes Soviet Criticism In Stride</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today deflected complaints by
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev that the U.S. review of arms
control and foreign policy was delaying negotiations to slow the
nuclear arms race.
   ``We are making a prudent review,'' Bush said. ``... Mr.
Gorbachev knows there is no foot-dragging going on, and I`m not
concerned in the least.''
   Gorbachev, on a visit to Britain, said through a spokesman on
Thursday that ``continuity is the name of the game. We are a little
bit apprehensive we could be losing it.''
   Bush, with a flash of irritation in a session in the White House
press room, said he would be ready to discuss the arms situation
with the Soviets when the review is completed. That is expected at
the end of the month or, at the latest, in early May.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III will go to Moscow next
month to discuss the suspended negotiations with the Soviets and
also prospects for a first summit meeting between Bush and
Gorbachev.
   The negotiations to reduce long-range nuclear weapons went into
recess in December and were tentatively set to resume in
mid-February. But the Bush administration postponed the resumption
for the review, which includes an analysis of U.S. nuclear forces.
   On a related subject, Gorbachev promised today to make deep cuts
in the Soviet military and announced he would close two more
nuclear reactors that produce weapons-grade plutonium.
   Asked for his appraisal, Bush again deflected the question. ``We
will react when we are ready to react,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Bush called developments in Poland ``mind-boggling''
because of the pace of reform. ``I think it is a sign of the change
of democratization. ... This is all very encouraging.''
   He said he had not decided whether he should consider a visit to
the East European country.
</TEXT>
