<FIRST>u i PM-Iran     04-07 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riots Break Out In Iran After Khomeini Dismisses Montazeri As Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riots broke out in the hometown of Iran's
Ayatollah Hussein Ali Montazeri after his dismissal as designated
successor to Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the main Iranian
opposition group said today.
   The Baghdad-based Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's Holy Warriors,
said a number of people died in the clashes between civilians and
soldiers in Najafabad in central Isfahan province.
   In a statement sent to The Associated Press office in Nicosia,
the group said residents, chanting ``Down with Khomeini!'' had
taken arms from the soldiers and returned their fire. The group
said the clashes started Sunday and continued through Wednesday.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said today that
Montazeri wrote to the city's residents asking them ``to thwart any
action against the Islamic Republic that might be taken in his
name.'' But IRNA, which was monitored in Nicosia, did not say a
riot had occurred in Najafabad.
   Montazeri, who in recent weeks openly criticized the
shortcomings of the 10-year-old Islamic revolution and called for
greater freedom, stepped down March 28 after Khomeini wrote him a
letter telling him to quit.
   Khomeini's decision to dump the 64-year-old cleric was seen as
part of a crackdown on more moderate members of the senior Iranian
leadership.
   The Mujahedeen Khalq report, telexed to The Associated Press in
Nicosia, said Najafabad was under curfew and authorities had set up
traffic checkpoints. It reported numerous arrests in the
disturbances in Najafabad and other central Iranian cities of
Yazdanshahr, Amirabad and Imam.
   IRNA reported Montazeri's letter in a dispatch from Tehran in
which Iran's chief justice, Ayatollah Musavi Ardebili, denied that
Montazeri's ouster signaled that the goverment was involved in a
power struggle.
   Ardebili said at a prayer service today that he was delighted
with Montazeri's letter, IRNA reported. ``He wrote it for those who
wanted to muddy the waters,'' IRNA quoted Ardebili as saying.
   Ardebili said nothing more about the letter, IRNA reported, but
said of the ouster, ``This is not a power struggle or a
conspiracy.''
   Khomeini, 88, designated Montazeri in 1985 as his successor but
asked him to step down as part of his campaign to revive what he
called Iran's flagging revolutionary spirit.
   The chief justice said he was speaking out because some people
were asking questions about the leadership issue and the future of
the Islamic republic, IRNA said. ``There's nothing for anyone to be
worried about,'' Ardebili said.
   In his resignation letter, Montazeri had asked that his
resignation not be used to foment government opposition. ``And I
would like to ask my dear brothers and sisters not to do anything
about the great leader's decision ... using their support for me as
an excuse,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
