<FIRST>u w PM-WrightProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0471 04-07 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Wright Aide Says Speaker Asked Aides to Help Him Sell Book</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Wright telephone call to aide, ethics panel
resumes deliberations, extension of counsel contract, likelihood of report
release.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright telephoned a former
aide last year and asked him to sign an affidavit stating that the
aide had volunteered to work on the speaker's book, ``Reflections
of a Public Man,'' according to testimony given to the ethics
committee investigating Wright's finances.
   The testimony also alleges that Wright, at a breakfast meeting
early in 1985, asked congressional aides to help set up promotional
events for the book, according to sources familiar with the
deposition of former Wright aide Matthew Cossolotto.
   Wright's directive was followed in the next month or so by book
signings at a Capitol Hill bookstore and the National Press Club, a
distribution of copies _ paid for by lobbyists _ to Democrats
attending a party conference and by an appearance on a televised
talk show.
   An aide to Wright, Mark Johnson, called Cossolotto ``a
disgruntled former employee'' but did not deny the speaker had
directed staff members to sell books.
   The ethics committee, which met behind closed doors to continue
its deliberations today, is looking into whether Wright used bulk
sales of the book to circumvent limits on outside income from
speaking and writing fees.
   Cossolotto testified to the panel that after a newspaper
reported last June that he had helped complile and edit the book,
including a three-week trip to Fort Worth to oversee final
preparation for printing, he telephoned the speaker. When Wright
called him back, he asked Cossolotto to sign an affidavit swearing
to the voluntary nature of the job assignment.
   The former aide told the committee he considered the book work
part of his official job assignment, and declined to sign the
affidavit.
   Johnson disputed that version of events, saying Cossolotto had
volunteered at first to give an affidavit, then backed out.
   Wright acknowledged Wednesday that in at least one instance _
the sale of 504 copies of the book to Southwest Texas State
University in lieu of a $3,000 speaking fee _ he had given his
assent to the deal.
   In that case, the suggestion to sell books came from a staff
member, Wright said.
   In at least one other case, the March 1986 sale of $1,000 worth
of books in lieu of a speaking fee from Mid-Continent Oil and Gas
Association, the suggestion to buy books also came from a Wright
staff aide, according to a source familiar with the transaction.
Wright was to ship the books not to the trade group, but to schools
in Texas, the source said.
   One ethics committee member, who did not wish to be identified,
cknowledged Thursday that the issue of book promotion was before
the panel, but it was unclear how serious the committee considers
that issue.
   The ethics panel is expected to reach some conclusion in its
nine-month investigation of Wright sometime next week, said
Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif. Sources have said the panel is
concentrating on the book sales and Wright's financial dealings
with his friend George Mallick, a Fort Worth real estate developer.
   As the panel resumed deliberations today, Dixon said the
contract of its special outside counsel, Richard Phelan, was being
extended through July 1.
   If the committee were to find cause to recommend sanctions
against Wright, the speaker would have 21 days to respond under the
panel's rules. Then the committee would have an additional 30 days
to decide whether to recommend disciplinary action to the full
House.
   A two-month extension of the contract could cover that time
period, but Dixon said ``you can't read anything into'' the request
for an extension.
   Both Dixon and Rep. John Myers, R-Ind., also said today that
committee precedent would call for eventual public release of the
full report by Phelan on all six original counts against Wright,
regardless of whether the panel agrees with them. That position
apparently is at odds with that of members of the House Democratic
leadership, who have argued the panel should release only those
parts of the report which support its conclusions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
