<FIRST>u a PM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0515 04-07 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0515,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Countdown Test Completed For Space Shuttle Planet Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with countdown test completed;
Pick up 3rd graf, `The two-day ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantis' five astronauts boarded
their spaceship today in a successful countdown test for the first
space shuttle planetary mission.
   Wearing bulky space suits, the crew members for the 29th shuttle
mission entered the cabin for the final two hours of the rehearsal
to run through launch day procedures.
   The exercise ended as planned five seconds before the count
reached zero.
   ``At this point, everything appears to have gone as planned,''
said NASA spokesman Hugh Harris. A number of technical problems
were built into the countdown, ``just to ensure that we do have the
capability of both solving problems and stopping the countdown
should a problem occur on launch day.''
   The two-day countdown test, which began Thursday, duplicates
much of the actual count, except that the fuel tank is not loaded
and some procedures are shortened.
   Also being monitored was the Magellan spacecraft in the cargo
bay. After reaching orbit, the astronauts are to release this $378
million payload on a mission to map the cloud-hidden surface of the
planet Venus.
   After a 466-day outward trip, Magellan is to sweep into orbit
around Earth's nearest planetary neighbor and aim a high-powered
imaging radar at the surface. During 243 days, the radar is to send
back the sharpest images yet of much of this mysterious planet.
   NASA is aiming for an Atlantis liftoff on April 28 but admits
the schedule is tight. Shuttle managers are to meet next Friday to
set a launch date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
