<FIRST>u w PM-BushRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0610 04-07 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0610, etc,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT ^Eds: Wrapup, new material and editing throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush firmly refused today to discuss
his role in the Reagan administration's secret plan to aid the
Contra rebels, saying he did not want to ``prejudice the trial'' of
former White House aide Oliver North.
   ``The legal process ought to run unfettered without you or me''
interfering, the president told a reporter who asked him to square
his previous statements on the affair with courtroom disclosures on
Thursday that suggested a greater role than had been known.
   Bush said the material presented to the North jury ``has been
available to'' government prosecutors and congressional
investigators previously ``and has been reviewed by them for any
special significance.'' He would not answer a questioner who quoted
Edmund Muskie _ a member of a White House investigating panel _ as
saying that some of the material looked new to him.
   ``I stand by my statement about the Iran-Contra committee,''
Bush said.
   Bush began his news conference with a statement increasing the
federal role in cleaning up the aftermath of the Alaska oil spill.
He ordered U.S. Armed forces personnel to assist in the cleanup,
saying, ``We all share the sorrow and concern of Alaskans.''
   ``Exxon's efforts standing alone are not enough,'' he said, but
emphasizing that the giant oil firm would continue to be
responsible and liable for the accident. He defended himself from
criticism that it had taken too long for him to provide federal
help to the clean-up effort.
   On other matters, Bush:
   Said he was unwilling to compromise with Democrats who seek a
larger increase in the minimum wage.
   Expressed some satisfaction with recent talks on Middle East
peace efforts.
   Defended himself from criticism by Mikhail Gorbachev that his
administration was slow to develop an initiative for arms reduction.
   Said developments in Poland were ``mind-boggling'' because of
the pace of reform. ``I think it is a sign of the change of
democratization... This is all very encouraging.''
   He said he had not decided whether he should consider a return
visit to the East European country.
   Bush announced the Alaska developments during an appearance in
the White House briefing room at which he was accompanied by
Cabinet members and Alaskan members of Congress. Questions quickly
turned to other matters, including Soviet affairs, much to Bush's
frustration.
   Concerning the Iran-Contra affair, he said the independent
counsel and congressional committees had access to the material
made public at the North trial.
   Asked what his pledge meant not to talk further on the subject,
he replied, ``It means I've said all I'm going to say about...on
the advice of lawyers.''
   ``Please accept it when I've said I'm not going to talk about it
anymore.''
   ``So nice try,'' he said to the reporter.
   He reacted brusquely when asked about Soviet suggestions that
the United States wasn't keeping pace with Soviet moves in arms
reduction. Gorbachev, on a visit to Britain, said through a
spokesman on Thursday that ``continuity is the name of the game. We
are a little bit apprehensive we could be losing it.''
   Bush said there was no delay in his administration's development
of policy regarding nuclear weapons negotiations and foreign policy.
   ``We are making a prudent review,`` Bush said. ``... Mr.
Gorbachev knows there is no foot-dragging going on, and I`m not
concerned in the least.''
   Bush also said he hoped his meetings this week with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
had produced some improvements in the peace prospects in the Middle
East. He said sometimes ``small steps'' can be important.
   Bush also emphatically refused to raise his proposal for a
higher minimum wage, despite Democratic pressure to force him to do
so.
   ``I have no intention of budging one inch on this. I have too
much at stake,'' said Bush, who appears headed for a veto
confrontation with the Democratic majorities of Congress over the
issue.
   The president opened his mid-morning news conference at the
White House with the announcement that after two weeks he had
ordered military personnel to assist in the cleanup of the
disastrous oil spill in Prince William Sound.
   Members of Alaska's congressional delegation and high-ranking
administration officials joined him at the White House press room
podium as the president predicted the effort would be ``massive,
prolonged and frustrating.''
   ``Our ultimate goal must be the complete restorationm of the
ecology and the economy of Prince William Sound including all of
its fish, marine mammals, birds and wildlife,'' Bush said.
   An Exxon oil tanker hit a well-marked reef in the sound two
weeks ago, resulting in a 10-million gallon oil spill. Bush said
his decision to deploy federal troops to help in the clean-up
operation ``should not in any way relieve Exxon from any of its
responsibilities or its liabilities.''
   In London, earlier today, Gorbachev promised deep cuts in the
Soviet military and announced he would close two more nuclear
reactors that produce weapons-grade plutonium. Asked for his
appraisal, Bush deflected the question. ``We will react when we are
ready to react,'' he said.
</TEXT>
