<FIRST>r w PM-US-Salvador 1stLd-Writlethru a0432 04-07 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writlethru, a0432,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Demand New Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 12 grafs new with news conference; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
The rebel. Removes last 10 grafs pvs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Alfredo Cristiani of El
Salvador today rejected a demand by Salvadoran rebels that he
declare his forthcoming administration a transitional government
and call for new elections.
   Cristiani's comment came at a news conference on a plan outlined
by rebel representatives on Thursday, calling for negotiations for
a ceasefire, after which elections would be held within six months.
   ``I believe this is a setback in the progress that has been made
in dialogue'' with the rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front, Cristiani said.
   He said it also was ``starting to show'' that the rebel faction
``does not really want peace, but rather is simply trying to play a
political game in which they are trying to pretend to be looking
for a peaceful solution but simply creating more and more obstacles
as things go along.''
   ``I would definitely not consider our government a transitional
goverment unless you put it in a five-year term,'' Cristiani said,
with the next election to be held in 1994.
   However, he said, his government will be willing to talk with
the rebels to ``try to seek a way by which they can incorporate
themselves into the process.''
   Cristiani's press conference came a few hours before a scheduled
meeting at the White House with President Bush.
   Asked whether he was satisified with the present level of U.S.
economic aid to El Salvador, Cristiani said, ``I think the aid
package in itself is reasonable. I think it is something that you
can work with. Obviously the problems are so big that we would like
to see the aid package increased, but we certainly understand the
problems that the United States has with its own budget.''
   Two young women who did not identify themselves were hustled out
of the room by security men after they rose and shouted questions
about charges linking Cristiani's Arena party to death squads.
   In response to a reporter's question about the death squads
later, the Salvadoran president-elect said such activity has been
diminishing and is the work of individuals, mostly in the armed
forces and security forces, ``taking matters into their own
hands.'' He said his government's policy would be to hold these
people responsible for their acts.
   Outside the National Press Building, where the news conference
was held, a small band of demonstrators shouted, ``Cristiani, you
can't hide. We charge you with genocide.''
   The rebel proposal also demands that U.S. aid to the Salvadoran
government be halted and U.S. military advisers withdrawn.
   ``The future government can choose between two options,'' said
Francisco Altschul, a representative of the political opposition
commission of the rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front.
``It can be a government which will deepen the war or it can be a
government of transition towards peace.''
   The rebel plan calls for negotiations leading to a cease-fire,
after which an election would be held within six months, with
military forces of both sides barred from polling places.
Cristiani, the candidate of the right-wing Arena party, was elected
March 19 in an election which the rebels had sought to have
postponed.
   The State Department has said the United States recognizes the
results of the balloting despite the Arena party's past links to
right-wing death squad activities. U.S. officials say the death
squads are now substantially less active than they were during
their peak in the early 1980s.
   After the election, the guerrillas escalated attacks on
government installations in the 9-year-old war against the
U.S.-supported government. More than 70,000 Salvadorans, most of
them civilians, have been killed since the war began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
