<FIRST>r a PM-StillAlive     04-07 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Still Alive,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Learns Estranged Husband Filed Lawsuit Claiming She Was Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lene is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man filed a wrongful death suit against the city
on behalf of his estranged wife and had ``her'' body buried in a
pauper's grave but his wife _ one of two _ is still alive and
police are trying to identify the body.
   Jacquelyn Brown, 34, of Arkansas, told police she last spoke to
her husband, Robert Jerome Brown, 33, at her home last October.
   Brown did not tell her he had identified her as the victim of a
Dallas pedestrian accident in January 1988 and had her buried at
county expense, the Dallas Times Herald reported today.
   Brown also didn't tell her he had hired an attorney to pursue
the wrongful death lawsuit for ``negligent failure to provide a
street light'' on a freeway where she supposedly was killed while
trying to cross four lanes of traffic on Jan. 3, 1988.
   ``It's one of the strangest cases I've been involved in,'' said
homicide Detective James Gallagher.
   Brown apparently read newspaper accounts of an unidentified
traffic victim and decided to claim the body as that of his wife,
he said.
   ``This man presented himself, said he was the husband of
Jacquelyn Brown and said he thought she might have been killed in
an accident,'' said Bill Lene, chief field agent for the Dallas
County medical examiner's office. ``We showed a photograph of her
to him, and he identified the photo saying, `This is my wife.'''
   Authorities had no reason to question Brown's identification of
her, Lene said.
   Six weeks after Brown told officials he had no money to bury his
``wife,'' he hired an attorney who filed a claim with the city for
monetary damages, saying he and his two children had suffered pain
and suffering and the loss of companionship and earnings as a
result of his wife's death.
   Police say they don't know that the couple had any children.
   Brown was arrested in Malvern, Ark., last month on an auto theft
charge and also has been charged with capital murder in a 1986
robbery and slaying of a Little Rock prostitute.
   Gallagher said Brown's second wife _ Sonya Brown, 20 _ also has
been charged with murder as an accomplice in the Arkansas slaying.
   Gallagher said that under questioning, Sonya Brown revealed that
Brown told her he was somehow involved in Jacquelyn's death.
   When a detective went to review the death as a possible
homicide, he discovered that ``Jacquelyn Brown is not only alive
and well, but (Robert Brown) in October 1988 went to Arkansas to
visit her.''
   Gallagher said police now believe the dead woman may be a
22-year-old who was reported missing by her sister only last month.
The sister told police she had not seen the woman since December
1987.
</TEXT>
