<FIRST>r a PM-SlayingConfession 1stLd-Writethru a0519 04-07 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Slaying Confession, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0519,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede PARMA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Man Confesses Slayings To Priest, Surrenders To Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with arraignment, CORRECT spelling of
suspect's first name to Stephen sted Steven, UPDATE with quotes from news
conference, judge, trims grafs 15-16 pvs to tighten. Changes byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRUTHERS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man confessed to a priest that he had
killed his 2{-year-old child and her mother and stuffed their
bodies in a refrigerator, said the priest, who persuaded the man to
surrender to authorities.
   Stephen A. Vrabel, 32, of Struthers, did not enter a plea when
charged with two counts of aggravated murder in Struthers Municipal
Court today. Judge Robert Kalafut set bond at $2 million and
appointed an attorney for the suspect, who said he didn't want a
lawyer.
   Vrabel turned himself in Thursday to authorities after spending
30 minutes in a confessional with the Rev. John Carlin, pastor of
St. Charles Roman Catholic Church in Parma, a Cleveland suburb.
   ``He told me that he has killed his wife and daughter,'' Carlin
said in a telephone interview Thursday.
   The confession in the confessional ``is a movie scenario,'' said
Carlin, 39, who has been a priest for 13 years. ``Yes, I was
scared.''
   The child, Lisa Clemente, was found bundled with two teddy
bears, blankets and a pillow and stuffed into the freezer
compartment of their apartment refrigerator, said Struthers
detective Dean Phillips.
   He said the body of the mother, Susan Clemente, 29, was in the
refrigerator compartment with blankets, sheets and a pillow tied
around her with rope. The refrigerator shelves had been removed.
   The woman and child each were shot in the head with a
small-caliber pistol, Phillips said. Authorities think they had
been dead for about a week when their bodies were found Wednesday
evening.
   ``Apparently, the reason he turned himself in is he heard the
news media reports'' Thursday about the bodies being found,
Phillips said at a news conference after the arraignment.
   Officials said that they were unsure whether Ms. Clemente and
Vrabel were married.
   Carlin said he would never have broken the secrecy demanded in
confession but twice was told by the man to help him explain to
police what had happened.
   When they talked with police, Carlin said, ``The guy was not
being real specific. He told me, `Well, you tell them what I said.'
''
   Vrabel repeated to Carlin in front of three police officers his
permission to have his confession of guilt disclosed, the priest
said.
   Carlin said he had never met Vrabel, who apparently was driving
through the neighborhood and spotted the church. Parma is about 60
miles northwest of Struthers, a Youngtown suburb.
   Vrabel approached the priest, who was hearing confessions. After
their talk they drove to police headquarters, where police found a
.22-caliber pistol in his car after obtaining a search warrant.
   During the arraignemnt this morning, Vrabel told the judge he
had last worked about six months ago and didn't have any income.
   Kalafut said investigators found beer cans throughout the
apartment and a type of gas mask that he said is often used in drug
use.
   ``Certainly this ranks as one of the most gruesome (slayings) in
the area in my 26 years as judge,'' Kalafut said. He said a
preliminary hearing would be held within 10 days.
   Vrabel, held at the Struthers jail, was to be transferred to the
Mahoning County jail to await trial, Phillips said.
   Ms. Clemente lived in a two-story apartment building in
Struthers, with her daughter and Vrabel, said Ms. Clemente's uncle,
Michael C. Clemente.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
