<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru a0466 04-07 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Sees Climate In Mideast Improved, Pledges US Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New with Bush quotes first 8 grafs; editing thruout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, pledging U.S. help in seeking
a Mideast settlement, today described the situation in the troubled
region as marginally improved.
   Referring to a plan by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to
hold elections among Palestinian Arabs living under Israeli control
in the West Bank and Gaza, the president said:
   ``In the Middle East, a little step sometimes can be fruitful. I
think the climate is better than it has been.''
   Bush, meeting with reporters at the White House, said in
response to a question that it was too early for him to consider
traveling to the region to try to resolve the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   ``If I personally can be helpful, I am going to do it,'' Bush
said.
   But, he added, ``it is not a time when a lot of high-visibility
missions on the part of the president can be helpful in the
process.''
   As for the proposed elections, which Shamir suggested as a way
to select Arab delegates to meet with his goverment, Bush said:
   ``We haven't fully resolved exactly who's going to have a role;
that's a matter to be determined between the parties. ... The PLO
has people living on the West Bank. ...We want to see elections
that are free and fair.''
   Shamir's intent is to avoid PLO participation in selecting Arab
representatives by having Israeli authorities run the selection
process.
   Shamir presented his proposal to Bush on Thursday. At a news
conference, the prime minister ruled out having international
observers on hand for the voting. Still, Secrertary of State James
A. Baker III said he was encouraged about Mideast prospects.
   ``I think the important thing is that his proposal comes with
something that can be worked with,'' Baker said Thursday. ``It
offers us an opportunity to perhaps move the peace process forward.
And I think that's encouraging.''
   Shamir, who was meeting today with members of Congress, said
Israelis and Palestinians would oversee the balloting he intends to
hold on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   ``We do not think there is a need of international
supervision,'' he said. ``Israel has a long tradition of democracy
and decent and honest elections.''
   Shamir said he thinks that a majority of the 1.4 million
Palestinian Arabs living under Israeli control would participate in
the election. ``They are waiting for a peaceful solution,'' he said.
   The territories have been plagued with violence since
Palestinians began an uprising in December 1987. A total of 420
Palestinians and 18 Israelis have died in the unrest.
   Shamir, who blames the PLO for the violence, acknowledged the
PLO was likely to oppose the election. ``They want the immediate
establishment of an independent Palestinian state,'' Shamir said.
   His plan calls for the election of Palestinian leaders to
negotiate temporary self-rule. After a trial period, Shamir
proposes to have Israel, Palestinians, Egypt and Jordan work out a
permanent settlement.
   ``We do not want to run the lives of the inhabitants,'' Shamir
said in a speech Thursday. ``We want them to have self-rule.''
   But he again opposed establishment of a Palestinian state on the
West Bank and in Gaza, which Shamir said ``can only be a convenient
launching pad for terrorist attacks against the center of our
country.''
   Without the territories, Israel at its most densely populated
center is as wide as the distance between the White House and Chevy
Chase, a Washington suburb, Shamir said.
   While giving a qualified endorsement of the principle of holding
elections, Bush emphasized that Israel eventually must relinquish
the land the Arabs lost in the 1967 Six-Day war.
   Bush said he told Shamir ``we do not support an independent
Palestinian state, nor Israeli sovereignty over or permanent
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza.''
   By mentioning Israeli ``sovereignty,'' Bush went a step beyond
his statement Monday that Israel must end the occupation of the
territory. And that, in itself, indicated a hardening U.S. stance.
   Shamir, in his speech, did not challenge Bush directly. But he
called the idea of Israel trading territory for peace, which other
presidents have endorsed, a hoax.
   ``The choice is not between Israel keeping the territories or
risking war,'' Shamir said. ``The opposite is true. If we leave,
there will almost certainly be war.''
   The election would determine the makeup of a Palestinian
delegation to negotiate with Israel for ``an interim period of
self-governing administration,'' Shamir said. That would be
followed by negotiations for ``a permanent agreement,'' he said.
   Baker, speaking later to reporters at the State Department, said
he was encouraged by the proposition.
   ``There is something new in this proposal,'' he said. ``It is
new _ the concept of elections before you go to transitional
arrangements. That is new.''
   Still, Baker said, ``There are a number of questions ... that
have to be fleshed out and answered. But it gives people who are
interested in trying to move the peace process forward something to
work with.''
</TEXT>
