<FIRST>u a PM-Right-To-Die 2ndLd-Writethru a0601 04-07 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Right-To-Die, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0601,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stabbing Victim Who Was Taken Off Life-Support System Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf with 3 grafs to UPDATE with atttorney's
comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 26-year-old stabbing victim whose
life-support system was disconnected eight days ago over the
objections of his assailant died today, nearly four years after the
attack left him in a coma.
   Sylvia Lane said her son, Mark Weaver, died at about 2 a.m. ``He
died peacefully. He never had a moment's pain,'' she said.
   Noel Pagan, who served three years in prison for stabbing Weaver
during a street fight in 1985, fought unsuccessfully in court last
week to force Weaver's family to keep him alive on a feeding tube.
Prosecutors said Pagan, now on probation, could face a murder
charge once Weaver died, but they need a cause of death before they
can decide whether to seek charges.
   ``The medical examiner will conduct an autopsy and make a report
to us, and then we will make a decision,'' Attorney General James
E. Tierney said today.
   Tierney declined to say what sort of finding would be necessary
before a murder charge could be sought.
   ``I'm not going to answer any hypothetical questions about an
autopsy being conducted,'' Tierney said. He did not know how soon
to expect autopsy results.
   Pagan's lawyer, Robert Mullen, said last week he would try to
persuade prosecutors to file no additional charges in the case,
although he declined to appeal the ruling from Probate Judge Dana
Childs that allowed Weaver's family to remove the feeding tube just
after midnight on March 30. The judge said Pagan had no right to
intervene in Weaver's care.
   Mullen today declined to predict whether his client will face
charges, but he said if charges are lodged he will file motions to
get them thrown out.
   ``The first two that come to mind are double jeopardy and the
so-called year-and-a-day rule,'' Mullen said. Under that legal
provision, which was cited in at least two Maine cases, ``a person
must die a year and a day after an event to be charged with murder
or manslaughter,'' he said.
   The attorney for Weaver's family, Charles Kadish, did not answer
phone calls this morning.
   Funeral services were being arranged by the family.
</TEXT>
