<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan     04-07 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Ignore Cease-Fire; Fight For Jalalabad Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet-made Scud missile fired by
Afghanistan's besieged government forces blasted Pakistani
territory early today, authorities said. No casualties were
reported.
   Pakistan did not immediately respond. This country gives refuge
to more than 3 million Afghan war refugees and Moslem guerrillas
fighting to overthrow President Najib's communist government.
   The attack came after the guerrillas' government-in-exile
ordered more intense fighting in response to Najib's announcement
of a unilateral cease-fire to mark Islam's holiest month of
Ramadan, which began Thursday.
   Moscow added the missiles with their range of 100-175 miles to
the Afghan arsenal last November. They were paraded through Kabul
at the time, and Pakistan warned they were capable of hitting
hitting Pakistani territory.
   Government troops have been firing Scud missiles at Jalalabad,
where their fellow soldiers are engaged in an intense battle for
the city with Moslem guerrillas. Kabul is 120 miles west of the
Pakistan border.
   In the Afghan capital Thursday, state radio said nine civilians
and one soldier have been killed during the past 24 hours in a
barrage of rebel rocket fire on Jalalabad, 45 miles west of the
Pakistan border.
   The rebels' Afghan News Agency said in a statement that 80
Afghan soldiers were killed in fighting around Jalalbad in the past
three days.
   Kabul Radio also blamed rebels for the deaths of three people
whom it said were killed when rockets hit the eastern garrison town
of Khost, several miles from the Pakistan border. The radio report
said government troops killed 148 guerrillas in retaliatory
fighting.
   It is impossible to verify either sides' claims.
   Rebel sources in Pakistan have rejected as a propaganda ploy the
government's latest cease-fire offer, proposed Wednesday.
</TEXT>
