<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Gandhi     04-07 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Gandhi,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Charged with Conspiracy in Gandhi Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday charged five Sikhs
with conspiracy in the assassination of Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi in 1984, which it said was part of a plot to establish a
separate Sikh nation.
   One defendant, Rattan Singh, was killed by rival Sikh militants
in 1985, the government said. The others are Simranjeet Singh Mann,
a former senior police officer; Attinder Pal Singh, a well-known
militant; and college lecturers Dalip Singh and Jagmohan Singh Tony.
   Officers of the Special Investigating Team examining the case
filed the charges with S.L. Khanna, chief magistrate of New Delhi.
   All five are accused of waging war aginst the state, sedition,
criminal conspiracy, murder and attempted murder. The charges carry
the death penalty.
   Beant Singh and and Satwant Singh, Sikh members of Mrs. Gandhi's
personal guard, shot her down Oct. 31, 1984, in her New Delhi
residence. Beant Singh was killed by other bodyguards and Satwant
Singh was hanged Jan. 6.
   Also hanged was Kehar Singh, an uncle of Beant Singh, who was
convicted of conspiracy.
   None of the other Singhs are related. All male Sikhs take the
name Singh, which means lion in Punjabi, as a doctrine of their
faith.
   The government said the five began plotting after the army raid
Mrs. Gandhi ordered in June 1984 on Sikhism's holiest shrine, the
Golden Temple in Amritsar.
   Its list of charges gave this account of the defendants'
activities:
   They conspired to commit ``sensational acts in order to create
chaos, confusion and anarchy by hijacking planes, breaching canals,
poisoning drinking water supply and destroying Parliament House.''
   Those acts included organizing the hijacking of an Indian
Airlines plane to Dubai on Aug. 24, 1984. They planned to kill Mrs.
Gandhi and her son, Rajiv, who succeeded her as prime minister, in
September in Nagpur, central India, but ``the assassination ...
could not be executed for want of weapons.''
   Mann and Attinder Pal Singh decided to attempt the murder
through someone associated with Mrs. Gandhi's security, and
Attinder Pal Singh ``located Sub-Inspector Beant Singh as the most
suitable person,'' the government said.
   Attinder Pal Singh fled to Pakistan a week before the
assassination, ``where he was given a free hand'' to enlist support
for a separate Sikh nation in Punjab, the only Indian state where
Sikhs are the majority.
   He also was allowed to ``provide arms for training Sikh youth
and contact foreign-based activists for financial help,'' according
to the government.
   It did not elaborate on the militants' alleged links to
Pakistan, but India often accuses the Pakistanis of supporting Sikh
secessionists. No proof has been offered, and Pakistan, which
borders Punjab, denies it.
   Mann was arrested in December 1984 while trying to flee to Nepal
and Attinder Pal Singh was apprehended in October 1988.
   While in custody, Mann was named president of the Unified Akali
Dal, a militant Sikh political party in Punjab, a northern state
that is India's richest agricultural region.
   He resigned as a senior superintendent of police to protest the
raid on the Golden Temple, whose purpose was to dislodge militants
who had turned the shrine into a fortress. At least 1,200 people
were killed in the assault.
   Only 2 percent of India's 880 million people are Sikhs. They
accuse Hindus, who make up 90 percent, of discrimination.
   Sikh militants began fighting for a separate nation in 1982. At
least 2,400 people were killed in 1988 and more than 500 people
have been slain so far this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Gorbachev-Britain 10thLd-Writethru   04-07 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev-Britain, 10th Ld-Writethru,a0630,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Announces Halt In Production of Weapons-Grade Uranium</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Thatcher saying Soviet halt in uranium
production would have little effect. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Gorbachev today announced the Soviet Union
is halting production of weapons-grade uranium and will shut down
two more nuclear reactors that produce plutonium for nuclear
weapons by the end of next year.
   In a half-hour speech in London's Guildhall, the Soviet
president called his unilateral action ``another major step toward
the complete cessation of production of fissionable materials for
use in weapons.''
   Arms experts said today that while uranium and plutonium are
both used in Soviet nuclear weapons, plutonium is used more often
and that Moscow has enough on hand to produce more weapons.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told reporters the Soviet move
``will have no effect in practice'' because ``they probably have
quite a sufficient stockpile of uranium.''
   In Washington, President Bush declined to comment on Gorbachev's
announcement, saying he had not had time to review it.
   A Pentagon official said the steps outlined by Gorbachev would
not have a major impact on the Soviet capability to wage war.
   Gorbachev reiterated promises he made at the United Nations in
December that the Soviet Union would soon begin paring 500,000 men
from its standing army and withdrawing troops and tanks from Europe
and the Chinese frontier.
   Gorbachev made a strong appeal for world disarmament, but he
warned the process could falter if the West did not reciprocate.
   After the address, broadcast live throughout Britain and the
United States, Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, called on Queen
Elizabeth II at Windsor Castle, then left for Moscow at the end of
a six-day trip to Ireland, Cuba and Britain.
   Gorbachev invited the queen to visit the Soviet Union. She said
she would like to accept but that her foreign travel is always
fixed years in advance.
   Queen Elizabeth II would be the first monarch to go to Russia
since her grandfather's cousin, Czar Nicholas II, and his family
were killed after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution.
   Speaking at Guildhall, the city's seat of government for 1,000
years, Gorbachev said the world has reached a crossroad in which it
has to choose between peaceful interdependency and ``a policy of
force rooted in the past.
   ``If NATO goes ahead with its program of modernizing tactical
nuclear weapons,'' he said, ``this is bound also to devalue much of
what has been achieved under the INF treaty'' on medium-range
nuclear weapons that he signed with President Ronald Reagan in 1987.
   Gorbachev said, ``In addition to the industrial reactor for the
production of weapons-grade plutonium shut down in 1987, we plan to
shut down two other such reactors this year and next year without
commissioning new units to replace them.''
   ``We have completed the construction of a facility for the
destruction of chemical weapons and indeed to invite soon your
representatives to visit it,'' Gorbachev said.
   British experts on nuclear arsenals said it was difficult to
assess the impact of the Soviet cutbacks in production of
fissionable materials because the number of such production
facilities is secret.
   A nuclear physicist in England, who also requested anonymity,
said that uranium and plutonium are both still used in nuclear
weapons production but that plutonium is in wider use in the Soviet
Union and the United States.
   Francois Heisbourg, director of the London-based Institute of
Strategic Studies, said Gorbachev's announcement that the Soviets
would close two plutonium-producing reactors was new.
   But he said it was ``not as significant as it may sound because
there is already plenty of plutonium around which the Soviets can
use to make bombs.''
   The Pentagon official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the Soviets ``have stockpiles of weapons-grade materials'' and
could restart production in several years when supplies run low.
   Reiterating earlier promises, Gorbachev also said armed manpower
would be cut by 12 percent, the military budget by 14 percent and
weapons production by nearly 20 percent. Military factories are
being switched to production of consumer goods, and military
transport planes would be redeployed to carry civilian cargoes, he
said.
   He said the new Supreme Soviet, a legislative body to be
selected by the recently elected parliament, will publish the
nation's defense budget, most of which is now concealed.
   The speech got a standing ovation from the civic and political
leaders at Guildhall and a ringing endorsement by Mrs. Thatcher.
   ``We want you to succeed in your task,'' she said after the
speech. ``We're ready to help in practical ways.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0123 </DOCNO>
