<FIRST>u i PM-Arafat     04-07 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arafat,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Rejects Shamir Proposal For Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat today
criticized a U.S.-backed Israeli proposal for elections in
Israeli-occupied territories.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization leader, making the
comments on the second day of a two-day trip to Congo, also said
Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip will continue
a nearly 16-month-old uprising against Israeli rule ``until the
ultimate victory.''
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak ``Shamir's statement in
Washington is inappropriate, as usual. ... All oppressors in the
world have used the same language,'' Arafat said.
   Shamir proposed that Palestinians in the occupied lands elect
representatives to talk to Israel about establishing limited
self-rule. Under the plan, talks on the ultimate disposition of the
occupied territories would be left until later.
   President Bush, who has been meeting with Shamir in Washington,
gave qualified support to Shamir's proposal Thursday.
   Palestinians opposing the proposal have insisted elections be
part of a larger plan to end the occupation.
   Arafat reiterated his demand for an international peace
conference on the Middle East, with the participation of the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council and all concerned
parties, including the PLO. Israel refuses to negotiate with the
PLO, which it considers a terrorist organization.
   ``Until the ultimate victory, the uprising of the populations of
the Gaza and West Bank will continue,'' Arafat said.
   Israeli officials have said that Shamir's plan made no specific
demand for the end of the uprising as a condition for elections.
   Israel seized the West Bank, home to 1.7 million Arabs, from
Egypt and Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war.
</TEXT>
