<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Reaction 1stLd-Writethru a0583 04-07 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Reaction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0583,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Cool To Elections For Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Arafat criticizing Shamir
plan as ``inappropriate.'' Pickup 8th graf, ``Leaders of ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Mideast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Influential Palestinians reacted coolly today
to a U.S.-backed Israeli call for elections in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, insisting any balloting be part of a package that
promises an end to occupation.
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat, visiting Congo, criticized the proposal
as inappropriate and said the nearly 16-month-old Palestinian
uprising would continue ``until the ultimate victory.''
   Several thousand Palestinians rioted today, shouting nationalist
slogans and burning an Israeli flag outside Jerusalem's Al Aqsa
mosque.
   Police fired tear gas and rubber bullets to quell the violence,
a day after President Bush gave Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
qualified support of his proposal for elections in the occupied
lands to choose Palestinian leaders who would negotiate self-rule.
The two leaders are meeting in Washington.
   Talks on the ultimate disposition of the occupied territories
would be left until later.
   ``I think the intefadeh (uprising) will continue until Shamir
comes up with a better proposal,'' said Hanna Siniora, editor of
the pro-PLO daily Al Fajr newspaper.
   Siniora and most other Palestinians interviewed today said
Israel would have to accept giving up land it seized in the 1967
Middle East war and end the military occupation over the 1.7
million Arabs in the West Bank and Gaza.
   Israeli newspaper editorials said the right-wing premier had won
only a brief respite from the diplomatic pressure on Israel to make
concessions to match Arafat's steps in recognizing Israel and
forswearing terror.
   The Palestinian Liberation Organization leader, on a visit to
Congo, said ``Shamir's statement in Washington is inappropriate, as
usual. ... All oppressors in the world have used the same
language.''
   Leaders of the left-leaning Labor Party headed by Finance
Minister Shimon Peres were initially silent on the Washington
talks. But Shulamit Aloni, leader of the liberal Citizens Rights
Movement, accused Shamir of procrastinating.
   Palestinian leftists and pro-Syrian supporters rule out
elections. Other opinion leaders expressed skepticism about
Shamir's motivation but appeared to leave the door open to further
discussions.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, businessman Said Kenaan said
Shamir's real objective was to avoid talking to the PLO and
sidetrack negotiations to a temporary solution that ignored
Palestinian demands for statehood.
   Nabil Jabari, the board chairman of Hebron University who spent
65 days in administrative detention without trial for alleged
contacts with PLO leaders, said the PLO would have to approve any
election plan.
   ``I would not agree to any election if it is only limited to
voting and is not part of an overall package to solve the
Palestinian problem,'' he said.
   Some Palestinians said elections would have to be preceded by
tension-relieving steps such as the release of the 1,187
Palestinians detained without trial, allowing deported activists to
return to stand as candidates and lifting military orders
restricting freedom of speech and assembly.
   Jonathan Kuttab, a West Bank lawyer and human rights activist,
said in an interview: ``Palestinians are not opposed to elections
themselves but are opposed to the idea if the real objective is to
avoid dealing with the Palestinian people's representatives, the
PLO.''
   Kuttab said laws banning contact with the PLO would have to be
lifted so any Palestinians elected could serve as a bridge to the
PLO, the only body that could speak for the world's 5 million
Palestinians.
   Al Quds, the leading pro-PLO daily in Arab east Jerusalem, noted
with satisfaction the U.S. opposition to continued Israeli
occupation and its stand against Israeli annexation of the land.
But it cautiously avoided comment on the elections proposal that
Bush endorsed.
   In Washington, Bush told the visiting Israeli prime minister the
United States does not suport ``an independent Palesntinian state,
nor Israeli sovereignty over or permanent occupation of the West
Bank and Gaza.''
</TEXT>
