<HEAD>WASHN: Oliver North?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A. No.
   Q. Mr. President _
   A. Because I don't want to prejudice the trial, John.
   It would be imprudent for us to do that, and we're not going to
do it.
   And I stand by my statement about the Iran-Contra committee.
   Q. Will you speak after the trial?
   A. That's it.
   Q. Mr. President, the conventional wisdom is that an American
president never has much to gain by getting personally involved in
the Middle East. But I was thinking that maybe you were an
exception, given your initial round this week. Can you tell us
what's in your mind about the Middle East, if you see yourself
getting very personally involved over the course of your presidency
in trying to solve this?
   A. Look, if I help _ if I felt that being immersed in it would
help solve the problem of peace in the Middle East, I would do that.
   And I think you're right, there have been times when it appears
that the president shouldn't be fully involved.
   But we've had two visits here now this week _ President Mubarak,
Prime Minister Shamir.
   We'll have a visit, a forthcoming visit from King Hussein.
   And I'm going to give the same assurances to him I've given to
Mubarak and Shamir, and that is that if I personally can be
helpful, I want to do it.
   And in the meantime, why, I will say that _ I can't say I'm
