<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0500 04-07 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0500,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Unveil New Peace Proposal, But Cristiani Rejects It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with Cristiani rejecting rebel plan. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels unveiled a new
proposal for ending El Salvador's nine-year civil war, but it was
rejected today by President-elect Alfredo Cristiani.
   The proposal released Thursday termed ``illegitimate'' the
landslide victory of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance,
or Arena, in the March 19 presidential election. It called on Arena
to declare itself a transitional government and for general
elections before year's end.
   The rebels said the new government, which is scheduled to take
power June 1 from outgoing President Jose Napoleon Duarte, must
choose between escalated civil war and negotiated peace.
   Cristiani, who is in Washington to meet with President Bush,
said at a news conference today: ``I would definitely not consider
our government a transitional government unless you put it in a
five-year term.'' However, he said, his government will be willing
to talk with the rebels to ``try to seek a way by which they can
incorporate themselves into the process.''
   Cristiani has said many times that the insurgents must lay down
their arms and incorporate themselves into the democratic process.
The guerrillas say that is tantamount to a call for surrender and
reject it.
   The guerrillas have vowed to step up attacks in the coming weeks
to demonstrate to Arena the country is ``ungovernable'' without
their consent.
   Thursday's guerrilla proposal was similar to one announced Jan.
23. The new plan added elements resulting from subsequent talks in
Mexico between the rebels and Salvadoran political party
representatives.
   The Salvadoran government rejected the January proposal.
   ``We do not believe the image campaign through which Arena is
trying to present itself as a moderate force,'' said the guerrilla
document, signed by the five members of the insurgent high command.
   After its 1981 founding, Arena was associated with right-wing
death squads accused of slaying tens of thousands of suspected
leftists.
   Cashiered army Maj. Roberto D'Aubuisson, the alleged godfather
of the death squads, is an Arena legislator and leader of the
congress' majority block.
   Cristiani maintains the party has matured into a modern
conservative organization with an ideology similar to that of U.S.
Republicans. Arena opponents say Cristiani is little more than a
pseudo-democratic veneer for a neo-fascist party.
   ``Arena has made it clear it will pursue a policy of slaughter
and total war,'' said the rebel proposal.
   It alleged that Arena is now virtually running the government
despite the still-incumbent Christian Democratic administration. It
claimed human rights abuses have surged since the Arena victory.
   Independent human rights monitors have said they lack enough
data to back up that contention.
   The guerrillas reiterated earlier demands that implicated army
officers be tried and punished for rights abuses and that the army
be reduced from its current strength of 56,000 to its 1978 level of
12,000.
   They also called for elimination of the three police forces and
formation of a single police force under civilian administration.
The internal security forces currently depend on the Defense
Ministry, which is headed by an army general.
   They said additionally that the judicial system, which they
characterized as corrupt and inefficient, must be purged and
reformed.
   The rebels said that if their conditions were met, the FMLN
would cease the armed struggle and incorporate itself into the
country's political process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
