<FIRST>r i AM-Kopelev     04-07 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kopelev,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expelled Soviet Writer Gets Permission to Visit Homeland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lev Kopelev, the Soviet writer and
human rights activist expelled from his homeland eight years ago,
has been given permission to visit Moscow, his wife said Friday.
   Raisa Orlova Kopelev confirmed the report in the Essen-based
Neue Ruhr-Neue Rhine newspaper that Kopelev had been granted a visa
and said her husband would likely travel to the Soviet Union on
Sunday to celebrate his 77th birthday.
   She did not say how long the visit might last.
   The Soviets' decision to approve a visa for Kopelev ``came as a
total surprise,'' Mrs. Kopelev said by telephone from their home in
Cologne.
   Kopelev, now a West German citizen, was expelled from the Soviet
Union in 1981. In the 1960s and 1970s Kopelev spoke out in support
of writer Alexander Solzhenitsyn, physicist Andrei Sakharov who won
the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975, and other critics of the Kremlin.
</TEXT>
