<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1323EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-KingChurch     04-07 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-King Church,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pastor Says King's Old Church Losing Spirit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Addre' in last graf is correct.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pastor of the church where Martin
Luther King Jr. rose to national prominence has decided to retire,
complaining the congregation is losing the spirit that helped bring
about social change.
   The Rev. G. Murray Branch, 74, said he will step down as pastor
of Dexter Avenue King Memorial Baptist Church on June 30 and return
to Atlanta, where he taught for many years at a seminary.
   ``I'm a little weary,'' he said. ``But the main reason I'm
leaving is there has been a demand on the church _ an increase in
service _ but participation has declined.''
   The church in downtown Montgomery has become a tourist
attraction because King was its pastor when he rose to national
prominence as leader of the Montgomery bus boycott in 1955-56. The
church since has been the rallying point for many civil rights
demonstrations.
   But Branch said the congregation has declined to about 250
active members and there has been a drop in community and church
activities by the remaining members.
   ``That's another reason I'm unhappy with this congregation,'' he
said. ``Given the laity of this congregation and the status of the
majority of the members _ socially and economically _ they ought to
be involved in more meaningful community service.''
   Addre Bryant, chairman of the board of deacons, agreed with
Branch that not everyone was participating fully. ``It takes
different things to motivate folks to do things. Some things may
depend on the organization of the church,'' he said. ``There really
has been no organization.''
</TEXT>
