<FIRST>r a PM-SoCalHeat 1stLd-Writethru a0540 04-07 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SoCal Heat, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0540,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Scorching Weather In Store For Southern California</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with morning temperature, El Toro
nation's hot spot; Picks up 4th graf, `The forecast ...'; ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sweltering weekend lay ahead for southern
Californians sweating out a springtime heat wave that has packed
beaches and prompted special patient care in a hospital left
without air conditioning after a fire.
   Residents braced today for a sizzling repeat of Thursday's
weather, which sent the temperature at the Los Angeles Civic Center
soaring to 106 degrees _ the hottest day of the year and the
hottest April day on record.
   El Toro in Orange County was the hottest spot in the nation
Thursday, frying at 112 degrees.
   The National Weather Service forecast temperatures to top 100
degrees in most of the region for a fourth straight day and issued
a heat warning for residents, urging them to sit still and drink
plenty of water.
   The record April 7 high at the civic center was 88, set in 1904,
and was certain to fall. By 9 a.m., downtown was already 82 degrees.
   The forecast concerned nurses at UCLA Medical Center, who were
giving patients tepid baths and covering them in moist towels after
a fire Thursday night knocked out air conditioning in the
400-patient hospital.
   Adminstrators closed the emergency room and surgeons canceled
all elective surgery while workers scrambled through the night to
repair the giant air conditioning units, said spokesman John Lewis.
   ``The best we can hope for is to have half the air conditioning
going by mid-afternoon today,'' he said. ``But it's still dark, and
I'm already beginning to feel the heat coming on.''
   Firefighters were investigating the cause of the blaze that
struck the cooling towers on the roof of the hospital. No patients
had to be transferred as of early today.
   The hot, dry Santa Ana winds from the desert bathed the Los
Angeles basin in heat from the mountains to the beaches, where air
temperatures in the 80s and 90s clashed with more seasonal water
temperatures in the 60s.
   ``People going to the beach and not going into the water are
just exposing themselves to the sun,'' said Dr. George Gellert, a
Los Angeles County health official. ``They may be better off
remaining in the shade.''
   Northern California had its own heat wave.
   Even normally mild San Francisco hit a record 91 degrees on
Thursday, five degrees above the previous high for that date set in
1924.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
