<FIRST>b w PM-OilSpill-Congress 4thLd-Writethru a0643 04-07 0986</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill-Congress, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0643,1000</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Personnel to Assist in Cleanup of Alaska Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 6-7, At the Pentagon.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush ordered U.S. military personnel
today to assist in the cleanup of the huge oil spill off the coast
of Alaska. He predicted the effort would be ``massive, prolonged
and frustrating.''
   ``We all share the sorrow and concern of Alaskans,'' he said.
``Exxon's efforts standing alone are not enough.''
   Bush announced the decision during an appearance in the White
House briefing room at which he was accompanied by Cabinet members
and Alaskan members of Congress.
   Bush had been under pressure from members of Congress and
Alaskan officials to intervene in the oil spill cleanup.
   He said he had directed Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to ``make
available U.S. military forces personnel and equipment to assist in
the cleanup'' and Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner to
coordinate the whole operation.
   At the Pentagon, Defense Department officials said they had
postponed a decision on how many servicemen might be sent to Alaska
until a special assessment team ``determines the best way to apply
military support to the clean-up operation.''
   The Pentagon said its assessment team _ consisting of
engineering, environmental, medical and logistics specialists _
would depart for Valdez today. An Alaska Oil Spill Joint Task Force
was being established, headed by Lt. Gen. Thomas G., McInerney of
the Air Force, the commanding general of the Alaskan Air Command.
   The president insisted that ``We are not federalizing this
operation.''
   ``This should not relieve Exxon from any of its responsibilities
or liabilities,'' the president said.
   The Exxon tanker Valdez ran aground March 24, spilling 10
million gallons of crude oil into Prince William Sound. The captain
of the tanker, Joseph J. Hazelwood, has been charged in the
incident.
   ``A lot has been done,'' Bush said when asked why it had taken
the federal government so long to intervene.
   Asked whether he was satisified with the cleanup efforts thus
far, Bush said, ``I'm not satisfied with anything about it ... I
feel very, very strongly about the damage to our environment there,
so I'm not totally satisfied.''
   Bush, who made environmental issues a key theme of his
presidential campaign, said the oil spill was an ``aberration'' and
that it should not affect U.S. oil exploration.
   ``I am not going to suggest that because of this that we should
rethink a policy of trying to get this country less dependent on
foreign oil,'' the president said.
   ``Our ultimate goal must be the complete restoration of the
ecology and the economy of Prince William Sound, including all of
its fish, marine mammals, birds and other wildlife.''
   He conceded the job ``will be massive, prolonged and
frustrating. Nothing we can do will resolve this problem in the
short term.''
   Throughout his remarks, Bush reiterated that Exxon bears the
ultimate responsibility for the oil spill. ``In addition to paying
damage claims against it, we urge Exxon to increase its local
hiring for the cleanup effort,'' he said.
   Bush also said he had directed White House staff to develop
plans to ``enable volunteers to participate in cleanup activities''
and that he hoped such a program would be in effect by summer.
   ``I kind of think the president has told the fishermen if they
want economic relief they should join the army,'' said Valdez Mayor
John Devens after watching Bush on television from his Washington
hotel room. ``He showed a lack of sensitivity as to what has
happened economically.''
   Even as Bush was announcing an increased federal effort, Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, was telling colleagues he
finds it alarming that the administration waited so long.
   ``A federal takeover of the cleanup effort was warranted after
it became clear on the day of the accident that Alyeska (the oil
pipeline service company) and Exxon had not respond in the manner
called for by the contingency plan and did not have sufficient
equipment available to contain the spill,'' Mitchell said.
   Witnesses at congressional hearings Thursday testified that
neither the industry nor the government was prepared for the
environmental disaster created by the oil spill.
   During a Senate hearing, Adm. Paul Yost, commandant of the Coast
Guard, cautioned against federal control.
   ``I am not prepared to federalize this spill,'' Yost said,
adding that such a move might leave it open for Exxon ``to close
their checkbook'' and force the government to assume cleanup costs.
   Yost did say that the Coast Guard was assuming greater direction
over the Exxon Corp.'s cleanup efforts, such as how it goes about
the cleanup, what equipment it uses and what the cleanup priorities
are.
   L.G. Rawls, chairman of Exxon Corp., told the Senate panel that
the petroleum giant ``will continue doing all we can to clean up
and mitigate the spill's effects.''
   Rawls maintained that the federal government should share some
of the blame for early delays in the cleanup because authorities
refused to approve use of a chemical dispersal agent until nearly
three days after the spill began.
   Yost defended the decision not to approve use of the chemical
and said Exxon only had ``a few thousand gallons'' of the chemical.
He called that amount a ``drop in the bucket'' given the size of
the spill.
   But he criticized Exxon for moving too slowly in the hours
immediately after the accident.
   A fisherman, choking back tears, described the disappointment
the Prince William Sound community felt toward Exxon's efforts.
   ``We expected Exxon to mobilize and clean up the spill and
assist the Sound communities with recovery efforts,'' said Pete
Isleib. ``The truth is that the people of Cordova reached into
their own treasury and began protecting uncontaminated areas of the
Sound while Exxon helped its out-of-town experts react.
   ``It is not a joke that the inevitable souvenir T-shirts were
deployed before the containment boom was around the Exxon Valdez.''
</TEXT>
