<FIRST>r i AM-Mandela     04-07 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandela,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandela Calls For Black Unity In Letter To Zulu Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jailed African National
Congress leader Nelson Mandela says he is deeply troubled by black
factional fighting, and he urged unity among anti-apartheid groups,
according to a letter released Friday.
   ``I consider it a serious indictment against all of us that we
are still unable to combine forces to stop the slaughter of so many
innocent lives,'' said the letter, released by Mangosuthu
Buthelezi, a Zulu leader at odds with the ANC.
   ``The (political) struggle is our life, and even though the
realization of our fondest dreams may not be at hand, we can
nevertheless make that struggle immensely enriching or absolutely
disastrous,'' according to the letter, which Buthelezi said he
received from Mandela last month.
   Buthelezi, leader of self-governing homeland of KwaZulu, read
the letter Thursday at the KwaZulu Legislative Assembly, one of the
few instances in recent years that Mandela has been quoted publicly.
   Mandela has been imprisoned since 1962 and is serving a life
sentence for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-run
government. There has been widespread speculation that he could be
released within the next year.
   Mandela, 70, was treated for tuberculosis last year and was
moved to a suburban-style house on the grounds of the Victor
Verster Prison outside Cape Town.
   The ANC wages a bombing and sabotage campaign in its bid to
undermine South Africa's government.
   Buthelezi opposes apartheid, the government's policy of racial
separation, but the ANC and other militant anti-apartheid
organizations say he is too conservative because he does not
support sanctions, strikes, demonstrations and other
confrontational methods of political resistance.
   Mandela's letter called for reconciliation between the ANC and
Buthelezi, who also heads Inkatha. a 1.5 million-member political
organization.
   ``My fervent hope is to see, in due course, the restoration of
the cordial relations which existed between you and O.R. (ANC
President Oliver R. Tambo), and between the two organizations in
the '70s,'' Mandela wrote to Buthelezi.
   Inkatha has been involved in vicious faction fighting in Natal
Province for the past two years with supporters of the banned
United Democratic Front, which is the country's largest
anti-apartheid coalition and a political ally of the ANC.
   More than 1,000 blacks have been killed in the battles around
the southeastern cities of Durban and Pietermaritzburg.
   ``In my entire political career few things have distressed me as
to see our people killing one another as is now happening,''
Mandela wrote.
   ``The most challenging task facing the (black) leadership today
is that of national unity,'' he added. ``At no other time in our
history has it become so crucial for our people to speak with one
voice.
</TEXT>
