<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Palme     04-07 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Palme,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial of Murder Suspect to Start May 29</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a 42-year-old man
suspected in the 1986 killing of Prime Minister Olof Palme will
start May 29, court officials said Friday.
   The trial of Christer Pettersson is expected to last at least
four weeks, they said.
   Pettersson, arrested Dec. 14, has denied he shot Palme.
   Prosecutors said they have enough evidence to try Pettersson,
who has a previous manslaughter conviction, a long record of petty
crime and a history of mental disturbance and drug and alcohol
abuse.
   The prosecutors said they plan to file charges within a month
but declined to say what the exact charges will be.
   Palme, shot Feb. 28, 1986, was a controversial figure at home
and abroad, a committed socialist and a champion of Third World
liberation movements. The killing stunned Sweden, where no
political leader had been slain for 200 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
