<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have released one of
the five kidnappers of Dutch beer baron Alfred Heineken after
serving two-thirds of his sentence, the Justice Ministry said.
   Martin Erkamp, 25, who in 1984 got an eight-year jail term, was
freed on parole late last month, a ministry spokesman said Thursday
in exchange for anonymity in line with ministry practice.
   The kidnapping of Heineken and his chauffer, Ab Doderer,
captivated the nation for three weeks in November 1983. The two
were freed unharmed after the reported payment of $11.5 million.
Four-fifths of the ransom has reportedly been recovered.
   Three kidnappers remain in jail, serving terms of 10 to 12
years, while the fifth is on the loose after escaping from a
psychiatric hospital more than four years ago.
   On Thursday, the 65-year-old Heineken, one of the Netherlands'
wealthiest people, announced he would retire this summer as
chairman of his brewery's board.
