<FIRST>r a AM-ExxonBacklash     04-07 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Backlash,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Urge Protests Against Exxon Because Of Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut lawmaker is urging consumers to boycott Exxon
products May 2 to protest the Alaska oil spill, and other
environmentalists are urging their own protests.
   ``Many people are outraged and frustrated over this incident,''
state Sen. Michael Meotti said Thursday. ``This is an oportunity
for everyone, as consumers in the free marketplace, to make a point
to Exxon.''
   In Erie, Pa., a couple are trying to organize an ongoing
boycott. And in Florida, marine biologist Jack Rudlow had a more
direct way of making his point. He packed his Exxon credit cards in
an oil-filled plastic bag Thursday and mailed them to the company.
   Rudloe, an author and environmental activist from Panacea, Fla.,
said he hoped others would join his protest.
   ``It makes a very interesting package to see this Exxon card
swilling around in black oil, and I think it gets the point
across,'' he said. ``They say a picture is worth a thousand words,
and this beats all the rhethoric.''
   The protests come two weeks after the tanker Exxon Valdez ran
aground in Alaska's Prince William Sound, disgorging 10.1 million
gallons of crude oil. Alaska officials, who are angry with Exxon's
handling of the cleanup, said Thursday that less than 4 percent of
the oil has been recovered.
   Exxon Chairman L.G. Rawl, in a statement to a congressional
committee Thursday, again apologized on behalf of his company for
the spill, but said Exxon's response was ``immediate and thorough.''
   In Erie, Pa., Mary Machuga, 34, said she and her husband, Mike,
38, began campaigning for a boycott this week out of frustration
and have been getting messages of support.
   ``We have not been real activists, but we finally decided it's
time to do something,'' she said. ``And, luckily, people from all
over the country have felt the same way.''
   Meotti said he is working with Connecticut environmental groups
to spread word of the one-day boycott. He said the economic impact
on Exxon may be small, but the gesture will send a clear message.
