<TEXT>
   Marlee Matlin, who won an Oscar in 1986
for her performance in ``Children of a Lesser God,'' says speaking
at last year's Academy Awards signaled a dramatic change in her
career.
   The deaf actress, 23, said she had been afraid to pursue roles
that required her to speak until she decided to present the
nominees for best actor last year by talking instead of using sign
language.
   Her action was criticized by some hearing impaired
organizations, who argued that she gave the impression that every
deaf person could speak.
   ``I felt sad for those individuals who did not or would not
respect me for what I did, but I decided I'm not going to let other
people change me,'' Matlin said in Friday's editions of The
Nashville Banner.
   Matlin's newest film, ``Bridge To Silence,'' was an added
challenge, said the actress, who has been deaf since the age of 19
months.
   ``It was a great deal different because I've never acted and
spoke at the same time,'' she said. ``And I would do it again and
again and again if I was offered the opportunity.''
