<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Strike     04-07 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Strike,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Longshoremen Strike Over Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 Japanese longshoremen demanding pay
raises and shorter working hours have gone on strike, halting
container shipping at nine ports, union officials said Friday.
   The strike that began Wednesday at container yards at ports
including Yokohama, Kobe and Osaka blocked the entrance and exit of
290,000 tons of containers a day, said Masaya Tamada, a labor union
spokesman for the National Council of Dockworkers Unions of Japan.
   ``Although other sections at each port are functioning normally,
the halt of containers would affect people's everyday life because
the circulation of goods, from foodstuffs to machinery, stops,''
Tamada added.
   There are 150,000 longshoremen in Japan. The Japan Port and
Harbor Association's labor union has 50,000 members, according to
Tamada.
   The union demanded a $303 to $380 increase in monthly salaries,
or a $1,970 monthly salary for the average worker. The Japan Harbor
Transportation Association, composed of 1,600 employers, offered
$1,700, Tamada said.
</TEXT>
