<FIRST>r a AM-ColombianJudge     04-07 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombian Judge,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Judge Sues Detroit News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian judge brought to the United States by
the Drug Enforcement Agency to protect her from a Colombian drug
lord has sued The Detroit News, claiming the newspaper defamed her.
   Judge Consuelo Sanchez-Duran and her husband, Augusto Sanabria,
seek at least $10,000 in the lawsuit, filed Thursday in Wayne
County Circuit Court.
   The lawsuit claims a Feb. 12 story defamed the couple and
endangered their lives.
   The story said Sanchez-Duran left Colombia after her life was
threatened for ordering the arrest of Pablo Escobar, head of
Colombia's largest cocaine ring. It also said the judge had 24-hour
guards paid by the U.S. government.
   Escobar hasn't been arrested and is believed to be in Colombia.
He also has been indicted in the United States.
   The story quoted a ``highly placed source'' as saying a team of
15 elite police officers had been assigned to protect the judge. It
also said tenants of the apartment building in which she lives are
concerned over her presence.
   Sanchez-Duran claimed the story ``was unnecessary and dangerous,
recklessly placing (the couple) and the general public in a
position of harm.''
   The lawsuit names columnist Pete Waldmeir and News Executive
Editor Robert H. Giles. A woman who answered the telephone in
Giles' office Friday said the newspaper hasn't been served notice
of the lawsuit.
   At the time the story was published, Giles said the News
believed it did the right thing.
   ``You balance whatever the presumed risk to the judge against
whether the community needs to know about this, ... and there was
no question'' to run the story, he said.
   The newspaper printed the name of the apartment complex where
she was living. ``We recognized that many of the people in the
current Detroit location already knew she was there,'' Giles said.
</TEXT>
