<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Spain-Satellites     04-07 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Spain-Satellites,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spain Approves $370 Million Satellite Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday approved its first
communications satellite program at a cost of $370 million, as
Spain prepares for its Summer Olympics and world's fair in 1992.
   The plan calls for three Hispasat satellites whose
telecommunications and television range would cover Spain and most
of Latin America and the United States, said Transport and
Communications Minister Jose Barrionuevo.
   Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez's socialist government has placed
high priority on modernizing communications before the 1992 Summer
Olympics in Barcelona and Seville's Expo '92, a world's fair to
commemorate Christopher Columbus' voyage to the New World.
   The first satellite will be launched in December 1991 and the
second in April 1992, with the third held in reserve, Barrionuevo
said.
   Companies in the running to build the satellites include Hughes
Aerospace of the United States. The U.S. Titan or Delta rockets or
the French-built Ariane will launch them.
