<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-Cambodia     04-07 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Calls For UN Supervision of Vietnamese Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Khmer Rouge, which governed
Cambodia by famine and massacre before the Vietnamese invaded a
decade ago, urged on Friday that the United Nations supervise
Vietnam's troop withdrawal.
   It also demanded the Hanoi-sponsored government of Cambodia be
replaced by a coalition including the three resistance factions, of
which the Khmer Rouge is the most powerful.
   Fear of the Khmer Rouge regaining power has been at the heart of
negotiations for a settlement.
   France accepted a request from Prince Norodom Sihanouk, once
Cambodia's ruler and now leader of the resistance alliance, that it
hold an international conference on the future of Cambodia.
Sihanouk also has recommended U.N. supervision of the withdrawal.
   Vietnam said Wednesday would pull out of Cambodia by Sept. 30
after nearly 11 years of occupation, and urged that China and other
countries stop aiding the resitance.
   The occupation blocks diplomatic relations with the United
States, from which Hanoi hopes to get aid, and hinders trade
relations with non-communist neighbors. China has linked withdrawal
to resumption of normal relations with the Soviet Union, Vietnam's
ally.
   A statement Wednesday by Vietnam, Laos and the Cambodian
government of Premier Hun Sen proposed that India, Poland and
Canada monitor departure. It rejected demands that the Hun Sen
administration be dissolved.
   In its first statement on the Vietnamese plan, the Khmer Rouge
said through its clandestine radio that ``the entire Cambodian
people absolutely cannot accept the announcement of a unilateral
troop pullout of the Hanoi Vietnamese aggressors.''
   Vietnamese soldiers entered Cambodia in December 1978 and ousted
the Khmer Rouge, under whose rule of less than four years an
estimated one-fourth of Cambodia's 8 million people were executed
or died of hunger.
   Western intelligence sources estimate Khmer Rouge strength at
20,000 to 40,000 fighters, far more than the Khmer People's
National Liberation Front and forces led by Sihanouk.
   Hanoi has withdrawn about half its troops from Cambodia and says
50,000 remain. Western analysts put the number at about 70,000.
   The Khmer Rouge broadcast, in a statement attributed to its
leader Khieu Samphan, accused Hanoi of trying to avoid U.N.
supervision so it can keep soldiers in Cambodia secretly. It also
proposed the coalition of Hun Sen's government and the resistance
groups.
   Resistance leaders oppose Poland as a monitor because of its
ties to the Soviet Union, and India has recognized the Hun Sen
government.
   ``Without genuine supervision by the United Nations, there would
be no genuine withdrawal of Vietnamese troops,'' the Khmer Rouge
radio said.
   Vietnam and its client government in Phnom Penh oppose U.N.
supervision because Sihanouk's coalition has been given the
Cambodian seat in the General Assembly.
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas said in Paris that France was
willing to sponsor an international conference on Cambodia after
another round of talks by the Cambodian factions. Two meetings have
been held Jakarta, Indonesia, without substantial results.
   Sihanouk said Thursday the conference should include Vietnam,
the Cambodian factions, the six member nations of the non-communist
Association of Southeast Asian Nations and the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council: the United States, Soviet
Union, China, Britain and France.
</TEXT>
