<DOCNO> AP890407-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-North     04-07 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-North,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Refuses to Talk About Contra Aid Involvement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush repeatedly refused on Friday to
talk about a written government admission that he took part in the
Reagan administration's secret Contra aid operation, saying he
wanted to avoid ``endangering the trial'' of Oliver North.
   Bush rebuffed reporters' questions, saying any comment from him
could prejudice the federal trial of North, the former White House
aide who is accused of lying and obstructing Congress about his
efforts to assist the Nicaraguan rebels.
   ``I am not going to comment on any aspect of the North trial
while it's in progress,'' Bush said at a White House
question-and-answer session. ``If I even comment on your question,
it could prejudice the trial.''
   He declared, ``The legal process ought to run unfettered without
you or me endangering the trial process. And that's the last
question I will take on that subject.''
   Bush deflected two later attempts to get his response to a
lengthy statement introduced at North's trial on Thursday. Parts of
the statement disclosed that Bush, while vice president, saw
several North memoranda involving the secret U.S. effort to aid the
Contras.
   The court summary of facts, introduced by North's attorneys and
agreed to by the government, also stated that Bush met in 1985 with
then-President Roberto Suazo of Honduras to tell him U.S. aid to
his country was being expedited.
   At the time, the administration was engaged in efforts to ensure
Honduras continued its key role in supporting the Contras while
Congress had forbidden U.S. aid to the rebels fighting the
government of Nicaragua.
   The expedited aid to Honduras was part of a secret agreement
calling for that nation, in return, to help the Contras, according
to the court summary.
   There was no indication that Bush mentioned this linkage when he
met with Suazo.
   Bush said Friday it would be imprudent for him to discuss the
matter. He also said, however that the material from the court
document has ``been available to the independent counsel and the
Iran-Contra committees and reviewed by them for any special
significance.''
   ``I've said all I want to say about it, because I really believe
on the advice of lawyers that that's the last thing we ought to do
is even be kicking it around,'' he said, his voice rising. ``So
please accept it when I said I don't want to talk about it any more
and I'm not going to.''
   Bush has denied knowing at the time about any diversion of Iran
arms-sales proceeds to the Contras, although he has acknowledged
knowing about the clandestine arms sales to Iran. He has said he
was not familiar with details of the Contra supply effort.
   In a speech just over a week after the Iran-Contra affair became
public at the end of 1986, Bush said he had supported the Iran arms
sales but, ``I was not aware of _ and oppose _ any diversion of
funds, any ransom payments or any circumvention of the will of the
Congress.''
   Meanwhile on Friday, House Speaker Jim Wright said Bush's role
in covert support for the Contras shouldn't damage evolving
bipartisan cooperation on foreign policy between Congress and the
White House.
   ``We're not going to permit anything that happened in the past
to interfere with what happens in the future,'' Wright, D-Texas,
told reporters following a speech in which he extolled
bipartisanship in U.S. policy toward Central America.
   ``That does not imply approval, or sanction'' of Bush's past
role as disclosed in the North trial statement, Wright said.
   The court document is preceded by a heading stating, ``The
United States has admitted for purposes of this trial the following
facts to be true.''
   It shows that Bush met with Suazo at a time when the Hondurans
had shown reluctance to continue helping the Contras.
   The Reagan administration, in part through special offers of
assistance, was trying to enlist Honduras and Nicaragua's three
other Central American neighbors to give the Contras weapons,
facilitate armament deliveries and allow use of their lands to be
used for such crucial Contra needs as aircraft landing zones.
   In early March 1985, Bush asked National Security Adviser Robert
McFarlane whether Bush should ``encourage a private group to donate
a planeload of medical supplies that would arrive in Honduras
coincident with'' Bush's meeting with Suazo.
   ``Bush strongly favored such a flight,'' the document said,
``noting that the (unidentified) group was supportive of the
resistance.'' It said North told McFarlane that Bush's idea was
sound. The document did not reveal whether the planeload of
supplies actually arrived.
</TEXT>
