<SECOND>AM-People-Grateful Dead,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cincinnati Beefs Up Police Presence for Grateful Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city will beef up police presence at
Saturday night's Grateful Dead concert because of violence this
week at concerts in Pittsburgh.
   Thirty-three officers will be at Riverfront Coliseum, along with
82 security officers and 60 ushers, said Dave Rager, the city's
assistant safety director.
   Some fans already were in town Thursday. Most of the 16,144
tickets sold went to out-of-towners, with almost 7,000 pre-sold to
``Dead Heads,'' as the group's ardent fans are called.
   ``Dead Heads'' often camp out at concerts and trade tapes and
souvenirs. City and Riverfront Coliseum officials planned to set up
a makeshift campground Friday night.
   Police in Pittsburgh arrested 55 people, mostly on public
intoxication and drug charges, at Grateful Dead concerts Sunday and
Monday. Pittsburgh police clashed Monday night with a crowd of more
than 500 who had surrounded the Civic Arena but did not have
concert tickets.
   The Grateful Dead band directed letters to ``Dead Heads'' to
inform them of Cincinnati's makeshift camping arrangement.
Riverfront Coliseum and the Cleveland-based Belkin Productions,
promoter for the Cincinnati concert, also printed fliers to inform
fans of the camping arrangements.
