<DOCNO> AP890407-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ScandalRating     04-07 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scandal Rating,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Movie Rating Board Sticks to X-Rating for `Scandal' Flick</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's movie rating board has stuck to
the X rating slapped on ``Scandal,'' about the 1960s Profumo affair
that toppled a British government, despite appeals from the
moviemaker.
   The Motion Picture Association of America's appeals board voted
Thursday in New York to sustain the X rating, an action viewed as
box office poison because few theaters show such films and
advertisements are difficult to place.
   ``Scandal'' distributor Miramax Films recruited First Amendment
attorney Martin Garbus to state its case.
   Garbus conceded ``Scandal'' was a sexy film, but argued that if
British audiences could see it so should American moviegoers.
   The appeals board voted 8-7 to retain the X rating. A two-thirds
vote of the appeals board is required to overturn an MPAA rating.
   Miramax lawyer Dan Zinkin said the close vote was unusual,
noting the board is usually unanimous. He suspected the highly
erotic content in an orgy scene guided those voting for X.
   The MPAA doesn't disclose reasons for its rating decisions.
   Miramax must now decide whether to keep the X rating, reject it
and go out unrated, or cut the offending orgy scene and resubmit it
to the MPAA.
   Harvey Weinstein, co-chairman of the film company, said only
that Miramax was ``currently examining legal options and consulting
with their attorneys.''
   ``Scandal'' recreates the torrid Profumo affair that brought
down the conservative government of Harold Macmillan in 1963.
   The movie, based on the Phillip Knightley and Carolyn Kennedy
book called ``An Affair of State: The Profumo Case and the Framing
of Stephen Ward,'' features philandering politicians, call girls,
Soviet spies and the sex party.
   The story surrounds the liaisons between call girl Christine
Keeler, war minister John Profumo and Soviet operative Eugene
Ivanov.
   British critics loved the movie, but politicians condemned it
for raking up memories of the affair that forced a minister to
resign, caused Ivanov's recall and led to the suicide of Ward, a
prominent osteopath.
   The movie stars Joanne Whalley-Kilmer as Ms. Keeler, John Hurt
as Ward, Ian McKellen as Profumo and Britt Ekland as Mariella
Novotny, a brothel keeper.
   Roy Hattersley, deputy leader of the opposition Labor Party,
said the movie ``seems to be a disgrace to our society.'' But
London's Daily Mail praised the picture.
   ``This account of the Profumo affair is the most accomplished
British commercial film in a long time _ fluent, engrossing, racing
along the story capsuled long ago in that headline ``The Minister,
The Model and The Russian Spy,''' the Daily Mail said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Foreign-Travel-Cohen     04-07 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign-Travel-Cohen,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokeswoman Says Maine Senator Will File Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, will file a
report required by federal law stating that the East German
government paid for one night's lodging at a conference he attended
in June 1987, his spokeswoman said Friday.
   Cohen was one of at least a handful of members of the House and
Senate who neglected to report travel expenses picked up by foreign
governments as required under the 1978 Foreign Gifts and
Decorations Act, The Associated Press reported this week.
   Several lawmakers said they were unaware of the law or confused
about its requirements. It calls for any gifts or travel expenses
paid by foreign governments to be reported on a form. Senators must
report gifts over $100; House members have a ceiling of $180.
   Cohen's spokeswoman, Kathy Gest, said information just received
from the American Embassy in East Germany indicated the cost of the
hotel was $132.40, $32.40 over the $100 filing limit. As a result,
she said, Cohen would file under the foreign gifts act.
   ``It would be naive to think that anyone would intentionally
violate the law for that amount of money,'' she said. ``We were
originally under the impression that no form was required.''
   She said the incident raises questions about some of the
provisions of the law and its clarity.
   Cohen was invited to the conference by the Institute for
East-West Security Studies, a non-profit group in New York that did
not specify the East Germans would pay for the lodging.
   Rep. Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., another conference participant,
estimated three nights in Potsdam cost $400.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., has also filed a form, indicating that
the governments of New Zealand and Australia paid for ground
transportation on a trip to those places in January 1987, said Mark
Bowen, his spokesman.
   Others on the trips who did not file were Sens. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa, Larry Pressler, R-S.D., and then-Sen. John Melcher, D-Mont.
   Failure to file within 30 days carries a penalty, on conviction,
of $5,000, plus the cost of the expenses.
   But officials of the Senate and House ethics committees say they
do not know of anyone being charged for failing to report travel
expenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
