<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0668,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot at Al Aqsa Mosque; Palestinians React Coolly to Election Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf ``A similar ...'' to UPDATE with
settlers stoning Arab cars; Gaza wounded; INSERTS 2 grafs after second-last
pvs, ``Police said ...'' to ADD mayor's comment.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Palestinians rioted and stoned
police Friday outside Al Aqsa Mosque after midday prayers on the
first day of Ramadan, the Moslem holy month.
   Police responded with rubber bullets and tear gas. At least five
policemen, three Palestinians and several journalists were hurt.
   The hour-long battle on Temple Mount _ known to Moslems as Haram
al Sharif, or Noble Sanctuary _ was the worst violence in a year at
the third holiest site of Islam. Clouds of tear gas rose from the
hilltop in Jerusalem's Old City dominated by the Al Aqsa and Dome
of the Rock mosques.
   A leaflet distributed by the Moslem fundamentalist Hamas (Zeal)
movement urged Palestinians to welcome Ramadan by escalating their
16-month-old uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   At least 37 Palestinians were arrested. Police commander Yosef
Yehudai said most were from the West Bank and Arab east Jerusalem.
   A similar protest occurred at Hebron in the West Bank. Hundreds
of worshipers chanting nationalist slogans stoned soldiers, who
opened fire, wounding four Palestinians. The army put the city
under curfew.
   Jewish settlers in Hebron hurled stones at Arab-owned vehicles,
retaliating for similar Arab attacks, Israel radio said.
   In Gaza Strip, Israeli troops shot and wounded two Palestinian
teen-agers during a riot, Arab hospital officials said.
   The violence came one day after President Bush supported Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's proposal for residents of the occupied
lands to elect representatives to negotiate with Israel.
   Influential Palestinians greeted the idea coolly and said it
must be part of a broader program, including promises to end the
occupation and trade land for peace. Israel captured the West Bank
and Gaza from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war.
   Hanna Siniora, editor of the daily Al Fajr, said the uprising,
in which 420 Palestinians and 18 Israelis have been slain, would
continue ``until Shamir comes up with a better proposal.''
   His paper supports the Palestine Liberation Organization, with
which Israel refuses to deal.
   While Siniora and other moderates expressed skepticism about
Shamir's motivation, they left the door open to further
discussions. Palestinian hard-liners ruled out elections.
   Shamir said on Israel radio Friday there ``appears to be a full
understanding'' between him and Bush. He made little of their
differences, including Bush's call for an end to Israeli occupation.
   Rioting began in Jerusalem after about 25,000 worshipers
attended noon prayers on the first day of Ramadan, the Moslem month
of daytime fasting and religious fervor.
   Israeli officials have expressed fear of an escalation of the
uprising during Ramadan, which marks the month the prophet Mohammed
began receiving the holy Koran from Allah.
   Al Aqsa is an important national symbol to Palestinians and the
Dome of the Rock marks the spot from which, in Islamic belief,
Mohammed ascended to heaven on his horse.
   The 35-acre rectangular platform on which the mosque coplex is
built also is the site of the ancient Jewish Temple, the holiest
shrine of Judaism, which the Romans destroyed in the year 70.
   About 4,000 worshipers stayed behind in the mosque complex after
prayers Friday, police said.
   They chanted ``Allahu Akbar!'' _ ``God is great!'' _ and
``Palestine is Moslem!'' They also waved five larged Palestinian
flags and burned two Israeli flags. Palestinian flags are illegal
in Israel.
   At first, only a few Palestinians threw stones at the hundreds
of police arrayed outside the courtyard walls. Then a policeman
fired a shot into the air.
   ``This shot led to the great confusion,'' said Moshe Nussbaum,
an Israel radio reporter. ``Seconds after the shot was fired, we
were barraged by stones.''
   Rocks pelted dozens of journalists who had observed the prayers
from an adjacent rooftop.
   Wolfgang Scheider, a cameraman for Austrian TV, was struck in
the head and collapsed, blood streaming down his face.
   Police fired rubber bullets and hundreds of tear gas canisters
over the wall, then entered to arrest demonstrators.
   At the Wailing Wall, which lines one side of the complex, the
ground was littered with stones. The area was devoid of the Jewish
worshipers who normally crowd the site.
   Jerusalem Mayor Teddy Kollek said: ``If they continue to exploit
the Temple Mount's sanctity for riots and harm worship at the
Western (Wailing) Wall, Israel will know how to deal with them.''
   Police said they would increase security and keep some
Palestinians away from mosques.
</TEXT>
