<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     04-07 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Gunners Bombard Christian Region, Violate Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners fired 11 howitzer shells
into Lebanon's Christian-held regions Friday, violating a fragile
cease-fire. Police said no casualties were reported.
   A police spokesman said eight Soviet-designed 130mm shells
slammed into sandy beaches near the Christian port of Jounieh north
of Beirut early Friday.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified in line with standing
rules, said three other Syrian-fired shells exploded near the
Christian suburb of Hadeth on Beirut's southeastern edge Friday
afternoon.
   Police put the casualty toll at 177 people killed and 591
wounded in the monthlong confrontation between Gen. Michel Aoun's
20,000 Christian troops and an alliance of Syrian and Druse forces.
   The confrontation exacerbated a political crisis that created
competing Christian and Moslem governments and split the army on
sectarian lines.
   Syria has 40,000 troops in Lebanon and has become the country's
main power broker during the long civil war. Aoun has declared a
``war of liberation'' against the Syrians.
   The truce was called Wednesday by Kuwait's foreign minister,
Sheik Sabah Ahmed Sabah, who heads an Arab League committee on
Lebanon.
   Despite the limited cease-fire violations, most residents around
Beirut remained huddled in basements and underground shelters to
avoid a sudden outbreak of hostilities.
   ``One can't predict what might happen,'' said Adel Bohsali, a
spare parts dealer in Moslem west Beirut. ``I'm keeping my wife and
two sons in the basement _ or close to it.''
   Syrian and Christian gunners briefly broke the truce at midday
Thursday with a mortar and rocket duel that wounded 15 people.
   Aoun has formally rejected the truce, but a spokesman for Aoun
said the general would ``not respond to the Syrian provocative fire
if it remains within bearable limits.'' The spokesman, who cannot
be named under standing procedure, would not define those limits.
   Aoun has urged all Lebanese factions to meet to settle to the
14-year-old civil war.
   Nabih Berri, who heads the mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal
militia, rejected Aoun's offer and urged the Syrians to maintain
their troops in Lebanon.
   Lebanon's latest political crisis began Sept. 22, when
Parliament could not agree on a successor to President Amin Gemayel
at the end of his six-year term and Gemayel named Aoun to head an
interim government.
   Moslems rejected the appointment and swore allegiance to Salim
Hoss, the Sunni Moslem premier who led the government during
Gemayel's administration.
   Under an unwritten national covenant dating to independence from
France in 1943, Lebanon's president is a Christian, the premier a
Sunni and the Parliament speaker a Shiite Moslem.
   The confrontation broke out March 8, after Aoun ordered a
blockade of the private ports with which Moslem militias finance
their operations.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's militia rejected the decision and
started shelling the Christian-held regions. Syrian troops later
joined in.
</TEXT>
