<FIRST>r i AM-SwissWatches     04-07 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swiss Watches,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss Watchmaking Birthplace Holds Sale Expected To Raise Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This birthplace of Swiss watchmaking on Sunday
will be the site of an auction of 301 timepieces that organizers
expect will bring in millions of dollars.
   A team of watchmakers took nine years to design and assemble the
1,278 parts of the top item, said auctioneer Osvaldo Patrizzi.
   The exposition, ``Calibre 89,'' has been viewed by nearly 10,000
potential buyers and watch fans on a pre-sale world tour with stops
in Europe, the United States, Japan, Hong Kong and Singapore.
   Made by Patek Philippe, the Geneva watchmaking company to mark
its 150th anniversary, the 18-carat, 3.4-inch-diameter gold case
packs 68 springs, 126 jewels and 332 screws.
   The parts include a wheel that turns once in a century and a
lever that moves every four years to make sure that the watch's
calendar skips a leap year date.
   It is the first watch in the world that determines the date of
Easter, which varies, and also features a disc of sapphire crystal
showing the Milky Way and 2,800 stars in five sizes according to
their order of magnitude.
   Patrizzi, watch expert of the Habsburg, Feldman auctioneers
organizing the sale, said he was sure buyer interest would push the
price to between $3 and $6 million. To date, the highest price paid
for an auctioned timepiece was $1.2 million in 1984 for a mid-17th
century clock.
   Patek Philippe's ``Packard'' watch, one of the world's first
major complicated timepieces, was bought by American automobile
tycoon James Ward Packard in 1927 for $3,100. It was bought back by
the company for its own collection 61 years later for more than
$1.2 million.
   The sale of ``Calibre 89'' winds up the auction held before an
expected capacity audience of 700 in the ballroom of one of
Geneva's plushest hotels, the lakeside century-old Hotel de
Bergues. Hundreds of others can follow the sale in three other
rooms by closed-circuit television.
   The 300 other watches are also all by Patek Philippe. Several
are more than 100 years old and 34 are expected to fetch between
$60,000 and $600,000. All are pictured with detailed pedigree in a
catalogue in English and Japanese which sells for $60.
</TEXT>
