</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What began as an experiment in domestic
animal behavior at Texas Tech University has evolved into a
snout-to-snout competition in which pigs go for the gold _ a golden
bowl of corn meal mush, that is.
   When these porcine athletes run a 40-yard dash in the dirt of an
indoor arena Saturday there will be no brand-name running shoes and
no sporty uniforms, just sleek bodies, hairy legs and a team number
on each ear. The hog race is being held in conjunction with the
Little International livestock judging contest, where non-experts
practice judging livestock events.
   The 18 12-week-old animals racing to bring home the bacon are
part of an experiment in assistant animal science Professor John
McGlone's domestic animal behavior class, where students learn how
and why animals react in different situations.
   And everyone has his or her own training technique.
   ``I'd like to think I have the edge,'' said Eric Fugate, an
native of Fairbury, Ill. He boasts about his mysterious training
program, which features ``a secret recipe which is 100 percent
organic, no additives, no preservatives, no drugs.''
