<FIRST>r a AM-Right-To-Die 1stLd-Writethru a0716 04-07 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Right-To-Die, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0716,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stabbing Victim Dies; Prosecutors Weigh Homicide Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `While her...', to add length of time Pagan
spent in prison.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assailant who lost a court battle to
block his comatose victim from being removed from life support
could face a murder charge now that the man has died, prosecutors
said Friday.
   Twenty-six-year-old Mark Weaver died Friday, eight days after
his family removed his feeding tube and four years after the
stabbing that left him in a coma. Noel Pagan, who pleaded guilty to
assaulting Weaver, waged an unsuccessful court battle to keep him
alive to avoid risking more serious charges.
   ``We haven't ruled anything in or out,'' the chief of the
attorney general's criminal division, Fernand LaRochelle, said when
asked Friday whether homicide charges would be sought. ``We're just
trying to determine what the evidence is.''
   A medical examiner was performing an autopsy at Maine Medical
Center, but authorities did not know how soon it would be
completed. Attorney General James E. Tierney would not comment on
the type of autopsy findings would be necessary before Pagan could
be charged with Weaver's death.
   ``I'm not going to answer any hypothetical questions about an
autopsy being conducted,'' Tierney said.
   Weaver's mother, Sylvia Lane, said her son died at about 2 a.m.
   ``He died peacefully,'' she said. ``He never had a moment's
pain.''
   When she removed her son's feeding tube just after midnight
March 30, she had said it would take from one to two weeks for him
to die.
   Pagan's attorney, Robert Mullen, said he would try to persuade
prosecutors that no additional charges should be filed.
   ``It's up to them,'' Mullen said. ``I'll probably call them and
say, now that he's passed away, I'd like to do anything I can to
talk them out of charges.''
   While her son was still alive, Ms. Lane had said that it would
make no sense to seek further punishment of Pagan, who is now on
probation and living in Wellesley, Mass. Mullen said Pagan, 29, has
been staying out of trouble since his release after three years in
prison.
   Janet Mills, the Androscoggin County district attorney who
negotiated Pagan's guilty plea to an aggravated assault charge in
1985, said the stabbing occurred during a ``stupid street fight''
in Lewiston.
   Authorities believe Pagan and Weaver did not even know each
other, Ms. Mills said Friday from Auburn. ``It wasn't like one of
them set out to murder the other,'' she said. ``I think Weaver was
calling some names.''
   Mullen said that if charges are filed, he will try to get them
thrown out with motions instead of going to trial.
   He said he would cite constitutional provisions against trying
people twice for the same offense and a state law providing that a
person must die within a year and a day of an attack before the
attacker can be charged with murder or manslaughter.
</TEXT>
