<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev-Nuclear     04-07 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Nuclear,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Sheds Some Light on Nuclear Weapons Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's declared intention to close
facilities that produce weapons-grade radioactive material is the
first comment by a Soviet leader on an area that has been a deep
military secret.
   Under the Soviet leader's reform policies, and in arms
negotiations, some information has been given about conventional
forces, chemical weapons and nuclear missiles.
   He has used this more open attitude to press the United States
and its allies for arms control agreements Gorbachev needs to
redirect Soviet resources toward making the economy work.
   Until he spoke Friday in London, revelations about production of
uranium and plutonium for nuclear weapons remained off-limits.
   Gorbachev said: ``In addition to the industrial reactor for the
production of weapons-grade plutonium shut down in 1987, we plan to
shut down two other such reactors this year and next year without
commissioning new units to replace them.''
   The Soviet Union began allowing inspection of nuclear power
plants after the April 1986 explosion and fire at Chernobyl, which
killed at least 31 people and released a cloud of radiation that
spread around the world.
   It had not announced the closing of the reactor in 1987,
however, and no information had been available on what kinds of
facilities, or how many, the Soviets had for producing
weapons-grade material.
   ``U.S.S.R. Energy Atlas,'' a CIA study of all Soviet energy
sources, devotes only a little more than three of its 70 pages to
nuclear power because so much is concealed.
   ``Information on the Soviet uranium industry is a closely
guarded state secret,'' the report says. ``Only limited data on
uranium occurrences in the Soviet Union and minor details on
reserves, mining and processing operations have been published.''
   Francois Heisbourg, director of the Institute of Strategic
Studies in London, said after Gorbachev's announcement the Soviets
have a considerable stockpile of plutonium for nuclear weapon.
   Under the U.S.-Soviet treaty eliminating intermediate-range
nuclear missiles, U.S. inspectors have been given the unprecedented
right to inspect Soviet missile sites.
   Fifteen inspections were made last summer to verify deployment
sites and numbers and classes of weapons to be destroyed. Tass, the
official news agency, quoted Brig. Gen. Roland Lajoie as saying he
was ``staggered'' by the openness showed by the Soviets.
   In September, observers were allowed to witness a Soviet nuclear
test.
   Soviet officials have said that, after the U.S.-Soviet missile
treaty and Gorbachev's announcement at the United Nations in
December of unilateral military cuts, they are converting some arms
plants to produce goods for the domestic economy.
   Officials said Dec. 21 the engines from 10,000 decommissioned
tanks would be diverted to domestic use. Several weeks later, state
media reported that 250 arms plants would be incorporated into
efforts to design and build new food processing equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0187 </DOCNO>
