<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev-Glance     04-07 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Glance,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev's Visit to Britain, at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the highlights of Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's 40-hour visit to Britain that ended Friday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   In a major speech in London, Gorbachev announced cutbacks in
production of radioactive material for nuclear weapons. Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher said it was of no practical importance
because the Soviets already had all the material they needed.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Gorbachev said that if the West upgrades short-range nuclear
missiles in Europe, the arms control process could stall. Mrs.
Thatcher reiterated her belief in nuclear deterrence and said
modernization must proceed as planned.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Gorbachev invited Queen Elizabeth II to visit the Soviet Union,
and Mrs. Thatcher, who makes the final decision, said she was
delighted _ ``It is a very definite yes.'' The queen will be the
first British sovereign to visit the Soviet Union since the Russian
royal family, her cousins, were murdered after the 1917 Bolshevik
revolution.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A shadow fell over the summit as the Soviets confirmed _
following reports leaked by the U.S. administration _ that they
sold warplanes to Libya. Mrs. Thatcher complained to Gorbachev
about the sale to what she called a ``terrorist state,'' and said
later, ``We are deeply concerned.''

</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Gorbachev waded into crowds, first on Thursday after laying a
wreath at Westminster Abbey, and on Friday stopping his motorcade
in the middle of the City, London's financial district. Crowds were
delighted and so was Gorbachev, using a favorite tactic for wooing
Western opinion.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   He declared perestroika (restructuring) is irreversible. ``There
is no turning back for anyone. The people have firmly linked their
destiny with perestroika.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   He sampled British pageantry, lunching with the queen at
majestic Windsor Castle.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Gorbachev visited a high-tech factory outside London, and
appealed to business people to invest in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Mrs. Thatcher publicly acknowledged a marked improvement in
Soviet handling of human rights, thanked him for exit visas
recenlty granted to 15 refuseniks, but said others remained left
behind.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Both Soviet and British officials reported that rapport grew
between the two leaders, one a communist and one a conservative.
The British said the relationship reached ``a new high.'' Soviet
spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said, ``I am at a loss for words.''
</TEXT>
