<FIRST>r w AM-Farm-GAO     04-07 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm-GAO,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Says Current Law Has Bettered Farmers' Lot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report to Congress said Friday that current
farm law, which is set to expire next year, has helped improve the
state of U.S. agriculture.
   The General Accounting Office said the Food Security Act of 1985
was designed to help stabilize the farm economy, enhance U.S.
agricultural exports and prevent the buildup of large surplus
stocks of commodities.
   John W. Harman, GAO's director of food and agriculture issues,
said that in summary ``progress has been made toward the major
goals'' of the 1985 law.
   ``Most economic indicators have turned positive,'' Harman said.
``Exports have increased. And stock levels (of surplus commodities)
have generally moved lower.''
   But Harman said in his letter to Sens. Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.,
and Bill Bradley, D-N.J., who had asked for the GAO study, that
while the 1985 law has been a factor, ``it is uncertain how much
progress can be attributed to the legislation versus other
important factors such as monetary exchange rates.''
   The law includes a number of provisions that enabled the Reagan
administration to pursue its goal of ``market-oriented''
agriculture, including lower support prices for major farm
commodities so they could compete more easily in world trade.
   Similar goals have been expressed by the Bush administration,
including Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter, who has pushed
vigorously for more global elbow room for U.S. products.
   The report said that USDA's total costs for price and income
supports, and export programs were ``slightly higher under the
first three full years'' of the 1985 farm law than in the last
three full years of the previous legislation.
   Also, it said, USDA has had higher administrative costs
``because it increased staff levels to handle the greater work
load'' under the 1985 law. ``Even with more staff, USDA has found
its greater responsibilities difficult to administer,'' the report
added.
   The previous law, which was adopted in 1981, cost about $43.8
billion for its final three full years, compared with $48.7 billion
in the first three full years of the 1985 law, the report said.
   GAO said those figures did not include fiscal 1986 _ when total
farm commodity outlays were a record of $25.8 billion _ because it
was a transition year in which some spending were attributable to
crops produced under the 1981 law's programs and other crops under
the 1985 version.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
