<FIRST>r w AM-US-Lebanon     04-07 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Lebanon,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Praises Call By Lebanese Christian for Political Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Friday praised a call by
a leader of Lebanon's Christians for political reform, saying it
could open the way to resolving some of the fundamental problems
tearing the country apart.
   The comments appeared to indicate a State Department tilt toward
the Christians, who have been fighting a coalition of Moslem
militiamen and their Syrian backers in the worst round of civil
violence Lebanon has known for four years.
   It was the first time in the latest round of artillery duels,
which began four weeks ago, that the State Department has departed
from its language of neutrality.
   Gen. Michel Aoun, who leads the Christian units in Lebanon's
army, on Thursday called for a conference between the warring sides
to discuss power-sharing between Christians and Moslems.
   ``We have achieved equality in humiliation for 14 years,'' Aoun
said. ``We have to acquire equality today in responsibility,
liberation, dignity and partnership.''
   ``We have to be partners in making out destiny, because this
partnership alone is bound to realize justice, equality and equal
opportunities in a full national sense,'' he said.
   Aoun said the Lebanese will have to pay much more dearly if they
delay in achieving unity, security, dignity, stability and
reconstruction of their homeland.
   ``We welcome the commitment that General Aoun made,'' said the
State Department. ``We applaud his recognition that all Lebanese
have the right to security, liberty, and dignity.''
   Lebanon's factional violence stems from a political structure
instituted in the 1940s which favors the Christians over the
Moslems. But the Moslems, who have increased their numbers and now
constitute a majority in Lebanon, are demanding a bigger share in
running the country.
   Syria sent troops into Lebanon in 1976 under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate, but Lebanon's Christians contend the 40,000
Syrians are now an occupying power.
   ``We are required at once to reject subordination and to rebel
against the oppressive foreign will,'' Aoun said. ``We must
overthrow all dictated barriers and handicaps that would lead to
partition and meet around a Lebanese-Lebanese table for a free,
meaningful, open and honest national dialogue.''
   Richard Boucher, a State Department spokesman, said Aoun's call
is ``another step down the road'' to a settlement in Lebanon. But
he conceded that ``I can't say that we can be optimistic about the
situation. I think this shows a path to resolving some of the
fundamental problems that are there, and that's why we support it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
