<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru a0720 04-07 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Welcomes Step Toward Progress in Middle East Peace Process</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 14-17, bgng ``Later, in,'' to update with Shamir-CNN
and lift pvs next-to-last graf with background; recasts last graf for transition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp,Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, declaring that ``the climate
is better than it's been for a while,'' said Friday that the
election plan for Palestinian Arabs proposed by Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir represents a welcome step toward progress
in the Middle East peace process.
   Shamir, meantime, told reporters he sees no role for the
Palestine Liberation Organization in persuading the Arab residents
of the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza to take part in such
elections.
   ``In the Middle East, a little step sometimes can ... prove to
be fruitful,'' Bush said, adding that ``I think the climate is
better than it's been for a while.''
   Bush, answering questions from reporters at the White House,
said it is too early for him to consider traveling to the region to
try to resolve the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Asked if he saw himself getting personally involved over the
course of his presidency in trying to deal with the situation, Bush
said that ``if I felt that being immersed in it would help solve
the problem of peace in the Middle East, I would do that.''
   But he said that ``it is not a time when a lot of
high-visibility missions on the part of the president ... can be
helpful in the process.''
   As for the proposed elections, which Shamir suggested as a way
to select Arab delegates to meet with the Israeli government, Bush
was asked whether the PLO should have a role.
   Bush said that ``we haven't fully resolved exactly who's going
to have a role but I think that's a matter to be determined ...
between the parties. ... The PLO has people living on the West
Bank. ... We want to see elections that are free and fair there.''
   Shamir, speaking with reporters after meeting at the Capitol
with Senate leaders and members of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, made clear he intends to avoid PLO participation.
   ``I don't think the PLO could help,'' he said. ``I see the PLO
always as an obstacle on the way to peace in our area. The PLO is
against peace with us and therefore I cannot say anything about any
way the PLO could help.''
   Shamir was asked whether, in that case, elections represent a
dead end.
   He did not reply directly but said:
   ``As I said before, the PLO is against all of my proposals
because they don't want to see us _ to see Israel _ in peace
relations with the Arab peoples and nations. And therefore it is
useless to talk with the PLO.''
   Later, in an interview with Cable News Network, Shamir said that
elections can be held even if some of the Palestinian participants
are sympathetic to the PLO ``if these people will accept the
principle, ... accept the process of negotiations.''
   Shamir's plan calls for the election of Palestinian leaders to
negotiate temporary self-rule. After a trial period, he proposes to
have Israel, the Palestinians, Egypt and Jordan work out a
permanent settlement.
   Shamir told CNN the process would take ``at least five years,''
and that the initial period of self-rule would be ``a test to see
if it is possible to have peaceful coexistence.''
   The 1978 Camp David accords called for a five-year trial period
of Palestinian autonomy followed by negotiations for an overall
final settlement.
   Shamir presented his proposal to Bush on Thursday. At a news
conference, the prime minister ruled out having international
observers on hand for the elections which he said would be run by
Israeli officials.
   ``We do not think there is a need of international
supervision,'' he said. ``Israel has a long tradition of democracy
and decent and honest elections.''
   Shamir contends a majority of the 1.4 million Palestinian Arabs
living under Israeli control would take part in such elections
because they want a peaceful solution.
   Violence has held sway in the occupied lands since a Palestinian
uprising erupted in December 1987, killing 420 Palestinians and 18
Israelis.
   Shamir opposes establishment of an independent Palestinian state
on the West Bank and in Gaza, saying an Arab nation there would
become a launching pad for terrorist strikes against Israel.
</TEXT>
