<FIRST>r a AM-StillAlive     04-07 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Still Alive,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Claimed Wife Was Wrongfully Killed Has Two _ Both Alive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed the city was negligent in the
traffic death of his wife actually has two wives _ and both of them
are alive.
   Police began piecing together the saga of Robert Jerome Brown of
Dallas when he was arrested for auto theft last month.
   That started Texas and Arkansas officials on whirlwind
investigation that has uncovered suspects in an unsolved 1986
slaying, a phony identification of a traffic accident victim and
two wives _ one of whom says she was never near a Dallas freeway
accident that Brown contended had killed her.
   Brown, 33, and one of his wives, Sonja Brown, 20, remained
jailed Friday in Malvern, Ark., on capital murder charges stemming
from an unrelated incident.
   The two face arraignment on the capital murder charges Monday,
officials said.
   ``This is a very bizarre case,'' said homicide Detective James
Gallagher. ``If he didn't have this small problem with this
homicide case up in Arkansas, I'm sure we'd see quite a few more
charges against him.''
   In January 1988, Brown identified the body of a woman who was
struck and killed while walking across a Dallas highway as his
estranged wife, Jacquelyn Brown, 34, of Alport, Ark. When Brown
said he had no money to bury his wife, the body was placed in a
Dallas County pauper's grave.
   Then Brown allegedly hired an attorney to file a wrongful death
lawsuit against the city, claiming negligence in not placing a
street light in the area.
   But Brown's other wife, Sonja, tipped off Gallagher that there
might be something mysterious about Jacquelyn Brown's ``death.''
   Gallagher called Jacquelyn Brown's parents after reviewing her
death certificate and was startled to learn the woman was still
alive. He also learned the woman had been estranged from Brown for
several years but never divorced.
   ``Initially she was surprised,'' Gallagher said of Jacquelyn
Brown's reaction to the news of her reported death. ``But then when
I told her who had made these allegations, she wasn't too
surprised.''
   Calls from The Associated Press to Jacquelyn Brown's home in
Arkansas were not answered Friday.
   Brown, a Stuttgart, Ark., native who had been living in Dallas,
was apprehended March 3 while driving through Texas to Shreveport,
La. The car had been stolen in Arkansas, said Hot Springs (Ark.)
County Chief Deputy Leonard Tisdale.
   Under questioning by Arkansas officials, Brown confessed that he
and his wife Sonja had strangled a Little Rock prostitute in 1986
and left her body on Interstate 30, Tisdale said.
   The body of Gloria J. Reynolds, 24, was found about six miles
south of Malvern, just past a highway rest stop, on Dec. 4, 1986,
Tisdale said. She had been robbed of $50 and strangled with a belt.
   Gallagher said Dallas police began questioning Sonja Brown about
her alleged role in the murder and she admitted Brown had told her
he was somehow involved in Jacquelyn's ``death.''
   When Jacquelyn Brown was found alive, Dallas police began an
investigation into the real identity of the traffic accident victim.
   Gallagher said he is waiting for fingerprints to arrive from Los
Angeles to confirm who is in the grave.
   Gallagher said police believe Brown's motive in claiming the
unidentified body appears to be money from the lawsuit against the
city, but he never followed up on the suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
