<DOCNO> AP890407-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Collider     04-07 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Collider,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Governor Seeks Review Of Foreign Participation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign participation in the super collider
raises national security implications that must be investigated,
Texas Gov. Bill Clements said Friday as he sought such a review
from President Bush and Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
   ``Before we actively pursue foreign participation'' in the
project, due to be built in his state, ``we have an obligation to
make a considered judgment on what are the national security
implications in this project. This is a vitally important
question,'' Clements said.
   Clements met with Bush and said he had also raised the issue
with Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas; Cheney: Energy Secretary James
Watkins; National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft, and members of
Congress including Rep. Tom Bevill, D-Ala., whose House
appropriations subcommittee will set spending for the collider in
next year's budget.
   ``Everybody's in agreement that an evaluation of the national
security aspect has to be thoroughly explored and determined before
we get in to some kind of a foreign participation,'' Clements said.
   At a recent hearing of his subcommittee, Bevill suggested
Congress would not be willing to fund construction of the collider
unless foreign governments agree to help pay for it. Bevill said
Congress would insist on knowing specifically how much each foreign
contributor planned to spend. Bush is seeking $250 million to begin
construction next year for the particle accelerator at a site south
of Dallas.
   Clements said he met with Bevill on Thursday, and ``he
acknowledges that this area of national security needs to be fully
explored.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
