<FIRST>u w AM-US-Salvador     04-07 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Salvador,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Assures Salvadoran President-elect of U.S. Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush welcomed President-elect
Alfredo Cristiani of El Salvador to the White House on Friday,
assuring him of U.S. support for his rightist government in
battling leftist rebels.
   Cristiani and a White House statement issued after their Oval
Office meeting said the two discussed a shared commitment to
democracy and protection of human rights in El Salvador.
   Earlier in the day, Cristiani rejected a proposal by the rebels
that he declare his forthcoming administration a transitional
government and call for new elections. In return, the rebels would
have agreed to a ceasefire.
   The human rights question has been controversial for Cristiani
as head of the right-wing Arena party, which, along with its
founder Roberto D'Abuisson, has been accused of affiliations with
rightist death squads that have killed tens of thousands of
leftists.
   An administration source said one purpose of the White House
meeting was to underscore U.S. expectations that the new Salvadoran
government, which replaces the moderate Christian Democratic
government of Jose Napoleon Duarte, will be aggressive in keeping
human rights violations in check.
   Vice President Dan Quayle, on a trip to El Salvador in Feburary,
delivered a strong pro-human rights message to the military forces,
linking improved performance in that area with the continuation of
U.S. aid to the Central American nation.
   The White House said that Bush dismissed those who have
prejudged Cristiani and contend he will be weak on human rights.
Bush restated his view ``that Mr. Cristiani should be given the
chance to prove his dedication to democracy, peace and human
rights.''
   Bush also ``noted with satisfaction'' Cristiani's efforts in
getting court charges in a human rights case reinstated after a
judge threw out the case and ordered the release of two military
men and a landowner accused of involvement in a kidnap-for-profit
ring, the White House said.
   ``He said it showed we really meant it when we said that we are
willing to work for the respect of human rights in Salvador,''
Cristiani said.
   The ceasefire proposal by the rebels, announced Thursday,
contemplated elections six months after a ceasefire was in place.
   The proposal demanded the withdrawal of U.S. aid and military
advisers to El Salvador and would have barred military forces from
polling places.
   But Cristiani, who handily defeated his opponents in the March
19 ballotting, rejected the plan, saying he would not consider
naming his a transitional government as proposed by the rebel
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front.
   He said his government will be willing to talk with the rebels
to ``try to seek a means to bring them into the political civililan
life in El Salvador.''
</TEXT>
