<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-ForeignPolicy 1stLd-Writethru a0721SDAQover-the-counterindexesforFri.
04-07 0835</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Foreign Policy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0721,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Shrugs Off Gorbachev on Arms Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 6-7, bgng ``The coolness,'' to update with U.S.
accusation of bugging</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Friday shrugged off
complaints by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev that the U.S.
review of arms control policy was delaying negotiations to harness
the nuclear arms race.
   ``We are making a prudent review I will be ready to discuss with
the Soviets when we are ready,'' Bush said. ``And so, and Mr.
Gorbachev knows, that there is no foot-dragging going on, so I'm
not concerned in the least.''
   The State Department, meanwhile, dismissed as meaningless an
announcement by Gorbachev that he would close two more nuclear
reactors that produce weapons-grade uranium.
   ``It will not restrain their nuclear weapons program,''
spokesman Richard Boucher said. ``It's not really a change in
Soviet nuclear production capabilities.''
   He said the Soviets would retain military and civilian plants
that produce material that could be used for weapons.
   The coolness of the U.S. reaction to Gorbachev was enhanced
later by a State Department announcement that listening devices had
been discovered at the U.S. consulate in Leningrad.
   A brief statement said the department had protested, telling the
Soviets ``such hostile attempts at intelligence gathering, however
long ago they may have been initiated, are deeply resented by the
American people.''
   Gorbachev, on a visit to Britain, said through a spokesman on
Thursday that in arms control ``continuity is the name of the game.
We are a little bit apprehensive we could be losing it.''
   Bush, with a flash of irritation in a session in the White House
press room, said he would be ready to discuss the arms situation
with the Soviets when his administration's review is completed.
That is expected at the end of the month or, at the latest, in
early May.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III will go to Moscow May
10-11 to discuss the suspended negotiations with the Soviets and
also prospects for a first summit meeting between Bush and
Gorbachev.
   The State Department, in announcing the trip, said Baker would
stop at the North Atlantic Treaty Organization headquarters in
Brussels, Belgium, on the way home to brief U.S. allies on the
results.
   The negotiations to reduce long-range nuclear missiles, bombers
and submarines went into recess in December and were tentatively
set to resume in mid-February. But the Bush administration
postponed the resumption for the review, which includes an analysis
of U.S. nuclear forces.
   On a related subject, Gorbachev promised Friday to make deep
cuts in the Soviet military and made the announcement that he would
close two more nuclear reactors.
   Asked for his appraisal, Bush deflected the question. ``We will
react when we are ready to react,'' he said.
   Bush had said previously he would not be ``stampeded'' by
Gorbachev's various initiatives, which included a pledge to reduce
Soviet troops by 500,000 and to remove six tank divisions from
Eastern Europe.
   Gorbachev criticized the lengthy U.S. review through Gennady
Gerasimov, the Soviet foreign policy spokesman, who said on
Thursday ``the new administration has not yet decided what position
to take, how to interpret the international scene. Continuity is
the name of the game.''
   Administration officials suspect the Soviets' tactic may be to
try to promote division within NATO. Bush and Baker will meet with
leaders of the alliance in Brussels at the end of May.
   Asked if the allies were critical of the review, Boucher said:
``I haven't heard any such criticism.''
   On another subject, Bush called the pace of reform in Poland
``mind-boggling'' and ``all very encouraging.''
   On Wednesday, Polish government authorities agreed to legalize
Solidarity, the independent trade union, and to provide for
democratic elections in the East European country.
   Bush said he had not decided whether he should consider a visit
to Poland.
   Asked about the Middle East, the president described the
situation as marginally improved.
   Referring to a proposal by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
to hold elections among Palestinian Arabs on the West Bank and in
Gaza, the president said:
   ``In the Middle East, a little step sometimes can be fruitful. I
think the climate is better than it has been.''
   But Bush said it was too early for him to consider traveling to
the region to try to resolve the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   ``If I personally can be helpful, I am going to do it,'' he
said, but ``it is not a time when a lot of high-visibility missions
on the part of the president can be helpful in the process.''
   As for the proposed elections, which Shamir suggested as a way
to find Palestinian leaders to work out local self-rule with his
government, Bush said:
   ``We haven't fully resolved exactly who's going to have a role;
that's a matter to be determined between the parties. ... The PLO
has people living on the West Bank. ... We want to see elections
that are free and fair.''
</TEXT>
