<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages     04-07 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNESCO Leader Calls for Release of Hostages, Peace in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of UNESCO on Friday called for freedom for
two journalists and other hostages held in Lebanon and an end to
violence in that country.
   Federico Mayor, director-general of the U.N. Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization, noted the third anniversary
on April 17 of the kidnapping of British television journalist John
McCarthy, 32.
   Mayor said in a statement that the British journalist ``has now
passed three years of his life deprived of his freedom, denied the
right to exercise his profession and robbed of the joys of home and
family.
   ``Alas, he is not alone. Others are in the same intolerable
situation in the Middle East, including another journalist, Terry
Anderson.''
   Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated
Press, began his fifth year in captivity in Lebanon three weeks
ago. He was abducted March 16, 1985, and is the longest-held among
the 15 foreign hostages, who include nine Americans.
   A group of British, French and other journalists are organizing
a ceremony at UNESCO April 17 to mark McCarthy's captivity.
   Mayor said UNESCO is deeply concerned with the fate of the
hostages because one of its responsibilities in advancing
individual human rights is to promote the free exchange of ideas.
   Officials say different factions hold the hostages, but they all
are under the umbrella group Hezbollah, over which Iran is believed
to exercise control. Last week Mayor sent an envoy to talk with the
Iranian government.
   Mayor also said he was concerned about the people of Lebanon
because April 13 marks the 14th anniversary of the civil war in
that eastern Mediterranean country. For weeks now, Moslem and
Christian forces have been engaged in heavy artillery battles in
and around Beirut.
   ``I appeal to all governments concerned and to the international
community at large to do everthing within their power to end the
long suffering and hardship of this afflicted people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
