<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-US 2ndLd-Writethru a0745 04-07 0844</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-US, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0745,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians: U.S.-Backed Election Plan Won't Halt Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 12th, ``The interim...' with Shamir comment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians made clear Friday a U.S.-backed
Israeli call for elections in the West Bank and Gaza Strip would
not stop the uprising against Israeli occupation.
   Demonstrations in Jerusalem and the West Bank followed hard on
the heels of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's meeting
Thursday with President Bush. The protests signaled that
Palestinians believe the U.S. pledge to work on the election idea
was inadequate.
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat, speaking in the Congo, attacked
Shamir's proposal as ``inappropriate, as usual'' and vowed the
uprising would continue ``until victory.'' He reiterated a call for
an international conference, but it was uncertain from his comments
whether he ruled out the election idea.
   In Amman, Jordan, two elected mayors deported from the
Israeli-occupied West Bank denounced Shamir's proposed elections.
   ``As one who was elected back in 1976, I would remind Mr. Shamir
that those who were elected are either expelled (by the Israelis)
or dead or dismissed,'' said Mohammed Milhem, former mayor of
Halhoul, deported in 1980.
   Abdul-Jawad Saleh, mayor of El-Bireh until he was deported in
1973, said: ``The problem is they didn't understand that we are one
people with one leadership (the PLO).''
   Both men, in interviews, supported PLO suggestions that
elections might take place after Israel withdraws from the
territories.
   Some influential Palestinians in the occupied territories
indicated elections might be possible if certain conditions were
met, such as U.N. supervision and a withdrawal of Israeli troops.
Their comments appeared to give the U.S. government some leeway to
explore the idea.
   ``The PLO doesn't even have to openly agree to the idea. The PLO
just has to let the process start. We just need an atmosphere that
will let things take off,'' said an Israeli official who demanded
anonymity.
   Shamir's plan is to hold elections in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip to choose Palestinian representatives to talk with
Israel about establishing autonomy as an interim arrangement. Talks
on the ultimate disposition of the war-won land would be left until
later.
   But many Palestinians said they feared he sought only an
arrangement to halt the uprising and was not sincere about seeking
a long-term settlement.
   ``The interim solution will become a permanent solution. We have
no trust in the Israeli side on this matter,'' said Nablus
businessman Said Kenaan.
   In a television interview Friday, Shamir said: ``If we reach an
agreed solution'' in the negotiations, ``it would not be possible
to call it occupation. In any case, it will not be occupation.''
   Nabil Jabari, chairman of the now-closed Hebron University in
the West Bank, said the Palestine Liberation Organization would
have to authorize an international body to supervise the balloting
and elections would have to be part of a larger settlement.
   ``I could not agree to elections if it is only elections. It
must be part of a package to solve the Palestinian problem,'' said
Jabari, who spent 65 days in jail without trial for pro-PLO
activities during the uprising.
   Palestinians interviewed Friday said Israel would have to accept
giving up land it seized in the 1967 Middle East war and end the
military occupation over the 1.7 million Arabs in the West Bank and
Gaza.
   ``Shamir has to announce that ... he accepts the principle of
territory for peace,'' said Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij, who
received death threats earlier this year after proposing a truce in
the uprising in exchange for elections and prisoner releases.
   Palestinian leftists and pro-Syrian supporters ruled out
Shamir's latest proposal.
   ``No and a thousand times no to the elections and even to the
dialogue with Israelis under occupation,'' said Sufian Khatib of
Jerusalem, a surgeon whose views are associated with Damascus-based
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   Hanna Siniora, editor of the pro-PLO daily Al Fajr newspaper,
said he thinks the uprising in the occupied lands ``will continue
until Shamir comes up with a better proposal.''
   An Israeli official who briefed reporters on condition of
anonymity said Shamir's proposal to Bush did not link elections to
the return of calm to the West Bank and Gaza where at least 419
Palestinians have died since December 1987.
   The official said Israel hoped that international reaction would
be favorable to the election idea. ``If international public
opinion accepts, I think the Palestinians would not have an easy
time rejecting it,'' he said.
   The liberal daily Haaretz and the conservative Maaariv
newspapers concurred Shamir had only won a ``time out.'' Haaretz
said ``the impression is that the Bush administration is not going
to let Shamir off the hook soon.''
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres, head of the left-leaning Labor
Party and Shamir's rival in the coalition government, expressed
some skepticism about Shamir's plan. ``I still (don't see) a second
side for negotiations, and the question is whether we can find
Palestinian representatives,'' he was quoted as saying by the
national news agency Itim.
</TEXT>
