<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Shamir     04-07 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Shamir,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Final Status `Not Occupation'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Friday all
Palestinians will be able to run in elections he proposes for the
occupied lands, and any agreed solution ``will not be occupation.''
   His statements in an Israel television interview from Washington
seemed to be conciliatory deviation from earlier positions,
providing an opening for participation of PLO supporters in the
elections.
   Shamir proposes elections that would choose Palestinians to
negotiate an interim autonomy plan for the West Bank and Gaza,
where Palestinians have been in revolt against Israeli occupation
for 16 months. Talks on a permanent solution would begin after five
years.
   The prime minister consistently has ruled out a role in the
elections for the Palestine Liberation Organization, with which
Israel refuses to deal, and expressed hope of finding Palestinian
negotiators not affiliated with it.
   ``I believe the PLO ... does not want peace and therefore any
joint effort would be wasted and would not achiece the aim,'' he
said in the interview Friday.
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat called Shamir's election proposal
``inappropriate, as usual'' and said the uprising will continue
``until victory.'' It was not clear from his comments whether he he
opposed the concept of elections in the territories.
   Shamir said he believed the 1.7 million Palestinians in the West
Bank and Gaza would agree to elections even if the PLO did not
support them, and indicated PLO supporters would be able to run.
   ``Clearly, we think any Palestinian resident of Judea, Samaria
and Gaza'' can participate, he said, using biblical names for the
West Bank.
   ``If we reach an agreed solution, it would not be possible to
call it occupation. In any case, it will not be occupation.''
   Asked whether a member of the radical PLO faction Democratic
Front for the Liberation of Palestine could participate, he avoided
a direct answer.
   ``Look, we have to work out all the details,'' he said. ``What I
brought are mostly principles, general pictures that must be filled
with lines, spots. This we will have to do in the near future. .. .
I think we have to start in the next few days.'' Shamir said.
   He appeared to back off from his earlier insistence that the
uprising end before elections were arranged, linking such a truce
instead to the actual time of voting.
   ``It's self-understood that when we approach the elections, when
we start this process, it can't be conducted and accompanied by
riots, disturbances and attacks,'' he said. ``I would not mention
conditions, but this is understood. ``If we have partners for
implementation of that program, it's certainly a realistic program.
It can be carried out and I think it serves the interests of both
sides. It greatly satisfies the aspirations of the Palestinian
Arabs without harming Israel's security and principles.''
   Of his talks with President Bush and Secretary of State James A.
Baker III, Shamir said the Americans did not ask him to trade
territory for peace.
   ``They did not ask me to accept this formula,'' he said. ``They
know my views, and I adhere to the formula that says we're obliged
to hold talks in which the future of territories will be
determined.''
   Negotiations on final disposition of the territories Israel
captured in the 1967 war must be held ``without preconditions,
without determining what the solution might be,'' Shamir said.
``Only one thing: It must be accepted by both sides.''
</TEXT>
