<FIRST>u w AM-Alaska-Cleanup     04-07 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alaska-Cleanup,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Says Increasing Federal Role in Oil Cleanup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said Friday it is
searching the world for experts with oil-spill experience to help
in the Alaska oil cleanup, and also plans to recruit a work force
of young volunteers to help scrub petroleum-stained beaches.
   Those steps were outlined by U.S. officials after President Bush
first pledged military troops and equipment as part of an increase
in the government's role in repairing and containing damage from
the nation's worst oil spill.
   ``We're at full-scale,'' said Transportation Secretary Samuel S.
Skinner, who is overseeing the expanded federal effort. ``This is a
major civilian disaster. It is being treated as such by the
president.''
   Skinner said the youth corps might be mobilized later this
spring.to help clean up oil-fouled coastlines and wildlife on the
dozens of islands affected by the 10.1 million gallons of crude oil
that spilled from the tanker Exxon Valdez.
   Meanwhile, Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan said his department
is preparing a memorandum of understanding with Exxon for an
initial payment by the giant oil company at least $10 million to
cover the costs of assessing long-term environmental damages and to
plan for their mitigation.
   Lujan said the final total for cleanup and environmental
recovery is likely to be well in excess of the $100 million talked
about several days ago. ``The area that's covered keeps growing and
growing,'' said Lujan in an interview.
   ``I don't think we'll be through with all this business of
cleanup in anything less than a year,'' he warned.
   ``Right now we can't really tell you the extent of the damage to
the wildlife. We know that it's extensive, but as time goes on we
think it's going to be disastrous.'' said Lujan.
   The head of the Environomental Protection Agency, William
Reilly, said that ``one of my first jobs is going to be to bring to
bear on this problem a group of scientists.''
   ``We are looking around the world for the very best scientific
resources that are available _ people who have dealt with
significant oil spills before,'' Reilly said.
   Reilly said it is still too early to assess the full damage from
the oil spill. He predicted the EPA's study of the damage could
itself take as long as three years to complete.
   Other elements of the administration's Alaska relief plan
include:
   _ A yet-to-be determined number of troops will be sent to Alaska
to help in the cleanup. A preliminary Pentagon assessment team to
determine the scope of the work headed for Valdez on Friday.
   _ The Defense Department will send amphibious ships into remote
reaches of Prince William Sound to house and feed those involved in
the cleanup; the Valdez airport will be modernized so that flights
can land there around the clock.
   _ Exxon was urged by the White House to increase the number of
its employees working on the cleanup, and was asked to set up a
procedure for providing immediate payments to those suffering
damage from the spill, pending the resolution of permanent claims.
   _ The administration announced Bush would soon submit oil-spill
liability legislation to Congress, and he also called on the Senate
to give prompt attention to ratifying several pending international
oil-spill agreements.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said nearly all branches of the
military will be involved in the massive cleanup.
   ``We've got the capacity, I think, to go in and help solve that
problem,'' he said. He compared the decision to send troops to
Alaska to the use of military forces last year in fighting forest
fires in Yellowstone National Park.
   At the Pentagon, Defense Department officials said they had
postponed a decision on how many servicemen might be sent to Alaska
until the special assessment team reports back with a
recommendation.
   The military said in a prepared statement that the team was made
up of engineering, environmental, medical and logistics specialists.
   The Pentagon also said it was establishing an Alaska Oil Spill
Joint Task Force, to be headed by Lt. Gen. Thomas G. McInerney of
the Air Force, the commanding general of the Alaskan Air Command.
</TEXT>
