<FIRST>r a AM-Nussbaum-TV     04-07 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nussbaum-TV,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS To Do Miniseries On Hedda Nussbaum's Life Story</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS will create a four-hour miniseries based on
the life of Hedda Nussbaum, who testified against former lover Joel
Steinberg when he was tried for the death of their foster daughter,
a spokeswoman said Friday.
   Writing and casting have not begun, but CBS, which competed with
ABC and NBC for exclusive rights to the story, plans to broadcast
the miniseries sometime next season, said Ann Morfogen, vice
president of media relations.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, a former children's book editor, has pledged
her full cooperation, including the diaries she began writing at
age 15, but will not have editorial control of the project.
   The series will likely concentrate on Ms. Nussbaum's
relationship with Steinberg, who was convicted of first-degree
manslaughter in the fatal 1987 beating of 6-year-old Lisa, the
couple's illegally adopted daughter.
   Steinberg, 47, a disbarred lawyer, was sentenced to
8{-to-25-years in prison two weeks ago and is appealing his
conviction.
   Ms. Nussbaum, a patient at a psychiatric center, recounted years
of physical and psychological torture during her testimony.
   Andrew Lack, executive producer of CBS News' ``West 57th,''
arranged the deal with Ms. Nussbaum's lawyer, Barry Scheck.
   A network official who would not be quoted by name said Ms.
Nussbaum will receive ``well under $100,000.'' Lack said the money
will go toward her ``staggering'' medical bills.
   Steinberg lawyer Felix Gilroy told the Daily News: ``The fact
that the production exists and that it came out so quickly after
the sentencing just demonstrates that there was a monetary motive
behind her whole fabrication. If she told the truth, it wouldn't be
a story.''
   Nussbaum has refused to give interviews since she was arrested
with Steinberg in Lisa's death. Charges against her were dropped.
</TEXT>
