<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-DockStrike     04-07 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dock Strike,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Proposes Legislation to Scrap Guarantee on Dock Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday moved to abolish labor
regulations that guarantee dockworkers' jobs for life, prompting
strikes by thousands of employees at five big British ports,
including Liverpool and Tilbury.
   One union leader warned abolition of 42-year-old National Dock
Labor Scheme may provoke a nationwide strike.
   The leftist-led Transport and General Workers' Union, which
called the walkout, urged its members to return to work ahead of a
meeting scheduled Monday to discuss whether to hold a ballot on an
official strike.
   In the House of Commons, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
government put forward legislation to scrap the regulations by
July. They apply to 9,400 dockworkers at 46 ports handling 70
percent of Britain's foreign trade.
   The government plans to pay compensation of up to $59,500 to
each of the 1,000 dockworkers expected to lose their jobs when the
system is abolished.
   The legislation, welcomed by employers, is certain to be passed
because of Mrs. Thatcher's big majority in the Commons.
   On Thursday, Employment Secretary Norman Fowler called the dock
labor regulations an ``anachronism'' amid jeers from opposition
Labor Party legislators.
   ``As long as the scheme continues to operate, it will remain the
biggest obstacle to a modern and efficient ports industry,'' said
Fowler.
   More than 2,200 dockworkers at Liverpool, in northwestern
England, and the east coast port of Tilbury, two of Britain's
biggest ports, walked out after mass meetings Friday. Another
English port, Southampton, was at a standstill, and smaller
walkouts disrupted Bristol the Scottish port of Glasgow.
   The Labor Party accused the government of ``an act of wilful
sabotage.''
   The dock labor regulations, introduced by a Labor government,
stipulate that manning levels can be cut only when workers quit
voluntarily. If a port goes out of business, dockworkers covered by
the system must be hired at another port.
   The regulations were introduced to stop harsh employment
conditions, when dockers were hired on a day-to-day basis, competed
with each other for work, and had no job benefits. But critics say
abuses have grown and some dockworkers get paid not to work.
   John Connally, docks' officer at the Transport and General
Workers' Union, said a strike could spread.
   ``The docks membership of the union will undoubtedly react
strongly. ... and will call for the implementation of the
long-standing policy (to call a national strike) to oppose any
attempt to end the scheme,'' he said.
   Britain's other, newer 29 main ports employing another 4,000
dockworkers are not covered by the scheme. But Connally said he
believed they would also walk off the job if a national strike was
called.
   National docks strikes in 1972 and 1975 hit large parts of the
British economy.
</TEXT>
