<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-07 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow In Georgia, Record Heat In Southern California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A heat wave continued Friday over the Southwest, with
temperatures rising past 100, but in the East snow fell at higher
elevations of the southern Appalachians.
   The mercury hit a record 100 degrees in downtown Los Angeles at
1 p.m. Downtown had a record-tying 100 Tuesday and record highs of
105 Wednesday and 106 Thursday.
   Other early afternoon readings in southern California included
108 in Palm Springs, 100 in Burbank, and 93 in San Diego. An
estimated 60,000 people crowded Santa Monica Beach, lifeguards said.
   The National Weather Service predicted the beginning of a
cooling trend Saturday with the dissipation of the Santa Ana
weather condition, which began with warm wind last weekend.
   Snow fell at midday over the higher elevations of southern West
Virginia, western Virginia and western North Carolina.
   Early in the day, up to 4 inches of snow fell in the mountains
of northeastern Georgia, and schools in three counties were closed
because of slippery roads.
   Rain fell across much of the rest of Virginia, West Virginia and
North Carolina, and across eastern Tennessee, eastern South
Carolina, the Georgia coast, and northeastern Florida.
   The heaviest rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT was
0.83 of an inch at Cape Hatteras, N.C.
   Snow was scattered over western sections of Pennsylvania and New
York state, and across northwestern Lower Michigan.
   Snow also extended over northern and central North Dakota and
northwestern Minnesota, changing to rain or rain mixed with snow
across southwestern North Dakota and the eastern half of South
Dakota. Rain reached from eastern Nebraska and western Iowa into
northwestern Missouri.
   In northeastern North Dakota, up to 3 inches of snow fell during
the morning over Cavalier and Pembina counties. In adjacent
northwestern Minnesota, 4 inches fell at Badger and Roseau and 6
inches fell at Hallock.
   Also along the North Dakota-Minnesota border, ice jams and rapid
snow melt continued to swell the Red River. It was forecast to
crest at Fargo, N.D., at almost 20 feet above flood stage during
the weekend.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 24
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 109 at Palm Springs, Calif. Friday's
low for the Lower 48 states was 13 degrees at International Falls,
Minn.
   For Saturday, snow, some mixed with rain, was forecast over
northern Maine, Upper Michigan, northern Lower Michigan and
Wisconsin. Morning snow changing to rain was forecast over Montana
and northern Wyoming. Rain was forecast from central Maine across
inland sections of the Carolinas, northern Georgia, northern
Alabama, northern Mississippi, the Tennessee Valley, the Ohio
Valley and the remainder of the Great Lakes.
   Highs in the 30s and 40s were predicted from New England and New
Jersey across Montana and Wyoming; in the 50s and 60s from the
central Atlantic Coast across the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee
Valley, Missouri, the central Plains, the central Rockies and
Washington state; in the 90s from southwestern Texas across the
southern half of California; near 110 over the desert Southwest;
and generally in the 70s and 80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
