<SECOND>AM-India-Tribals,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tribals Kill 25 Villagers in Raids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tribal militants with machine guns and
rifles attacked sleeping residents at dawn Friday in three remote
northeastern villages, and at least 25 people were killed and 100
injured, news reports said.
   About 100 Naga tribals launched simultaneous attacks on the
villages along Assam state's border with Nagaland state, the United
News of India news agency said.
   The injured were taken to a hospital in Assam's Golaghat
district, it said.
   The tribals, who filtered in from Nagaland, also set fire to
more than 100 houses in Lachitgaon and two other villages,
ransacked and raided granaries, and carried away or killed hundreds
of cattle and other valuables, Press Trust of India said.
   PTI said police recovered leaflets in which the National
Socialist Council of Nagaland claimed responsibility.
   The Council, composed of tribal Nagas, began a violent campaign
in the 1960s seeking independence for Nagaland from India and
affiliations with China, which it borders, news reports said.
   Nagaland is in India's extreme northeast, about 1,375 miles east
of New Delhi. Most of its 775,000 people belong to tribes, the
largest of which are the Angamis and Aos.
   Most tribals converted to Christianity, now the state's main
religion, at the turn of the century.
