<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Rockets     04-07 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Rockets,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Rockets Miss Mark, Hit Homes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels fired six rockets Friday
at a police station in northern San Salvador, but five missed their
mark and exploded among modest homes in the Zacamil working-class
district.
   One child was killed and five other children and a woman were
wounded.
   The cinder-block home of Vicente Castillo was ripped apart, his
11-year-old daughter killed and his wife and three other children
wounded.
   But Castillo, 63, could not see the carnage. He is blind.
   He sat on a straight-backed chair on the patio staring ahead.
Beside him was the blanket-covered body of his daughter Carina.
   Castillo held between his knees a small small white bucket and
friends dropped coins into the container to help pay for Carina's
funeral. Near him was the basketball-sized hole where the anti-tank
rocket hit.
   Two children at a nearby house also were wounded.
   One rocket came near the target. It hit a brick guardhouse on
the grounds of a national police station, inflicting minor damage
but no casualties, according to Lt. Rafael Tobar.
   Castillo said, ``It (the rocket) must have been fired at the
station, but it came to fall on us. I heard the detonation and the
cries.''
   His wife, Virginia, daughters Sandra, 18, and Irma, 20, were
struck by shrapnel and a neighbor said they ran down the dirt path
leading from their house, crying in pain and terror. ``They were
covered with blood,'' the neighbor said. They were picked up by a
Red Cross ambulance.
   Castillo's youngest child Jose was slightly wounded.
   Carina's death became another statistic in the list of the
estimated 70,000 people killed in nine years of civil war. Most of
the victims were civilians.
   In February, the leftist guerrillas battling the U.S.-backed
government declared a halt to the use in urban centers of mortars
mounted on pickup trucks. The devices killed some civilians and
wounded dozens while doing only slight damage to military tartets.
   The guerrillas, who called the devices ``mobile artillery
platforms,'' said they would no longer use them ``because of harm
caused to the civilian population.'' They called on the armed
forces to reciprocate by halting the use of long-range artillery
and air raids on suspected rebel positions that killed thousands of
civilians. The military ignored the proposal.
   The rockets used Friday are shoulder-fired from disposable tubes.
</TEXT>
