<FIRST>u a AM-TankerAground 1stLd-Writethru a0801 04-07 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0801,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Tanker Runs Aground In Mississippi River</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with tanker freed, other details, background
on Alaska spill. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Exxon tanker carrying 13 million gallons
of petroleum products ran aground Friday near the mouth of the
Mississippi River, but the hull was not damaged and none of the
cargo spilled, the Coast Guard said.
   The 617-foot Exxon Wilmington was freed after seven hours and
resumed its journey to New Jersey, officials said.
   ``Thank goodness for something called Mississippi mud,'' said
John Reidy, a spokesman for Exxon.
   The ship ran aground at 8:30 a.m. about three miles downstream
from a Russian grain freighter that has been stuck in the channel
for 18 days, said Coast Guard Chief Dan Dewell.
   ``Some build up and settlement may have occurred in that area as
a result of changes in the current where the grain ship is,'' Reidy
said.
   Dewell said the tanker hit soft mud, unlike the Russian
freighter which is hard aground and was being unloaded so that it
can be floated free.
   The Exxon ship ran aground in the same place that a second
freighter was mired last week, Dewell said.
   ``This sort of thing happens ... seven to eight times a year,
especially in the early springtime,'' he said.
   Four tugs and a barge helped free the Wilmington, which had
taken on 8 million gallons of jet fuel and other cargo at the Exxon
refinery at Baton Rouge, Reidy said. Also aboard were about 5
million gallons of gasoline, lubricants and paraffin.
   ``With that kind of cargo, it's always a concern,'' Reidy said.
   Two weeks ago, an Exxon tanker ran aground on a reef on the
southern coast of Alaska, spilling more than 10.1 million gallons
of crude oil. It was the largest oil spill in North American
history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
