<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Scandal     04-07 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Additional Recruit Donations To Takeshita Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television network Friday reported the discovery
of still more past donations to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita by
the company at the center of a stock-profiteering scandal that has
hurt his government.
   The Japan Broadcasting Corp. said Recruit Co. donated about
$190,000 to Takeshita's political support groups in 1986.
   The report came one day after Takeshita confirmed that Recruit
contributed a total of about $380,000 at two of his fund-raising
parties in May 1987.
   Asked about the reported 1986 donations, Takeshita said: ``I
have not heard the full content of the report. We have to review
all facts first.''
   Under Japanese law, a company of Recruit's size can give a
maximum total of about $114,000 in political donations each year.
   Critics have questioned Takeshita's ability, afte receiving
large contributions from Recruit, to carry out his promised
political reforms and oversee a full investigation of the stock
scandal.
   Opposition party leaders on Friday renewed their demands that
Takeshita resign. He has rejected the calls and instead has vowed
to make reforms that will restore public trust in politics.
   ``How can you trust the man to prosecute Recruit when he owes
the company so much?'' asked Yuichi Ichikawa, a senior official of
Komeito, the Clean Government Party.
   Shun Ohide, an official of the largest opposition group, the
Japan Socialist Party, said: ``I am speechless now. I don't think
he has any other choice but to step down after all these
disclosures.''
   Leaders of four opposition parties met in Kyoto to discuss
forming a coalition government that they hope would take over the
administration if Takeshita stepped down. It was the first meeting
in three years among leaders of the Socialist, Komeito, Democratic
Socialist and United Social Democratic parties.
   About 80 members of Takeshita's governing Liberal Democratic
Party demanded this week that government and party leaders act
immediately to restore public trust in the party.
   Some also demanded the resignations of all politicians who
received money or cut-rate stock shares from Recruit. At least 25
politicians, including Takeshita and former Prime Minister Yasuhiro
Nakasone, have been implicated.
   Recruit, an information services conglomerate, sold
bargain-price unlisted shares in a subsidiary to about 150
influential politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen, who profited
handsomely after public trading in the shares began.
   Japan's most powerful business group said Friday that the
scandal pointed up the need for businesses to curb gift-giving and
donations to politicians and to establish ethics standards.
   The Japan Federation of Economic Organizations also said the
case threatened to ``damage the free enterprise economy.''
   Prosecutors have arrested 14 public officials and business
leaders in the Recruit case on bribery and securities law violation
charges. No politicians have been arrested, but prosecutors
reportedly have been questioning politicians and their aides.
   Three Cabinet ministers have resigned over the scandal, and
support for Takeshita in recent public opinion polls has fallen as
low as 9 percent.
   Takeshita does not have to call elections until next year for
the powerful lower house of parliament, in which his Liberal
Democrats hold 297 of the 512 seats. But half of the 256 seats in
the upper house will be up for election this summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
