<FIRST>u w AM-Budget     04-07 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley: White House and Congressional Budget Bargainers Are Near Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House and congressional budget talks
recessed Friday, missing their informal deadline for action, but
House Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley said the group was in ``the
proximity of an agreement.''
   The group, which includes Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady,
White House budget director Richard Darman, and the top members of
the House and Senate budget committees, had been pushing to finish
by Friday because of Congress' legislative timetable.
   Under the Gramm-Rudman law, Congress is supposed to finish a
fiscal 1990 budget resolution by April 15. House Budget Committee
Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., had said he needed to finish the
bargaining with the White House by Friday so that his committee
could complete a formal resolution next week.
   The congressional and White House negotiators planned to
reconvene Monday, and a meeting with Bush was scheduled for Tuesday.
   ``We're getting in the proximity of an agreement. I can't give
you a time or an hour,'' said Foley, D-Wash., after Friday's
all-day bargaining session.
   Several people involved in the talks said, privately, the hope
was to announce an agreement at the White House on Tuesday, but
Foley was cautious.
   ``I would not automatically draw the conclusion that it (the
White House meeting) is a special meeting,'' he said.
   ``We're making good progress, but we're not there yet,'' said
Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., senior Republican on the Senate
Budget Committee.
   The negotiations are designed to ensure that Congress' budget
resolution meets Gramm-Rudman's goal of reducing the deficit to
$100 billion, and that legislation produced to implement the budget
could pass muster with President Bush.
   According to Bush administration estimates, about $28 billion in
deficit reduction _ either new revenues or spending restraints _
must be made to reach the goal.
   The negotiators have been looking to make the package about half
revenues and half spending, with the revenues coming in the form of
asset sales, user fees, and changes in tax law that Bush does not
consider as violating his ``no new taxes'' pledge.
   It is unlikely that any agreement produced in the current talks
would include specific tax proposals or many specific spending
reductions. Instead, the group was working on a broad outline,
leaving details to be worked out later between the administration
and the committees in Congress with jurisdiction over individual
areas.
</TEXT>
