<FIRST>u w AM-Medicare     04-07 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Checks Cases In Which Private Insurance Should Have Paid
Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice and Health and Human Services
departments said Friday they are reviewing a number of instances in
which authorities believe Medicare paid medical bills for which
private insurance carriers were liable.
   The Justice Department's civil division, which recently filed
lawsuits against two private insurance companies to recover money
the government alleges should not have been paid by Medicare, is
continuing to review a number of cases submitted by the Health and
Human Services Department, said spokeswoman Amy Brown.
   Earlier this week, the department filed suit against Provident
Life &amp; Accident Insurance Co., claiming between $7 million and $223
million it contends the company should have paid instead of
Medicare.
   Last month, the department sued Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Michigan, claiming they should have paid at least $2 million in
medical and hospital costs that were billed to Medicare.
   The overpayment issue stems from an overlap in coverage between
Medicare and private health plans for elderly people who continue
to work.
   Under the law, Medicare is only liable for those charges that
are not covered by the elderly employee's private health plan.
   Dennis Siebert, a spokesman for the Health Care Financing
Administration, which runs the Medicare program, said in most cases
the agency is reimbursed by private insurance companies when it
tries to recover charges that should not have been assessed to
Medicare.
   ``In some cases where we have not been able to resolve the
situation with the responsible insurance company, we don't have any
recourse but to seek those legal means to get it back,'' Siebert
said.
   These cases are referred to the HHS inspector general or to the
Justice Department.
   Judy Holtz, a spokeswoman for the inspector general's office,
said Friday evening that the department has a task force on the
matter, combining people from her office _ auditors and
investigators _ as well as personnel from the Social Security
Administration and the HCFA.
   In the past week, the office issued a subpoena against Empire
Blue Cross and Blue Shield of New York to obtain their records, she
said, adding that the office has ``more than a half-dozen''
investigations under way at this time.
   The Wall Street Journal reported Friday that its investigation
of six years of HCFA records showed the agency failed to correct
the problem of overbilling. The Journal said the amount may be as
much as $10 billion over the period.
   ``I don't think anybody has an exact number of how much money is
involved in these cases, in fact how many cases are involved,''
Siebert said.
   The lawsuit filed here in federal court, accuses Provident,
which is based in Chattanooga, Tenn., of failing to tell Medicare
that it had a primary obligation to pay patients' medical bills.
   Instead, the company directed its claims adjustors in 1983 to
await whatever action Medicare took first, the lawsuit said.
   If Medicare paid the bulk of the patient's bills, Provident then
paid only secondary benefits even if the company had responsibility
to pay the main charges, the suit says.
   The lawsuit does not accuse the company of engaging in fraud.
   Provident, which denies any impropriety, has filed a countersuit
in federal court in Chattanooga charging that the Medicare program
was poorly administered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
