<FIRST>u w AM-Eastern1stLd-Wriththrua0771     04-07 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern 1st Ld-Wriththru a0771,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ueberroth Group Opens Talks with Unions ^Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after
5th graf prvs, bgng ``We're negotiating,' to include Texas Air lawsuit
against Icahn and TWA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unions opened negotiations Friday with the
prospective new owners of Eastern Airlines on multimillion-dollar
concessions that buyers led by Peter V. Ueberroth say are vital to
closing the deal to purchase the strikebound carrier.
   Before agreeing to any concessions, however, union officials
want guarantees the former baseball commissioner and his partners
have a viable plan for running the airline and no plans to sell any
more of Eastern's assets.
   ``This will take some time because it's not only money
involved,'' said an International Association of Machinists
official who asked not to be identified. ``How does our ownership
part shape up? How do we get our passengers back? What kind of job
security is involved?''
   Nevertheless, there was cautious optimism heading into the
talks, which began Friday at IAM headquarters and were expected to
continue through the weekend.
   ``We're negotiating, which is a lot different than it was a day
ago,'' said the IAM official. ``That's progress.''
   Meanwhile, Texas Air Corp. charged in a lawsuit filed in Fort
Bend County district court, near Houston, that TWA Chairman Carl
Icahn and TWA were trying to interfere with the planned sale to the
Ueberroth group.
   Houston-based Texas Air, parent of Continental Airlines and
Eastern, claims that Icahn, a takeover specialist, has ``illegally
communicated and negotiated with union groups representing
employees of Eastern offering inducements to those groups to deal
with Icahn and TWA rather than the Ueberroth-(Thomas) Talbot
group.''
   Texas Air said in a statement that ``by negatively influencing
discussions with the unions and the Ueberroth-Talbot group, Mr.
Icahn can hope to frustrate efforts to get Eastern flying again and
make a more favorable deal for himself.
   ``The delay, confusion and economic damage that Eastern would
suffer could obviously provide the opportunity for Mr. Icahn to buy
assets at bargain basement prices,'' the statement said.
   Icahn could not be reached for comment Friday.
   IAM spokesman Jim Conley said the unions would have no statement
on the Ueberroth negotiations because both sides in the talks had
agreed to a news blackout requested by the bankruptcy judge
overseeing Eastern.
   Reaching agreements with the three unions remains a major hurdle
to completion of the $464 million purchase and Ueberroth can call
off the deal if new contracts are not reached by Tuesday night.
Ueberroth also would need approval from a bankruptcy court in New
York.
   Ueberroth met informally with union leaders Thursday night after
the sale agreement was announced but was not involved in Friday's
negotiations. Ueberroth, considered a tough negotiator as head of
the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles and as baseball commissioner, was
expected to join the talks at some point.
   Representatives of the Air Line Pilots Association and the
Transport Workers Union, which represents Eastern flight
attendants, also were involved.
   By midafternoon, the negotiations involved few specifics,
according to sources who declined to be identified, one of whom
described the session as ``highly preliminary'' to more substantive
talks expected to continue throughout the weekend.
   Ueberroth has said he will sell Eastern's Northeast shuttle
service to developer Donald Trump and as part of his purchase
agreement with Texas Air Corp. gave the parent company landing
slots and a gate at New York's LaGuardia Airport as well as a New
York-Montreal route.
   The union leaders, wary those decisions will make it harder for
Eastern to return to profitability, are seeking assurances
Ueberroth plans no further asset sales.
   The IAM struck Eastern a month ago because it refused to accept
concessions demanded by Texas Air Corp. The pilots and flight
attendants have honored IAM picket lines.
   Ueberroth, according to sources who spoke on condition of
anonymity, wants $210 million in wage and benefit concessions.
   Wally Haber, general chairman of the Machinists District 100 in
Miami, said $210 million is the total amount of concessions
requested earlier by Texas Air, $150 million of that from
Machinists. He said he did not know if Ueberroth had adopted the
Texas Air demands.
   Haber said Machinists were willing to accept 15 percent wage and
benefit concessions.
   Union officials have indicated a willingness to accept
concessions provided Eastern was sold to a new owner. Also,
Ueberroth's agreements give employees a 30 percent ownership stake
in return for concessions.
   A spokesman for the flight attendants union, however, noted that
its members made major wage concessions in their last contract
three years ago and were wary of further losses.
   ``More concessions are really not something that we're really
looking forward to,'' said TWU spokesman Jim Gannon. ``Right now
there's really not much more to give.''
   Eastern has been flying about 110 flights a day during the
strike. Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock said the sale agreement
caused no noticeable increase in passenger loads Friday.
   Haber said his Miami office, across the street from Eastern
headquarters, has received calls from local union leaders asking if
members should return to work.
   ``Until we sign on the dotted line, we are still on strike,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
