<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Visitor-AIDS 3rdLd-Writethru a0848 04-07 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Visitor-AIDS, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0848,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Overriding INS, Judge Orders Dutchman with AIDS Freed from Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Verhoef left..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
Verhoef flying to San Francisco, quotes. Picks up 6th graf pvs: `Judge
Vinikoor...; Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Friday overrode U.S.
immigration officials and ordered a Dutch visitor suffering from
AIDS released from prison so he can attend a conference on the
disease.
   Immigration Judge Robert Vinikoor said Hans Paul Verhoef had met
standards required to allow him to be excluded from laws barring
foreigners with dangerous and communicable diseases from entering
the country.
   ``I believe he has shown a waiver of exclusion should be
granted,'' Vinikoor said. ``While I don't want to minimize the risk
of AIDS, the applicant has shown there is a minimal risk to the
United States if he is admitted on a temporary basis.''
   U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service officials
immediately asked the federal Board of Immigration Appeals in Falls
Church, Va., to stay the judge's order. But Friday night the board
refused to consider the request, said Thomas Schiltgen, INS
district director in St. Paul.
   Verhoef boarded a flight for San Francisco at 7:25 p.m. Friday
at the Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport. The five-day
conference in the California city ends Sunday.
   ``Good!'' Verhoef exclaimed after hearing the judge issue the
order in the courtroom, where he was handed a bouquet of pink roses
by supporters. Later, Verhoef spoke to reporters at the airport.
   ``I'm very glad that I can do what I have to do, now that the
U.S. government has let me go,'' he said.
   ``I'm very disappointed being imprisoned and getting this
treatment in this country,'' he said, adding that he was disturbed
about having to raise $10,000 bond before leaving Minnesota.
   Judge Vinikoor ordered Verhoef to post a $10,000 bond to enforce
the terms of the waiver, which is in effect until April 28. The
money was provided by supporters of the Minnesota AIDS Project
within a few hours of the judge's ruling, said Helene Haapala, one
of Verhoef's lawyers.
   Vinikoor's decision overrode the INS action earlier in the day.
The INS denied Verhoef's request for a waiver to attend the AIDS
conference.
   ``The risk of harm by an AIDS-infected alien in the absence of
humanitarian reasons for the temporary admission of aliens far
outweighs the privilege of an alien to enter the United States to
participate in a conference,'' Richard Norton, associate
commissioner for examinations, wrote in the INS ruling.
   At the hearing before Vinikoor, Verhoef stopped short of saying
he wouldn't engage in any sexual act while in the United States. He
promised only to practice ``safe sex.''
   ``I'm prepared to say under oath that I will abstain from risky
behavior,'' Verhoef said under questioning from Richard Soli, INS
district counsel.
   ``Is safe sex 100 percent safe?'' Soli asked.
   ``In my knowledge, yes,'' Verhoef replied.
   Verhoef described alternatives to intercourse including hugs,
sexual caresses and special toys. He said he brought toys that
could be used without a partner.
   ``I think everyone, all of the persons who have AIDS or who have
tested positive for HIV should be aware of the fact that they
shouldn't take any steps in spreading the virus,'' he said.
   ``I have got AIDS myself, and I realize very well what it is to
have AIDS. I don't want to do that to anyone else,'' he said.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   Verhoef was detained by immigration officials on Sunday at the
Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport as he was traveling to
the conference in San Francisco. He had been held at the Oak Park
Heights state prison.
   The judge said immigration officials acted properly in
apprehending Verhoef. But he said Congress allows discretion in
interpreting the law.
   His ruling echoed Thursday's recommendation by INS district
officials in St. Paul, who had said Verhoef should be allowed to
attend the conference. The U.S. immigration officials' opposite
stance drew fire from Dr. Tim Wolfred, executive director of the
San Francisco AIDS Foundation.
   ``The INS has decided to enforce a law founded on hatred,
bigotry and ignorance,'' he said. ``This decision says the federal
government has no compassion for people with HIV disease or
understanding of how AIDS is transmitted.''
</TEXT>
