<FIRST>r a AM-Brawley-McClease     04-07 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brawley-McClease,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Accused Tawana Brawley's Advisors Acquitted on All Counts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed to possess taped conversations
of Tawana Brawley's advisers expressing doubts about her tale of
gang-rape by whites was acquitted Friday of perjury and obstructing
justice.
   A U.S. District Court jury found Samuel McClease innocent on the
third day of deliberations in the week-long trial.
   McClease, 27, of Newark, N.J., added another twist to the
tangled Brawley case last June when he told federal investigators
and news reporters that he had bugged the conversations of Ms.
Brawley's advisers and could produce tapes undermining her story.
   Ms. Brawley, a black teenager from the upstate community of
Wappingers Falls, N.Y., claimed she had been abducted and raped by
up to six white men _ including one with a police badge _ in
November 1987.
   On the advice of her lawyers and family adviser, Ms. Brawley,
who was then 15, refused to cooperate with the grand jury
investigating her case, creating national headlines.
   McClease, a self-described surveillance expert, claimed to have
tapes demonstrating that Ms. Brawley's advisers _ the Rev. Al
Sharpton and attorneys C. Vernon Mason and Alton H. Maddox Jr. _
did not themselves believe her story of abduction and sexual abuse.
   All the Brawley advisers denied McClease's allegations, and the
10 tapes McClease later produced for a federal grand jury turned
out to be blank.
   Last November, after a seven-month investigation, a state grand
jury did not indict anyone and issued a report that concluded Ms.
Brawley concocted her story. A month later, a federal grand jury
indicted McClease on one count each of perjury and obstruction of
justice.
   McClease heaved a sigh of relief as the verdict was read and
later told reporters: ``I'm happy. Right now, I want to put this
behind me and get back into electronics _ legally!''
</TEXT>
