<DOCNO> AP890407-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-GATT-WorldTrade     04-07 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GATT-World Trade,0311</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Disagreement on Textiles Delays Final Trade Package ^By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World trade talks hit a snag Friday when European
nations made an unexpected proposal in negotiations on textile
trading, officials said.
   Negotiators at the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
meeting settled differences between the European Economic Community
and the United States on agricultural imports.
   The 12-nation EEC, however, unexpectedly offered a new textiles
proposal of ``a substantial nature'' said GATT spokesman David
Woods.
   Woods said Arthur Dunkel, GATT director-general, was ``angry''
at the development.
   But Tran Van-Thinh, head of the EEC delegation, said that ``much
employment and investment'' was at stake.
   ``We have the right and the duty to make any proposal right up
to the last minute of the negotiations,'' he said without
elaborating on the EEC's plan.
   Developing countries with large textile industries want liberal
regulations. Industrialized countries such as the United States and
EEC members are concerned about the impact a lack of restrictions
might have on domestic industries.
   Woods said discussions would continue through the night and that
Dunkel would try to present a final proposal on all issues for
approval on Saturday.
   An agreement would automatically include 11 other world trade
accords reached at a GATT meeting in December in Montreal. It also
would clear the way for more progress in the so-called Uruguay
Round of trade-freeing negotiations, due to end 1990.
   Negotiations on agricultural imports were stalled by a U.S.
demand that supports be eliminated. The EEC had resisted the idea.
   The agreement reached Friday calls for an overall freeze on farm
supports and import barriers through 1990. It calls for countries
to reduce their subsidies in 1990 but does not specify by how much.
   U.S. officials were not available for comment on the accord.
</TEXT>
