<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Elections     04-07 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Elections,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Says Government Reform Bill Insufficient For Fair Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition branded as insufficient
a electoral reforms package introduced in the National Assembly on
Friday by the leftist Sandinista government.
   The bill includes proposed reforms in elections and mass media
as part of a regional peace accord reached at a Central American
summit meeting on Feb. 14.
   The reforms are to ensure fair general elections, which
President Daniel Ortega moved up by 10 months, to Feb. 25, 1990.
   ``This is a joke,'' said Sergio Torres, a deputy from the
Conservative Democratic Party, which, with 14 deputies, has the
largest opposition representation in the 96-member assembly. The
governing Sandinista National Liberation Front has 61 deputies.
   Torres complained about a government proposal to allow
Nicaraguans abroad to register for voting at Nicaraguan consulates,
but require they vote in Nicaragua.
   ``I was under the impression that any consulate is considered
part of the national territory,'' Torres told reporters.
   Mauricio Diaz, leader of the Popular Social Christian Party,
said the proposed 30 minutes allowed daily to political parties in
state-run television and radio stations was not enough.
   ``Now that they're proposing that anything with 27 members can
call itself a party, (obtaining air time) will be very difficult,''
Diaz said.
   He also said allowing members of the armed forces to vote goes
against opposition demands.
   ``This package is not what the opposition has demanded,''
Virgilio Godoy, head of the Conservative Democratic Party, told The
Associated Press later.
   He called the proposals an attempt to make it seem the
Sandinistas are serious about democratization.
   ``This package is not directed at Nicaragua, it's not for
internal consumption,'' Godoy said. Ortega ``just wants to carry
that package in his pocket when he goes to Europe.''
   The president is leaving on an eight-country European tour April
25 to lobby for money and political support for Nicaragua.
   At the February summit in El Salvador, Ortega promised reforms
to ensure free and fair balloting, along with moving up the
elections. Under the accord, reforms must be in place by April 25.
   The five presidents _ of Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras,
Guatemala and Costa Rica _ also agreed to draft a plan by mid-May
to dismantle the Nicaraguan rebel force, known as Contras.
   About 11,000 Contras and their relatives have lived in Honduran
jungle camps in Honduras since their leaders and the Sandinistas
signed a cease-fire in March 1988, a month after the U.S. Congress
cut off military aid to the rebels.
   The government reform package on Friday was sent to committee
for subsequent assembly debate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
