<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Sher Adv10   04-07 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Sher, Adv 10,0837</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, April 10 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Antony Sher's ``Middlepost'': An Actor Turns Author</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not long ago, Antony Sher was being hailed as one
of the most exciting Shakespearean actors since Laurence Olivier.
   But instead of pursuing greatness on the stage, he switched to
literature, and ``Middlepost,'' his rangy and picaresque first
novel, represents the expatriate actor's emotional journey back to
his South African roots.
   ``The book is my coming-out as a South African,'' says Sher.
``I've been a closet South African for a long time; what I think is
healthy is that by writing the book, it feels much more comfortable
being myself.''
   That self refers to a protean talent by which an outsider has
managed to crack Britain's hermetic cultural circle. Both his
Richard III and his Shylock for the Royal Shakespeare Company were
revelatory interpretations that placed him at the top of the
English acting tradition.
   Sher acknowledges that during his two decades in England he has
worked very hard to become an Englishman, acquiring the tone and
mannerisms of a proper British accent.
   ``Middlepost,'' published last September in Britain and this
month in the United States, signals his attempt at the age of 39 to
come to terms with a country that could never fully be left behind
for the Cape Town-born grandson of Lithuanian immigrants.
   ``It has to do with the huge question mark that hangs over my
head, and I suppose over all the Jews of South Africa, really,'' he
said in an interview.
   ``At the time of the pogroms at the turn of the century when the
Jewish population evacuated Eastern Europe ... to those who went to
South Africa, it seemed history was playing a very, very cruel joke.
   ``It was inviting them to escape persecution and become the
persecutor.''
   Sher's first years in London were inauspicious. Rejected by two
leading drama schools, he attended the less prestigious Webber
Douglas and did provincial repertory.
   Not until 1982, and his ensuing affiliation with the RSC, did
the short, scruffy actor begin looking like a star. For his 1984-5
portrayal of the villainous Richard III, he hurtled around the
stage on crutches to capture the essence of Shakespeare's ``bottl'd
spider.''
   He played the role for 15 months in Stratford-upon-Avon and
London, and took it to Australia, stopping off in Middlepost to
research the novel.
   His ``Richard'' won him a commercial London run in Harvey
Fierstein's ``Torch Song Trilogy'' in which he played the
homosexual drag artist originated by Fierstein himself on Broadway.
   It was the first taste of above-the-title billing for an actor
who remembers 20 years ago being ``wide-eyed at this legendary
place of theater, staring at the names in lights there.''
   Back at the RSC he played Malvolio in ``Twelfth Night,'' Vindice
in Cyril Tourneur's ``The Revenger's Tragedy'' and in ``The
Merchant of Venice,'' a memorable Shylock whose full beard and
thick Jewish accent put to rest traditionally dry, classical
English approaches to this difficult part.
   Sher was already writing ``Middlepost,'' and he acknowledges
that his commitment to the book may have prompted the RSC to
sideline him.
   ``I didn't have time to get stuck in, so I got left out, and I
was angry,'' he said.
   ``My life seems constantly to surprise me. Three to four years
ago, if someone had said you'd be writing a novel, I would have
said, `I'm sorry; it's not in my plans.'''
   But as soon as he got the idea, the theme came very quickly.
``It must have been lying there.''
   Set in British-ruled South Africa in 1902, ``Middlepost'' is
about a Yiddish-speaking Lithuanian immigrant nicknamed Smous, the
Afrikaans word for peddler.
   Sher based Smous on his grandfather, a ``peddler who peddled his
way inland and ended up at this place called Middlepost.'' The tale
of Smous' discovery of self and country unfolds through the
characters he encounters, from the bushgirl Naoksa to the arrogant
Afrikaaner Breedt.
   Sher's family once owned Middlepost, a backwater town in the
Karoo Desert, and the novel's theme of alienation in a new land had
personal resonances.
   ``Smous' first day in Cape Town is like a lot of my early days
in London. They were incredibly bewildering, although I could speak
the language.''
   Having come to terms with his South Africanness through writing,
Sher now finds himself politicized. Last October, he organized a
benefit in London to raise money for victims of apartheid.
   Since leaving the stage, he has played Loki, a blacksmith's
dastardly apprentice, in Terry Jones' film ``Erik the Viking.''
It's his second movie following the little-seen 1985 ``Shadey.'' He
also has written a script for a BBC-TV telefilm, and plans a book
of his illustrations and a second novel, set in present-day England
and South Africa.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 10</NOTE>
