<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-TwoTerribleWeeks Adv09   04-07 1198</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Two Terrible Weeks, Adv 09,1235</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>On a Calm Night, Words of Disaster: `We're Leaking Oil.'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Course for Doom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was the kind of calm, clear night so
welcome in Prince William Sound because it is so rare. Across the
bay, the lights of Valdez twinkled as the mammoth tanker slipped
from its berth after filling its belly with more than a million
barrels of Alaska pipeline crude.
   On the fourth-story bridge of the Exxon Valdez' gleaming white
superstructure were skipper Joseph Hazelwood, several of his crew,
and Ed Murphy, one of the harbor pilots who routinely guide the big
ships through the tricky passage from Valdez into Prince William
Sound.
   Snow on the steep Chugach Mountains ringing the harbor cast a
faint glow in the inky darkness. The first hint of what passes for
spring in Alaska definitely was in the air that Thursday night.
   But before dawn, tragic mistakes would change Prince William
Sound, perhaps forever, and send environmental shock waves around
the globe. Before dawn, the captain would radio a gross
understatement, ``We're leaking oil. We're going to be here awhile.
I just wanted to make a report.'' Before two weeks were out, a
vast, often maligned cleanup effort would stagger out of control.
   Ed Murphy clambered over the side of the tanker onto a boat
headed back to port. By all accounts, the trip to that point had
been as uneventful as the thousands of others in nearly 12 years of
shipping oil out of Valdez.
   Hazelwood contacted the Coast Guard's traffic control center in
Valdez at 11:25 p.m., according to an initial transcript released
by a Coast Guard investigator.
   ``We are hooking up sea speed. Estimated time of arrival at
Naked Island 0100 (1 a.m.).''
   ``Roger that, sir,'' the Coast Guard replied, not tracking the
tanker on radar because traffic was so light and conditions were so
fine. ``Request updated ice report when you get down through
there.''
   The nearby Columbia Glacier regularly drops chunks of ice, some
as big as houses, that drift into the upper sound and the charted
shipping lanes.
   ``OK,'' Hazelwood replied, ``I was just about to tell you
judging from our radar we were just about to divert ... and end up
in the inbound lane if there is no conflicting traffic.''
   ``No reported traffic,'' the Coast Guard responded.
   Five minutes later, Hazelwood radioed he was altering course and
reducing speed to 12 knots. ``Winding my way through the ice,'' he
advised.
   It's not clear what happened next. Hazelwood seems to have set a
course directly for Bligh Reef. He didn't notify the Coast Guard of
the change, Coast Guard investigator Mark DeLozier told The
Anchorage Times. He left the bridge in command of Gregory Cousins,
a third mate not certified for those waters.
   All was calm until the five final frantic minutes, when the crew
tried to change course and avoid the outcropping of rocks lurking a
few dozen feet below.
   There followed what helmsman Robert Kagan later described as ``a
bumpy ride.'' Eight holes were ripped in the dark blue hull of the
2-year-old, $125 million ship, the pride of Exxon's U.S. fleet.
   According to the ship's log, the tanker came to a stop at 12:04
a.m., March 24, Good Friday.
   Hazelwood, who hadn't radioed in almost an hour, gave the Coast
Guard the news at 12:28 a.m.
   ``We've fetched hard aground,'' Hazelwood said. ``We're leaking
oil. We're going to be here awhile. I just wanted to make a
report.''
   Initial pollution report: ``Uncertain due to darkness.''
   Two minutes later, the Port of Valdez was closed to all traffic.
The tug Stalwart was dispatched to assist.
   By sunrise, oil was gurgling to the surface and the slick was
1,000 feet wide.
   Not until 11 a.m., more than twice the period promised in the
oil industry's spill response contingency plan, was a containment
boom snugged around the Exxon Valdez.
   Chemical dispersants applied to the slick at 6 p.m. did little
because the water was so calm. Two hours later, the tanker Exxon
Baton Rouge nestled alongside to begin pumping off the remaining
oil. By day's end, the spill was estimated at more than 10 million
gallons.
   The next evening, emergency workers tried to set the oil on fire
to burn it off, but the effort failed.
   On Sunday, the wind began to pick up, churning the slick into a
gooey mess covering more than 100 square miles and rendering all
containment and cleanup methods ineffective.
   Monday, the president of Exxon Shipping Co. conceded his company
was ``a little overwhelmed.'' Later that day, Exxon revealed that
Hazelwood had a history of alcohol problems, with two drunken
driving convictions in the previous five years. He had no
automobile driver's license.
   By this time, the oil was described as the consistency of
chocolate mousse. Reports of bird and animal contamination began
trickling in.
   Tuesday, March 28, the spill was moving ``like it's on a
superhighway,'' and the first animal deaths were confirmed. The oil
terminal in Valdez was reopened to restricted tanker traffic.
   Alarmed by the rapid spread of the oil toward vital hatcheries,
locals assembled a fleet of fishing boats to deploy containment
booms at the mouths of bays and harbors. Exxon's skimmers weren't
working.
   President Bush dispatched a team and two days later nixed the
idea of having the federal government take the management helm.
   Coast Guard Commandant Paul Yost said he couldn't understand how
it happened. ``This is not treacherous in the area they went
aground,'' Yost said. ``It's 10 miles wide. Your children could
drive a tanker up through it.''
   Exxon fired Hazelwood after tests revealed his blood alcohol
content was above legal limits nine hours after the wreck.
   One week after, the iridescent menace had begun seeping into the
Gulf of Alaska, threatening more fishing communities and a national
park. Angry, frustrated fishermen and unemployed laborers broke up
an Exxon briefing, sending a federal bird expert from the podium in
tears.
   As March ended, state authorities filed criminal charges against
Hazelwood for operating the vessel while intoxicated, reckless
endangerment and negligent discharge of oil.
   The oil eventually spread over an area larger than Delaware, and
the toll of dead birds, sea otters and deer mounted steadily. Exxon
apologized to the world for the spill in full-page newspaper
advertisements.
   Last Wednesday, the tanker was refloated and moved to a remote
cove, a kind of public exorcism of a great evil.
   Hazelwood turned himself in that day, and posted bail Thursday.
   Two weeks after Good Friday, oil reached a national park, and
officials confirmed the obvious: the spill has grown so large only
nature's forces _ tides, winds and ocean currents _ will be able to
remove it.
   ``The oil is unmanageable,'' said Jim Hayden, the state's
cleanup coordinator. ``It's just immense. I don't think a spill
this size is controllable now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This story was compiled by Bruce Bartley from
reports by Associated Press Writers Tad Bartimus, David Foster,
Susan Gallagher and Hal Spencer and from other news dispatches.
</TEXT>
