<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0787</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by former baseball commissioner
Peter V. Ueberroth has agreed to buy strike-crippled Eastern
Airlines for about $464 million. Union officials said they were
cautiously optimistic the deal could end the month-old walkout at
the nation's seventh-biggest airline.
   The deal, announced Thursday by Ueberroth and Texas Air Corp.
Chairman Frank Lorenzo, still must be approved by Eastern's major
creditors and the U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   Furthermore, the deal requires Eastern to reach new work
agreements with its three unions _ which would get 30 percent
ownership of the airline in return for contract concessions _ by
next Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taking advantage of strike-hobbled Eastern
Airline's absence in some lucrative markets, American Airlines
announced plans to add 11 flights in Miami and 13 in the Caribbean
by June.
   The expansion, announced Thursday, had been part of American's
long-term planning, but the timing was pushed ahead by the
Machinists union strike that left Eastern flying only about 10
percent of its schedule since March 4.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush vowed anew to veto any attempt
to raise the hourly minimum wage higher than $4.25 as the Senate
nonetheless debated setting the base wage at $4.65.
   Democratic sponsors Thursday planned to amend their bill to
slash its final target to $4.55 an hour but still appeared headed
for a confrontation with Bush. They conceded, though, that his
support for some increase was a welcome change after the Reagan
administration's dogged opposition to any boost.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress, under the cloud of $9.4 billion in
fresh deposit withdrawals from the nation's savings and loan
institutions, began amending President Bush's bailout bill and
immediately got into a dispute over reopening some of last year's
deals that provided $38 billion to the industry.
   On a bipartisan vote, the House Banking subcommittee on
financial institutions Thursday moved immediately to deny Bush some
of the controls he had sought over officials running the
government's deposit insurance program.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's major retailers reported mixed
March sales, and analysts said the sluggish growth at some chain
stores suggested that higher credit costs have made consumers more
cautious about spending.
   Inclement weather in parts of the country and the loss of a
selling day due to store closures for the Easter holiday were cited
Thursday as reasons for the mediocre results at the cash registers
of several big general merchandisers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Ivan F. Boesky plan to ask a
federal judge to reduce his three-year jail term on grounds that
the convicted inside trader's cooperation led to the indictment of
junk bond financier Michael Milken, sources said.
   Boesky became eligible for parole last month after one year in a
minimum security prison, but probably will seek early release from
the judge in Manhattan who sentenced him, not from prison
officials, an attorney involved in the case said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials awaited word from the
Coast Guard on who would manage the much-maligned cleanup of the
nation's worst oil spill, while the captain of the tanker that
leaked the oil was freed on bail.
   Gov. Steve Cowper said Exxon's cleanup has been too slow and
asked Coast Guard Rear Adm. Edward Nelson Jr. to take control. The
governor said Nelson agreed, but the Coast Guard said Thursday no
formal decision had been made.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush may order the military to help
in the long-term cleanup of the massive oil spill in Alaska, it was
disclosed as the administration underscored its opposition to a
federal takeover of the operation.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday that
Alaska's congressional delegation had asked officials to consider
using the military _ ``and we are.'' He said the armed forces could
help in washing oil from animals and birds plus cleaning up rocks
and shorelines and then continue in the long-term effort.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lapsed into a sluggish decline Thursday as
investors cautiously awaited monthly statistics on employment. The
Dow Jones industrial average dropped 12.83 points to 2,291.97.
   The dollar was generally higher in listless trading.
   Prices of government securities edged lower in dull trading.
Corporate and municipal debt issues rose slightly.
   Cocoa futures prices fell sharply because of concerns about
large supplies, while grain futures finished mixed after choppy
trading. On other futures markets, energy prices were mixed,
livestock and meat slumped, and precious metals were fairly steady.
