<DOCNO> AP890407-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0423EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Deal Bjt   04-07 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Deal, Bjt,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>How The Eastern-Ueberroth Deal Was Done</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD BLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Texas Air Corp. board met in Houston
last week, Peter V. Ueberroth assumed he had a done deal.
   But Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo's telephone call contained
news Ueberroth did not expect. Lorenzo said that hotel mogul Jay A.
Pritzker had made a higher offer.
   ``Peter told him `Congratulations. If I were you I'd take it,'''
a source familiar with the deal said.
   An hour later, Lorenzo called back and asked Ueberroth what he
was going to do.
   ``I'd take it,'' a source quoted Ueberroth as saying of
Pritzker's offer. ``I just told you an hour ago, we're history.''
   ``The thinking was that there was not less than a 50 percent
chance that there would be a deal,'' a source familiar with the
negotiations said.
   ``He used the Ueberroth negotiating strategy of a phantom bid,''
one Ueberroth friend said of Lorenzo.
   Ueberroth, according to friends, said he felt betrayed by
Lorenzo. He went home to California for his final day as baseball
commissioner and a weekend of golf.
   But by Monday, intermediaries got the two sides talking again.
And by Tuesday, according to several sources, Ueberroth's lawyers
and Texas Air officials were negotiating again.
   Henry Steinman of the New York law firm Latham &amp; Watkins headed
the Ueberroth negotiating team. By Tuesday afternoon, Ueberroth's
side thought a deal had been reached. Ueberroth returned to New
York on Tuesday night, and on Wednesday he began personal
negotiations with Lorenzo at Latham &amp; Watkins' offices.
   All through Wednesday, Ueberroth and Lorenzo stuggled with
details. Lorenzo's people claimed Ueberroth was nitpicking and
Ueberroth's people claimed Lorenzo was trying to change terms
previously agreed to.
   The sides argued about landing slots and gates at New York's
LaGuardia Airport. About the way notes receiveable would be
transfered from Eastern to Texas Air. Dozens of people went in and
out of the conference room during the talks, which began at 7:30
a.m. and continued until just before 8 p.m.
   On Thursday morning at 7:30, they went back at it. But in the
final stages, Ueberroth and Lorenzo did the negotiating one-on-one,
sources said. And at about 12:15, the two signed an agreement of
less than a dozen pages. The airline would be sold to a new
corporation, Eastern Airlines Employees and Service Company.
   About 90 minutes later, Lorenzo and Ueberroth walked to the
nearby Summit hotel. Ueberroth was wearing the same red-and-gray
paisley tie he wore Dec. 14 when he announced baseball's $1.06
billion four-year contract with CBS.
   It was about that time that Ueberroth had become interested in
Eastern, baseball sources said. Carl R. Pohlad, owner of baseball's
Minnesota Twins, also owned 12 percent of Jet Capital Corp., Texas
Air's holding company. With labor troubles coming up, Pohlad asked
Ueberroth if he would be interested.
   Ueberroth went to Miami and spoke with the pilots' union in
December. Not much happened until ealy March, when the Machinists'
union struck and pilots and flight attendants walked off in
support. Ueberroth sensed the opportunity.
   ``The bankruptcy indicated it was achievable,'' said Barry Rona
of the baseball owners' Player Relations Committee, one of the few
people willing to speak on the record. ``It became obvious as the
days went by that you were going to need new ownership and a new
management team to get the airline running again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0424EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Ueberroth Bjt   04-07 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Ueberroth, Bjt,0796</SECOND>
<HEAD>Like Predecessors, Ueberroth Brings High Profile To Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter V. Ueberroth brings to Eastern Airlines a
reputation as a no-nonsense manager and financial wizard
responsible for turning around ailing enterprises and honing his
public image in the process.
   That track record explains why the 1984 Olympics organizer and
former baseball commissioner agreed Thursday to buy a seemingly
hopeless airline beset by years of labor strife and $3.2 billion in
debt.
   ``It's certainly going to rank up there in attractiveness in
Peter's goals and aspirations, which is to take on a challenge,''
said Barry Rona, who heads the negotiating team for baseball's
owners.
   ``You can count on one thing, Peter will make money for
everyone,'' Rona added. ``If it turns out there are shareholders,
he'll make money for shareholders. His partners will make money,
the employees will make money and Peter will make money.''
   Eastern's last profitable quarter was in 1985 during an
industry-wide boom. Eastern since then has been hampered by labor
problems, its tarnished image and a corporate streamlining,
analysts said.
   ``We are not miracle workers at all in any way, shape or form,''
Ueberroth, 51, said at a news conference announcing the $464
million deal. ``I think most people will bet against us.''
   Ueberroth, who stepped down as baseball commissioner last
Saturday, isn't the first to take on the challenge of 60-year-old
Eastern.
   Eddie Rickenbacker, the World War I flying ace, ran the airline
from 1935 until his ouster by Eastern's board in 1964. He built
Eastern into a major national carrier but made passenger
convenience a low priority.
   ``He was one of those typical old pioneers,'' said aviation
historian Robert Serling. ``Eastern reflected Rickenbacker's own
image _ tight-fisted but close to the vest, no-nonsense, to hell
with service.''
   Two other men led Eastern from 1964 to 1975, when former Apollo
8 astronaut Frank Borman took over the airline, but the airline
retained its reputation for bad service.
   As an Eastern vice president, Borman was known for visiting
workers from baggage handlers to flight attendants on the job. When
he became president, he turned to erasing the bad service image.
   ``He was the first airline chief executive who allowed himself
to become the symbol of the airline itself through television and
newspaper ads,'' said Serling, who collaborated on Borman's 1988
autobiography, ``Countdown.'' ``Long before Lee Iacocca did, Frank
was appearing in television commercials.''
   Borman began appearing on television about a year after taking
over Eastern, pledging Eastern's dedication to service. ``We have
to earn our wings every day,'' the slogan went.
   Lorenzo, chairman of Texas Air Corp., acquired Eastern in 1986
with the blessing of Eastern's unions, most of which had accepted
wage concessions to help the financially ailing carrier. The union
endorsement came even though Lorenzo had taken Continental Airlines
into bankruptcy court and broke its unions.
   Now comes Ueberroth, who was vice president of Trans
International Airlines for two years before he founded a travel
agency in Southern California in 1963, First Travel Corp.
   Ueberroth and his brother sold First Travel in 1979 to Carlson
Cos. of Minneapolis for $10.1 million. John Ueberroth ran it as
president of Carlson Travel Group, building it into the largest
travel agency operation in North America with $3.2 billion a year
in revenue.
   Ueberroth generated $230 million in profit as organizer of the
1984 Los Angeles Olympics and turned baseball's fortunes around
from a $67 million loss in 1983 to $100 million profit in 1988.
   During his term as commissioner, Ueberroth was the darling of
most of baseball's 26 owners, but less liked by players' union
officials, who claim he took credit for reviving the national
pastime where it wasn't necessarily due.
   ``He's an eyeball-to-eyeball guy. Everybody respected him,
considered him to be a great leader, though of him as being
intelligent,'' said Avron Fogelman, co-owner of the Kansas City
Royals. ``He was a step ahead of us all.
   ``And he did it very simply and did it without a lot of
adjectives. He used the most direct approach in dealing with
baseball owners as imaginable.''
   Marvin Miller, executive director of the Major League Baseball
Players Association for 17 years, accused Ueberroth of flipping
sides during 1984-85 in collective bargaining negotiations _ a sign
of his take-credit style.
   ``It's a public relations technique that says `When I started in
this job things were terrible,''' Miller said. ``Whether or not
that's true, you just say so. Then after a short while you say
everybody's making money. You don't have to add, `I turned it
around.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   04-07 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>March Retailers' Results Varied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Weakness in sales at some big chain stores may be more evidence
that consumers are losing their spending enthusiasm as overall
economic activity eases, analysts say.
   Reports Thursday from many of the nation's major general
merchandise, discount and apparel stores sent mixed signals about
the March performance.
   Opinions ranged from Sears, Roebuck and Co. saying its sales
were better than anticipated to K mart Corp. describing its volume
as disappointing.
   ``It's hard to look at these numbers and make any
generalizations,'' said Karen Sack of Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
``It's kind of a mixed month. There are some good double-digit
numbers in there, though.''
   Allen Sinai of Boston Co. Economic Advisers Inc. said the chain
store sales were consistent with recent statistics showing a
moderation in growth.
   It was widely anticipated that consumer spending, which accounts
for about two-thirds of overall economic activity, would contract
in reaction to the increases in interest rates this year.
   Expenditures for costly items that are normally financed over
time already have fallen as indicated by the weak March auto sales
the car manufacturers reported earlier this week.
   Most analysts refused to attach too much significance to the
March numbers, preferring to defer judgment on the retail outlook
until April's sales are tallied.
   ``Realistically, we have to look at March and April combined to
get a good assessment of what's happening,'' said Jeffrey Edelman,
an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   For March, cold, stormy weather in parts of the country and the
loss of a selling day due to store closures for the Easter holiday
were cited as reasons for the mediocre results of several big
merchants.
   ``Sales during March were disappointing as colder-than-normal
weather adversely affected such key early spring businesses as our
outdoor garden shop, home improvement and ladies apparel,'' said K
mart Chairman Joseph E. Antonini.
   K mart, the second-largest U.S. retailer, said sales in the five
weeks ended March 29 were $2.42 billion, up 2.5 percent from $2.36
billion in March a year ago.
   Sales at K mart stores open for at least a year, called
comparable or same-store sales, slid 0.8 percent from the year-ago
level.
   Retailers and industry analysts say same-store sales give a
better reading of a company's performance than totals that include
sales at newly opened stores. Not every retailer reports same-store
sales.
   The biggest U.S. retailer, Sears, said sales were even better
than it hoped they would be in the month in which the company
introduced a new competitive pricing policy.
   Sears posted an 11.9 percent sales increase, to $2.97 billion
from $2.66 billion.
   Its same-store sales rose a healthy 9.6 percent and 15.4 percent
after adjustment for the loss of 2{ selling days due to Easter and
the closing of Sears' more than 800 stores nationwide for repricing
in preparation for the switch to an ``everyday low prices'' program.
   The gains at Sears may have cut into the sales growth at
competitors' stores, but analysts said it is too early to tell how
much of an impact Sears' new strategy is having.
   Elsewhere, specialty apparel retailers showed signs that the
sales rebound that began late last year has continued.
   Good results at stores such as the Gap Inc., Limited Inc. and
several department store chains, such as Neiman Marcus Group Inc.,
indicated current fashions were selling well.
   The figures released Thursday were from the biggest general
merchandise chains and apparel retailers. Unlike monthly retail
sales figures released by the government, they do not cover sales
at auto dealers, supermarkets or retaurants.
   Here are some of the results:
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the fast-growing discount and general
merchandise chain based in Bentonville, Ark., reported March sales
totaled $1.92 billion, up 26 percent from $1.53 billion in March
1988. Same-store sales rose 12 percent.
   J.C. Penney Co. said sales amounted to $1.233 billion in the
five weeks to April 1, up 0.7 percent from $1.225 billion a year
earlier. On a comparable store basis, sales fell 2 percent.
   Dayton Hudson Corp., a Minneapolis-based store operator, said
sales rose 6.4 percent in the five weeks ended April 1 to $1.1
billion from 1 billion. Comparable-store sales edged up 0.9 percent.
   F.W. Woolworth Co. said its domestic sales increased 5.4 percent
in the five weeks ended April 1 to $482 million from $457 million.
Domestic same-store sales rose 1.3 percent.
   Limited Inc.'s sales rose 15 percent in the five weeks ended
April 1 to $393.8 million from $343.3 million. Comparable store
sales were up 8 percent.
</TEXT>
