<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Employees     04-07 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Employees,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Employees: We'll Tighten Belts To Run Airline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines strikers, calling their monthlong
walkout a victory, say they're ready to take pay cuts and get back
to work _ as long as it's without boss Frank Lorenzo at the
controls.
   Cautious union leaders, however, warned the strike won't end
until new contracts are signed. But most workers jubilantly greeted
the sale to a group including former baseball commissioner Peter
Ueberroth as a done deal _ even though it reportedly involves some
$210 million in union concessions.
   The $464 million agreement would give employees a 30 percent
share in the company in exchange for wage concessions. Eastern,
under parent company Texas Air Corp., had demanded $125 million in
wage and benefits cuts.
   ``This is better than winning the lottery, because 30,000 people
won it together,'' said flight attendant Alice Martinez. ``It's
wonderful.''
   She and her husband Jorge, an Eastern mechanic, said all the
workers know current wage levels will be dropping. Mechanics, for
example, earn a top wage of $18.83 an hour and ramp service workers
$15.60 an hour. Pay at Eastern's major competitors ranges from $16
to $20.10 an hour for mechanics and $15.51 to $17.45 for ramp
service workers.
   But though the cuts will hurt, they said, they would gladly
sacrifice to save the Miami-based airline without Texas Air
Chairman Lorenzo.
   Moreover, broader issues were at stake, Martinez said.
   ``Whatever happens here at Eastern is going to dictate what
happens with the rest of the airlines, and in other industries
too,'' he said. ``We had been stripped of our dignity while we were
working for Frank Lorenzo _ now we have it back, and we are going
to rebuild the airline.''
   Employees blamed Lorenzo's attitude toward workers, not wage
disputes, for the atmosphere of crisis that culminated in the March
4 strike by 8,500 workers, mostly mechanics and baggage handlers.
Most Eastern pilots and flight attendants have refused to cross
picket lines.
   Ken Walters, an Eastern pilot, expressed the strikers'
widespread admiration for Ueberroth.
   ``The first thing that came out of his mouth was he wanted to
share the airline with the workers,'' Walters said. ``The first
thing to come out of Lorenzo's mouth was `I don't talk to unions.'
''
   Stephanie Orent, a mechanic, said she knew the economic
sacrifices made during the strike would be hard to make up, but
said it was worth it despite the expected pay cuts.
   ``I don't know what it translates into in dollars and cents, but
we're willing to give,'' she said. ``We'll just tighten our belts.
We all want Eastern to survive, and we can't wait to get back to
work.''
   Ramp service worker Jose Lorie said the cost of the walkout was
not just economic.
   ``I've been hurt, my wife's been hurt, economically, emotionally
_ my nerves have been affected. And we know the airline has been
hurt _ how much, we'll have to find out,'' he said.
   He said he was a little taken aback about suddenly becoming an
owner of a company he has been on strike against.
   ``My feelings are confused,'' he said. ``But I feel a lot better
now that I'll be a part of the airline. It's like something extra.''
   Not everyone was ecstatic about the sale, with some saying they
want to see the fine print.
   ``I've seen so much deception that I'm not going to pick up my
tools until I've seen (the contract),'' said Julio Valentine, a
terminal maintenance worker for 23 years, who said he had emptied
his bank account since the strike began.
   But even Valentine said that if union leaders recommended it, he
would be willing to make concessions to Ueberroth.
   Pilot Sal Fallovallita said the strike had brought Eastern
workers together as never before, and the new team spirit would
help in rebuilding the airline.
   ``People go where they get a good product,'' he said. ``And
we're going to give them a good product.''
</TEXT>
