<FIRST>d f PM-FarmScene     04-07 1004</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,1035</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beef Industry More Able to Ask, Where's the Fat?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Texas A&amp;M scientists say the beef industry
has done well by reducing the amount of fat served consumers in
their steaks and hamburgers, but they warned that the job isn't
finished.
   H. Russell Cross and Jeff Savell said work continues on
resolving questions about fats and health, notably the dietary
linkage to high levels of blood cholesterol.
   Savell on Thursday told a conference sponsored by the National
Cattlemen's Association that if he had to send cattle producers and
the beef industry a note from the teacher, it might say:
``Excellent progress made in making product fit consumers' needs.
Keep working on leanness, convenience and cost, value. Remember to
maintain taste, or consumers will go elsewhere.''
   The beef industry drew praise from Jay Fletcher of the Community
Nutrition Institute, a citizens' interest group that conducts
research on nutrition and food policy issues. Fletcher agreed that
less fat is being sold to consumers.
   ``I think they have done more than many other industries to
recognize the dangers of excessive fat consumption and take steps
to inform consumers about that,'' Fletcher said in a telephone
interview.
   But selling meat is also a business, he said, and the beef
industry wants to recover the market share it has steadily lost to
chicken and poultry in general over the past 10 years.
   Fletcher said that occurred ``largely because of consumer
perception of beef as a high-fat food.''
   It was just a year ago that the Agriculture Department released
a study by Texas A&amp;M, led by Cross and Savell, that showed the
trimmable fat on retail cuts of beef had been reduced 27 percent in
two years.
   The $45,000 study, paid for by the beef industry and USDA,
showed that the average thickness of fat on steaks and roasts from
primal cuts, or the major wholesale cuts of beef, was 0.14 inch,
while the average for all cuts, from chuck roast to stew meat, was
0.11 inch, or less than one-eighth of an inch.
   Most retailers have been using a quarter-inch beef fat trim, or
less, since 1985, compared with a standard of half an inch before
that, according to the industry.
   At the conference, Cross said consumers have indicated they
would pay for more closely trimmed beef, preferably with external
fat of less than one-eighth inch.
   Internal fat, or marbling, has been a factor in the taste of
beef, and Cross said this still is important to consumers. The
challenge, he said, is to take fat off beef, not out of it.
   Cross said that Texas A&amp;M meat scientists are currently working
with medicine researchers at Baylor College of Medicine and the
University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center on projects aimed
at further improvements in the healthfulness of beef.
   The work includes modification of the fatty acid content of meat
products through changes in cattle feeds and products themselves.
Fatty acids can potentially elevate cholestrol levels in human
blood. But Cross said that even now, only 27 percent of the total
fat in beef is the type of saturated fatty acid that can raise
cholesterol.
   Savell told of recent research on the composition of cooked as
well as raw beef with reduced or no external fat. For example, if a
slice of beef with all the fat trimmed off is cooked, the fat
content of the interior meat is reduced by 20 percent from a slice
with a quarter-inch layer of fat.
   That is because less fat migrates from the outside into the meat
tissue.
   ``When you trim the fat off a steak that has a half inch of fat,
you get rid of half the total cholesterol,'' Savell said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the Soviet
Union has bought more U.S. corn and that China has been sold wheat
at subsidized prices.
   Officials said Thursday the Soviet purchase was for 400,000
metric tons of corn to be delivered this year and that the wheat
sale to China was for 300,000 tons. Both deliveries are scheduled
for this year.
   More than 2.7 million tons have been purchased since the Soviets
resumed buying U.S. corn on March 28 after a layoff of almost three
months.
   The latest sales brought total corn sold to the Soviets for
1988-89 to almost 13 million tons. Additionally, sales include 4
million tons of wheat, 450,000 tons of soybeans, 1.4 million tons
of soybean meal, and 507,400 tons of grain sorghum.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 400,000 tons of
corn would be about 15.8 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.45 per bushel at the
farm level, according to the latest USDA five-day average, meaning
that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $39 million.
   John J. Reddington, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said the wheat was part
of 2 million tons authorized Feb. 27 for China under the Export
Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition
in selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   The latest sale boosted to about 8.5 million tons the amount of
wheat sold to China for 1988-89 delivery under EEP.
   Reddington said the latest sales were handled by Garnac Grain
Co. Inc., 50,000 tons; Bunge Corp., 50,000; Bartlett and Co.,
100,000; and Continental Grain Co., 100,000.
   He said the wheat will carry an average subsidy rate of $6.33
per ton, or about 17 cents a bushel. About 910,000 tons are still
available under the current authorization.
   The 300,000 tons would be about 11 million bushels and, at
recent prices of about $3.96 per bushel, would have a farm value of
around $44 million.
</TEXT>
