<FIRST>r f PM-AmericanExpansion     04-07 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-American Expansion,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Adds 24 Flights In Eastern's Absence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taking advantage of Eastern Airlines' monthlong
absence from the regional market, American Airlines plans to add 11
flights in Miami and 13 in the Caribbean by June.
   American officials Thursday said the move resulted from
long-term planning by the airline, saying the strike by Eastern's
machinists union merely pushed ahead American's expansion program.
   The strike that started March 4 has reduced Eastern's service to
less than 10 percent of its normal daily flight roster.
   Thursday's announcement that Peter Ueberroth's group is buying
Eastern and plans to return the Miami-based carrier to full
operation appeared not to bother American's senior vice president
for operations, Robert Baker.
   ``The likelihood is that Eastern will still be the largest
carrier'' in the region, said Baker. ``None of what we have
announced today will rise and fall on what happens to Eastern
Airlines or anyone else.''
   American's new schedule raises the carrier's flights from 20 to
31 a day out of Miami and from 45 to 52 a day out of San Juan,
Puerto Rico.
   Baker said Eastern's troubles were not a major factor in the
expansion plans, noting that American announced last August _ long
before Eastern's labor-management showdown _ that it would install
a new crew base here.
   But Baker said American quickly decided to follow through on the
plan when the Eastern strike began March 4.
</TEXT>
