<FIRST>r f PM-GrainTalks     04-07 0113</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grain Talks,0117</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks with Soviets Open Late This Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Soviet Union officials will meet
April 26 to open semiannual discussions about the long-term grain
agreement between the two countries, the Agriculture Department
says.
   The meetings are required under the pact, which was extended
after negotiations last year. The agreement specifies that the
Soviet Union will buy a minimum quantity of wheat and corn from the
United States each year.
   The department said Thursday that the meetings in Washington
``will include a review of the worldwide, U.S. and Soviet grain
situations and the status of purchases and shipments under the
agreement.''
</TEXT>
