<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0852EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Budget     04-07 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says White House Shows New Flexibility on Taxes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House is showing new flexibility on
taxes but agreement with Congress on any specifics is not imminent,
the chairman of the Senate Finance Committee says.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said Thursday, that Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady and President Bush's budget director
Richard Darman indicated in a meeting that the president would
accept modifications of his plan to cut the capital gains tax rate
and other tax proposals in his fiscal 1990 budget.
   But the capital gains plan, which the administration claims
would raise $4.8 billion next year, still stood little chance of
passage, Bentsen said.
   ``There is great disagreement on which taxes to raise, or user
fees as the administration prefers,'' said Bentsen. ``We have a lot
of negotiating to do on that and I'm not sure how it will come
out,'' Bentsen said.
   The Gramm-Rudman law mandates reducing the deficit to $100
billion in fiscal 1990, which would require about $28 billion in
new revenues or in spending restraint, according to White House
estimates.
   Bentsen said there was widespread agreement that about $14
billion in new revenues will be included in a budget package this
year. That includes not only about $5.6 billion in taxes, but sales
of government assets, user fees, and increased enforcement of
existing taxes.
   Brady and Darman declined to comment on whether the White House
was revising the $14 billion in revenues in its fiscal 1990 budget.
   Bentsen said the administration ``absolutely'' could find
revenue-raising ideas that Congress would accept. But he did not
offer any specifics, and said he doubted any would be nailed down
soon.
   ``No way they are going to get that (agreement by today) on the
revenue side,'' he said.
   The meeting with Bentsen was one of a series of visits Brady and
Darman have had with senior members of the House and Senate
tax-writing committees. They also continued talks with
congressional budget-writers on an overall spending and revenue
framework for the new fiscal year which begins Oct. 1.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said Thursday's discussions focused on spending
restraint on entitlement programs, including agriculture subsidies.
   Panetta said he was still hopeful a broad consensus could be
reached on Friday, but he softened his talk of moving ahead
immediately with his own package in his committee if the
negotiations drag on.
   ``I'm hopeful, but I think there's also a chance that we are
going to slip into next week,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
