<HEAD>No. 2 Official Leaving</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department's No. 2 official,
Deputy Secretary M. Peter McPherson, is leaving the agency to
become an executive vice president of Bank of America.
   The departure of McPherson, who had been deputy secretary since
August 1987, was expected. President Bush in February announced
plans to nominate John E. Robson, dean of the business school and a
professor of business management at Emory University, to succeed
McPherson.
   McPherson had served as acting treasury secretary between the
departure of James Baker III last August and the confirmation of
Nicholas Brady in September. From 1981 to 1987, he served as
administrator of the Agency for International Development and as
chairman of the board of the Overseas Private Investment Corp.
   The department said Thursday that McPherson would serve as Bank
of America's director of debt restructuring and have responsibility
for all the bank's negotiations on Third World debt.
</TEXT>
