<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Inflation     04-07 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Inflation,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Inflation Reaches 5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices in Western Europe rose a hefty
0.5 percent in February, raising the annual average inflation rate
to 5 percent, the highest in 37 months, the EEC statistics agency
Eurostat said Friday.
   The 5 percent annual rate was up from 4.8 percent in January,
when consumer prices rose an average 0.7 percent in the 12 European
Economic Community nations, Eurostat reported.
   February's price hikes lifted the EEC annual inflation rate past
that of the United States, which ended February with an annual rate
of 4.8 percent after having been above the EEC level since April
1987.
   In February prices rose most sharply in Portugal, 1.4 percent;
Italy 0.8 percent; and Britain 0.7 percent, Eurostat said.
   February's price rises were `` more moderate in Belgium (up 0.4
percent), in Germany, France, the Netherlands, Luxembourg (all up
0.3 percent) and in Spain (up 0.2 percent),'' it added.
   ``The Greek index showed a decrease of (0.4 percent) owing to
the winter sales of clothing and footwear.''
   Eurostat provided these annual inflation rates for the EEC
nations individually:
   The Netherlands, 1 percent; West Germany and Belgium, both 2.6
percent; Luxembourg, 2.7 percent; Ireland, 3.3 percent; France, 3.4
percent; Denmark, 4.4 percent; Italy, 6.1 percent; Spain, 6.2
percent; Great Britain, 7.8 percent; Portugal, 12.1 percent and
Greece, 13.8 percent.
   It gave these corresponding rates for non-EEC nations:
Switzerland and Austria, both 2.3 percent; Norway, 4.9 percent;
Sweden, 6.4 percent and Finland, 6 percent.
</TEXT>
