<FIRST>r f PM-Coleco-Bankruptcy     04-07 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coleco-Bankruptcy,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coleco Board Approves New Reorganization Plan, Decides Not To Sell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GORDON FAIRCLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of directors of Coleco
Industries Inc., once one of the nation's largest toy companies,
has dropped plans to sell the company in a reversal of an earlier
decision.
   The reversal was made as the board voted to amend its bankruptcy
reorganization plan to head off complaints that the company is not
offering its unsecured creditors adequate compensation.
   Morton E. Handel, chairman of Coleco's board of directors, said
the board decided against pursuing a sale of the company on the
grounds that maintaining Coleco ``as an independent, ongoing
business is in the best interests of the creditors and
shareholders.''
   In February, the board of directors had authorized management to
explore selling Coleco as a means of solving its financial problems.
   The new reorganization plan, announced Thursday, ``is intended
to satisfy the needs expressed by the unsecured creditors'' during
bankruptcy proceedings in New York federal court, Handel stated.
   The Avon, Conn.-based company, which makes Cabbage Patch dolls
and other toys, filed for protection from creditors under Chapter
11 of the federal bankruptcy laws in July 1988.
   Coleco's unsecured creditors have criticized a reorganization
plan filed by the company in January, saying it did not offer them
enough.
   U.S. District Judge Prudence B. Abram, who is presiding over the
bankruptcy proceedings, said last month Coleco should not be
surprised that most creditors objected strongly to the original
plan. Abram said, ``I can't think of another plan where I've seen
the unsecured creditors so wholly wiped out as they are in this
case''
   The board of directors said the amended version would
``represent a substantial improvement for the unsecured
creditors,'' who include bondholders, manufacturers and advertising
agencies. Coleco owes them more than $400 million.
   Under the proposed amendment, which must be approved by the
federal bankruptcy court, the unsecured creditors will receive
stock in Coleco, giving them ownership of about 37 percent of the
company.
   Handel said the unsecured creditors will also receive a package
of ``other securities, cash, notes and other debt instruments.''
Handel said the package will be worth about $40 million, or 10
cents per dollar of their claims.
   The amendment also calls for the secured creditors, those first
in line for repayment, to convert their current claim of about $80
million into Coleco common stock, giving them 60 percent ownership
of the company.
   The remaining approximately 3 percent of the company will stay
in the hands of current owners of preferred and common stock.
   Handel said the proposal has been approved by the secured
creditors, New York financiers Isaac Perlmutter and Bernard Marden.
He said it would be submitted to the bankruptcy court in New York
before April 25.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0267 </DOCNO>
