<FIRST>r f BC-Malaysia-Boeing     04-07 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Malaysia-Boeing,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Malaysia Airlines To Buy Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its single largest deal,
government-owned Malaysia Airlines will buy at least 16 U.S.-made
Boeing 737 jetliners for about $400 million, the airline's managing
director said Friday.
   The purchase is part of the airline's expansion and
modernization program, Abdul Aziz Abdul Rahman told reporters after
signing an agreement with Singer Link Miles Co. of Britain to buy a
Boeing 737-400 flight simulator.
   The deal would involve 10 Boeing 737-400 aircraft and six or
seven 737-500 aircraft, Aziz said. The new planes will replace the
airline's 12 aging Boeing 737-200 aircraft.
   He said Malaysia Airlines is expected to sign a purchase
agreement with Seattle-based Boeing Co. next month. The aircraft
are expected to be delivered by 1992, he said.
   The purchase of the flight simulator will enable pilots to
become familiar with the plane before the airline takes delivery of
the aircraft, Aziz said.
   The airline's Boeing 737-200 jets, which have been in service
since 1972, are no longer produced by Boeing, and Malaysia Airlines
is expected to auction them off to other airlines.
   Separately, the carrier recently signed an agreement with
International Lease Finance Corp. of California to lease seven new
Boeing 737-400 planes for delivery between 1990 and July 1991.
</TEXT>
