<FIRST>r f BC-ElephantBoots     04-07 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Elephant Boots,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acme Drops Elephant Hide From Exotic Line</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acme Boot's elephant-skin boots will
vanish from stores by mid-summer as production of the $200-a-pair
footwear ceases because of possible poaching in Africa.
   Acme, the world's largest boot manufacturer, dropped the line of
casual boots this week after several years of production. The
60-year-old company continues to make footwear from the skins of
exotic creatures including the ostrich, snake, lizard, alligator
and eel.
   Acme, based in Clarksville, Tenn., said its purchases of African
elephant hides, made through an importer, were legal. But special
interest groups had questioned the treatment of elephants by others.
   ``We have seen increased concern by environmentalists and
consumer groups about illegal poaching for tusks, not for hides,''
said Bill Whitlock, Acme vice president of marketing.
   ``They have run ads showing grotesque pictures,'' he said
Thursday. ``This drew our concern. We thought it best to
disassociate ourselves with it in general even though this involved
tusks and not hides.''
   No special interest groups had contacted Acme about dropping the
line. ``There was no pressure,'' Whitlock said.
   The elephant-skin boots, which were dyed mostly in light colors
to fit a casual image, accounted for less than 1 percent of Acme's
total production.
   ``The boots are very masculine, rugged looking,'' Whitlock said.
``They were tough; they wore well and had a long life. They went
well with jeans.''
   Acme, which employs 2,200, has plants in Clarksville and
Waverly, Tenn.,; El Paso, Texas, and Corcoran, Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
