<DOCNO> AP890407-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0940EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;Ls 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 1st Ld-Writethru,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Votes Down to Make Certain States Help Pay for S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Recasts lead and 11th graf, This would, to make clear that Frank
remark made after vote; also moving general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional panel rejected an attempt to
force Texas and other states with lax regulations to help pay for
the savings and loan mess, a provision one member said would have
started a ``second Civil War.''
   Meeting as regulatory agencies made two announcements
underscoring the urgency of swift action, the House Banking
subcommittee on financial institutions on Thursday also decided to
permit regulators to charge higher deposit insurance premiums to
institutions engaged in speculative lending.
   By a 27-20 vote, the subcommittee authorized the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp., if it chooses, to levy higher premiums against
S&amp;Ls and banks making high-risk investments.
   The Bush administration opposes the measure. It is trying to
prevent delay of its S&amp;L rescue package by deferring ticklish
deposit insurance issues until the completion of an 18-month study.
   The FDIC said it took over 38 institutions, bringing the total
number of S&amp;Ls under its supervision to 215 in 31 states. The
agency is attempting to hold losses down at the sickest S&amp;Ls until
Congress appropriates the money to close or merge them.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board said the industry
suffered $9.4 billion in withdrawals in February, the 10th
consecutive month of outflows and down only slightly from the $10.6
billion record in January.
   The House subcommittee, in the first of three scheduled all-day
sessions, slogged through 48 of 165 proposed amendments, adopting
two that would increase the power of the FDIC over S&amp;Ls and deny
the Bush administration some of the political control it had sought
over the agency.
   But it was a push by Northern legislators to force Texas,
California, Florida and other states with lax regulation of
state-chartered S&amp;Ls to pay part of the bailout cost that generated
the most heated debate.
   The panel voted 39-7 against an amendment sponsored by Reps.
Paul E. Kanjorski, D-Pa., and Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, requiring
states with high numbers of state-chartered thrift failures to
contribute 20 percent of the cost of bailing them out.
   The measure drew considerable sympathy, but committee members
argued against it for political reasons.
   ``This would have sent the bill to Fort Sumter. It would have
started the second Civil War,'' Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said
after the vote.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, argued that attaching punitive measures
to the S&amp;L bill could draw a veto from President Bush: ``All I ask
the people here is, with this provision, is there a slight chance
that a Texan in the White House will sign it?''
   Kanjorski and Kaptur argued that Texas will get the lion's share
of the bailout, $31 billion, representing $1,856 for every man,
woman and child in the state, while most other states will pay more
than they get, $479 per capita in Connecticut, for instance.
   ``What we are involved in here ... is the most mammoth transfer
of resources from many regions of the country to one region of the
country in the history of the republic. Everything else done by the
government pales in comparison,'' said Rep. John J. LaFalce, D-N.Y.
   However, Rep. Steve Bartlett, R-Texas, said the measure was
unconstitutional, arguing, ``This is an excellent amendment for
those who wish to vent anger, but it is bad law.''
   Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the full banking
panel, called the amendment an ``outlandish'' and ``shoddily
written concoction.''
   The FDIC was one of the big winners in Thursday's session. It
won support on a 35-12 vote for an amendment giving it, rather than
the Federal Home Loan Bank System, primary authority over
state-chartered S&amp;Ls.
   The measure was sponsored by Leach, who intended it as a rebuke
to the bank system. S&amp;Ls' chief lobby group, the U.S. League of
Savings Institutions, said in a letter Thursday that they oppose a
similar measure before the Senate Banking Committee.
   In a move to secure the political independence of the FDIC, the
House panel provided fixed four-year terms to its chairman and vice
chairman. The Bush administration had proposed that the chairman
serve at the pleasure of the president. It also increased the
FDIC's borrowing limit.
   Meanwhile, the Senate Banking Committee concluded three days of
behind-closed-door meetings intended to smooth the way for a full
Senate vote the week of April 17. The House subcommittee plans to
finish its version of the bill next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
