<FIRST>r f PM-PerotTrial 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Perot Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Partially in Perot's Favor in Breach of Contract Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 2-3, The ruling, to CORRECT location of EDS; also
moved general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled partially in favor of Texas
billionaire H. Ross Perot in a breach of contract suit brought by
the company he founded but later sold, allowing him to continue
operating his new Perot Systems Co. provided he makes no profit.
   The ruling on Thursday by Fairfax Circuit Court Judge William
Plummer followed four hours of debate by attorneys representing
Perot and Electronic Data Systems, the company based in Plano,
Texas, he had founded.
   Attorneys for EDS described Perot as ``resolved to ruin'' his
former company. EDS is trying to stop Perot from operating his
company and from recruiting employees away from EDS.
   Perot's lawyers replied that EDS was overstating his contractual
obligations to his former company and was laying legal traps to
hold off a feared business adversary.
   Plummer left a final decision on the recruiting issue for Monday
when the trial reconvenes, but he gave an opinion on the matter
Thursday that seemed to be a compromise.
   The judge said Perot may recruit from among his former EDS
colleagues _ but only those who were employed by the company before
December 1986, when a non-competition contract between the two
firms was signed. The usual contract prohibiting employees from
joining a competing enterprise would be waived in the case of Perot
Systems, because the contract acknowledged their special allegiance
to Perot, the judge said.
   EDS claimed Perot had intended to recruit from within its ranks
``in perpetuity'' _ luring away the company's best talent even
after the non-competition contract lapses in December.
   It said Perot already has raided EDS of 150 to 200 employees,
including eight executives.
</TEXT>
