<FIRST>r f PM-Scalia-Drugs     04-07 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scalia-Drugs,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Justice Calls Drug Testing Excessive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Permitting random drug tests of employees is
``going off the deep end a little bit'' to fight the drug crisis,
U.S. Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia said.
   In a lecture Thursday at the University of Georgia School of
Law, Scalia called the U.S. Constitution ``not only the token but
indeed the substance of what continues to bind us together as a
people.'' But he said the document will last ``only as long as it
endures in the hearts and minds of the people.''
   He said the court is merely a reflection of society and its
beliefs. And he warned that opposition to drugs could erode
people's rights.
   ``We are facing a particular crisis. ... I feel we have gone off
the deep end a little to meet that crisis,'' Scalia said.
   ``If society continues to feel that way 50 or 60 years from now,
you are going to have justices on the court who were plucked from
that society,'' he said. ``I can't save you from yourselves.''
   Scalia, a conservative named to the high court in 1986 by
then-President Reagan, wrote a stinging dissent in a Supreme Court
decision in March upholding drug testing for some U.S. Customs
officers, though in another case decided at the same time he backed
tests for railway workers after accidents.
   He was greeted at Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport by a
handful of anti-bortion demonstrators but left via a side exit.
   In Athens, a small group favoring legal abortions stood quietly
outside the auditorium holding a banner reading, ``We won't go
back.''
</TEXT>
