<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-OPEC-Production     04-07 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-OPEC-Production,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Crude Production Slips in March, According to Estimates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The OPEC nations produced about 19.6
million barrels of oil a day in March, slightly under the level of
February but still ahead of their output targets, according to
estimates released Friday.
   The International Energy Agency said in its Monthly Oil Market
Report that estimated production by the 13-nation Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries slipped about 200,000 barrels a day
last month.
   Total output was estimated at 19.8 million barrels a day in
February and 20.2 million barrels in January.
   The OPEC countries agreed in November to reduce their output to
18.5 million barrels a day in the first half of this year from more
than 22 million in an effort to push up prices.
   Since the accord, prices have rallied more than expected,
surpassing OPEC's target of $18 a barrel. The average price of a
basket of seven crudes monitored by OPEC reached $18.57 a barrel
this week.
   A panel of eight OPEC ministers met last week in Vienna and
reaffirmed their commitment to the accord.
   All 13 ministers will meet in early June to decide the output
levels for the second half of the year. Observers have said the
ministers would likely boost the production ceiling if prices held
at their current levels.
   The report by the International Energy Agency estimated world
oil supply _ outside such centrally planned economies as the Soviet
Union _ at 50 million barrels a day in March, about the same as in
the previous month.
   The oil tanker accident off the Port of Valdez reduced
production in Alaska's Prudhoe Bay to 800,000 from 2 million
barrels a day, the report said.
   ``Shipping is being resumed on a limited basis, which if it
continues should restore Alaskan supplies to normal levels in the
near future,'' it said.
   It said production in industrialized nations belonging to the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development registered
about 16.4 million barrels a day last month, up 200,000 barrels
from February. About two-dozen developed nations, including the
United States, belong to the OECD.
   The report said oil consumption by those industrialized nations
in the first quarter of this year was 38 million barrels a day, up
1.6 percent from the first three months of 1988.
   ``In North America,'' it said, ``there was moderate consumption
growth in most products, with jet fuel growth very strong.''
   Consumption increased in Japan, it said, because of strong
economic growth.
   For all of this year, the report estimated oil consumption in
the industrialized nations would increase by less than 2 percent.
Most of the gain, it said, would likely be in fuel used in
transportation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1416EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv10   04-07 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 10,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, April 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Three-Month T-Bill Takes Spotlight In First Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation fears drove up interest rates and
depressed most of the credit markets during the first quarter, but
three-month Treasury bills and junk bonds stood out among the pack,
analysts say.
   A quarterly analysis by Moody's Investors Service Inc. released
this past week found that high-yield, high-risk ``junk'' bonds had
the best rate of return in the January-March period, roughly 2.2
percent.
   Three-month T-bills had almost as good a return: 2.1 percent
return.
   But junk bonds contain a risk of default that must be factored
in when considering their return, said John Lonski, a senior
economist with the securities-rating firm.
   ``One would have to say that the superior performance adjusted
for risk unquestionably belonged to the three-month Treasury
bill,'' Lonski said.
   By comparison, investment-grade corporate bonds provided a
return of about 1.4 percent; and long-term Treasuries, those of
7-30 years maturity, 1.1 percent.
   A separate index of government and corporate bonds compiled by
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. showed a total return of 1.1 percent in
the quarter.
   The rate of return includes accrued interest plus any capital
gains through price increases.
   Investors that fared best during the quarter followed a
so-called ``barbell strategy,'' which calls for concentrating
investments on the two extremes of the spectrum, short-term bills
and long-term bonds, according to James L. Kochan, chief
fixed-income strategist for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   The plan paid off during the first quarter because short-term
rates jumped while prices of long-term bonds held up fairly well,
he said.
   Three-month Treasury bills yielded 8.39 percent on Jan. 3, the
first trading day of the year. On March 31, they yielded 9.18
percent.
   The 30-year Treasury yielded 9.08 percent on Jan. 3, and 9.09
percent on March 31, though it fluctuated many times due to
economic news that jolted the market.
   Prices and yields on bonds move in opposite directions, so a
high yield means a low price.
   The situation in which the yield on the three-month T-bill
surpasses the 30-year Treasury bond's yield is what Wall Street
calls an ``inverted yield curve.''
   The yield curve, which illustrates the difference between
short-and long-term interest rates, normally slopes upward to the
right, with longer-maturing issues yielding more than shorter
issues to reflect the risk of keeping money tied up.
   But short-term rates rose during the quarter amid concerns that
worsening inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income
securities, would lead to further credit tightening by the Federal
Reserve.
   An inverted yield curve is sometimes viewed as an early warning
of a recession because it means shorter rates have risen so high
that they could choke off economic growth.
   The inflation news during the first quarter brought concern
among the credit markets. The government reported that wholesale
prices rose 1 percent in January and February.
   Since then, several other government-issued economic reports
have indicated the economy might be slowing, easing fears of
inflation and adding a lift to the credit markets.
   Prices of long-term bonds have risen back to the range
prevailing before the March 17 figures, indicating a high degree of
resiliency in the bond market, Kochan said.
   ``It's extraordinary, really. It's probably performing better
than any of us had any right to expect,'' said Kochan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Monday, April 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1130EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-07 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0246</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices were lower and soybeans and
other grain prices were mixed early today on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Reports that farmers have been holding onto their corn and news
that the Soviet Union has bought 400,000 metric tons of U.S. corn
buttressed futures trading in that product, analysts said.
   Rain and a forecast for more rain on the drought-stricken
farmlands of Kansas weighed on wheat prices, they said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 3{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.97 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to } cent higher, with May at $2.66\ a bushel; oats were \ cent to
1 cent higher, with May at $1.87; and soybeans were 1} cent lower
to 1 cent higher, with May at $7.15 a bushel.
   Most livestock and meat prices were lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, cattle were .10 cent higher to .30 cent lower,
with the contract for delivery in April at 77.77 cents a pound,
feeder cattle were .10 cent to .87 cent lower, with April at 77.80
cents pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .27 cent lower, with April
at 39.75 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .10 cent to
.42 cent lower, with April at 34.25 cents a pound.
   On Thursday, livestock and meat prices were lower.
</TEXT>
