<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1201EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debate Resumes With Bush Vowing Not to Budge ``One Inch''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Bush comments, debate resuming; Pickup
graf 4 pvs, Sponsors were hoping; also moved general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today he had ``no
intention of budging one inch'' from his minimum-wage proposal as
Senate Democrats moved forward with their plan to raise the base
wage higher than Bush has said he will support.
   It was the second veto threat from the president in as many
days, and Bush's clearest statement about the fate of the
Democrat-sponsored plan if it reached his desk.
   ``We fired our best shot and last shot and only shot first,''
Bush said at a meeting with reporters. ``I have no inention of
budging one inch on this. I have too much at stake.''
   That drew fire from one leading supporter of the Senate
Democrats' plan, as debate on it resumed today.
   ``Don't give us a take-it-or-leave-it proposal,'' said Sen.
Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio. ``That's the kind of administration
we've had the last eight years. Confrontation. Confrontation.
Confrontation.''
   Sponsors were hoping for a final vote today but were unable to
reach agreement with Republicans, meaning the debate likely will
extend into next week. Amendments lowering the final minimum wage
target to $4.55 from $4.65 and providing for a 60-day subminimum
wage for new workers were likely to be offered with the resumption
of debate today.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, the Republican floor leader, urged
Democrats to accept Bush's proposal as a compromise.
   ``President Bush has extended an opportunity to the Congress to
enact a minimum wage increase,'' Hatch said. ``In my opinion, it is
a worthy alternative to the proposal now before us.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass. and chief sponsor of the Senate
bill, entered into a compromise with Southern Democrats over the
$4.55 top minimum that appears to give him more than enough votes
to win passage.
   Bush, however, appears to have the votes necessary to sustain a
veto.
   The amendments would bring the Senate bill in line with a
House-passed measure. Whether the bill would go straight to Bush
appears dependent on the Senate provisions for the subminimum. The
proposal being discussed late Thursday was slightly different from
what is in the House bill.
   The House-passed bill allows a subminimum to be paid to new
hires for two months but only if it was their first job. The
tentative Senate provision allows the subminimum to be paid to any
worker in that worker's first 60 days in the job market, regardless
of how many jobs the person held in that period. Both proposals
would abolish the subminimum in October 1992.
   Kennedy opened the debate by saying Bush's support for some
increase was a welcome change after the Reagan administration's
dogged opposition to any boost.
   ``Eight years of stonewalling against the minimum wage are
over,'' said Kennedy. Still, he said Bush's proposal ``gives too
little protection'' to the nation's low-wage workers.
   The minimum wage has been $3.35 since 1981.
   Both the House-passed bill and the amendments Kennedy promised
to support would raise the hourly minimum wage to $3.85 on Oct. 1,
to $4.25 on Oct. 1, 1990, and to $4.55 a year later.
   Bush's proposal calls for an increase to $3.65 on Jan. 1, 1990,
to $3.95 a year later and a final jump to $4.25 on Jan. 1, 1992.
The president's measure would allow employers to pay new workers
$3.35 an hour for their first six months. That subminimum would
rise to $3.40 an hour in 1992.
</TEXT>
