<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     04-07 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0294</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market struggled to a small gain today
following what analysts described as an ambiguous report on
employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.87 to 2,297.84 by
noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 6 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 652 up, 568 down and
563 unchanged.
   The Labor Department reported this morning that the unemployment
rate declined to 5.0 percent, a new 15-year low, in March, from 5.1
percent the month before. That surprised analysts, who had been
looking for a small increase.
   By contrast, the data also showed a smaller-than-expected gain
of 180,000 in nonfarm payroll employment, providing some support
for the view that the economy has been slowing since early this
year.
   Brokers said the overall result was something of a letdown,
however, since many investors had been hoping for a more clear-cut
signal that pressures were abating on inflation and interest rates.
   That left stocks in the same listless, drifting pattern that
prevailed for the past several sessions while traders awaited the
employment figures.
   The strongest buying showed up in the recently depressed
technology sector. International Business Machines rose 1| to 109|;
Digital Equipment 1] to 97]; Honeywell 2] to 73\; Hewlett-Packard
1{ to 53\, and Apple Computer, traded in the over-the-counter
market, 1 to 37.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.49 to 166.51. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .09 at 329.99.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 73.49 million shares at
noontime, against 70.55 million at the same point Thursday.
</TEXT>
