<FIRST>r f BC-GATT-WorldTrade 1stLd-Writethru   04-07 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-GATT-World Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with deal confirmed, details, more quotes,
no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trade negotiators from more than 100 countries
reached an agreement in principle Friday on agricultural subsidies,
officials said.
   Informal talks resolved remaining disputes on European Economic
Community farm subsidies and the issue of ``food security,'' the
officials said.
   ``The book is closed on agriculture. We have reached an
accord,'' chief EC farm negotiator Guy Legras told a press
conference.
   But he added that ``an enormous amount of work'' remains in
continuing world trade talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade. He predicted ``intense and difficult'' negotiations over
the next 1{ years.
   The tentative accord, which delegates were expected to approve
formally later Friday, calls for an overall cap on farm supports
and import barriers through 1990, Legras and other officials said.
   It also calls for countries to reduce their subsidies in 1990
but does not specify by how much, chief Canadian negotiator Germain
Denis said.
   The pact meets a Community demand of letting the European
trading bloc bring up in future negotiations the issue of
redistributing its agricultural subsidies, Legras said.
   He said that senior officials, after three days of
GATT-sponsored negotiations, had set ``clear and precise''
objectives for the remainder of the running round of world trade
talks under GATT.
   Denis said a committee will meet in six months to assess
compliance with the farm accord. However, violators face no
penalties.
   The issue of food security, which preoccupied Japan, Indonesia,
the Nordic countries and Switzerland, was resolved by requiring
negotiators to address the problem in the next 20 months, Denis
said.
   Officials said those countries were worried that liberalized
trade arrangements could leave them dependent on food imports.
   In the other main dispute, the Community insisted on the right
to redistribute its payments to farmers even while reducing their
overall level. The United States and other producer countries
charged the European approach ran counter to the goal of
liberalizing trade under the current set of GATT talks, known as
the Uruguay Round.
   GATT spokesman David Woods said progress also was made regarding
trade in textiles and clothing, patents and other intellectual
property rights, and safeguards, or escape clauses for countries
confronted with a sudden surge of imports.
   Those issues, together with the clash over farm policy, held up
other agreements reached at a GATT ministerial meeting in Montreal
last December. The current four-year round of talks is due to end
at the end of 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
