<FIRST>u f BC-ChryslerProxy     04-07 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chrysler Proxy,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iacocca Earned $3.7 Million in 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca last year
received nearly $3.7 million in cash, benefits and stock, far below
the $17.9 million he received the year before, the company said
Friday.
   In proxy statements being mailed to shareholders, Chrysler said
the 64-year-old Iacocca received about $1.47 million in salary and
incentive payments, $2.2 million in stocks or exercised stock
options and $12,000 in company contributions to a savings plan.
   The previous year, Iacocca received $13.5 million in stock
options and $1.49 million in salary, benefits and incentive
compensation. The rest came in stock and cash bonuses and a stock
grant.
   The United Auto Workers union, which called Iacocca's 1987
payment ``an incredible ripoff,'' did not immediately comment on
the 1988 figures.
   Chrysler Vice Chairman Gerald Greenwald, Iacocca's likely
successor, received $1.2 million in salary, benefits and stocks;
Chrysler Motors Corp. Chairman Bennett Bidwell received $1.2
million; Chrysler Motors President Robert Lutz received $979,256,
and Executive Vice President for Finance Robert Miller received
$902,453.
   In addition, the top five officers also received stock options,
with various redemption values, to buy shares at $25.88 each.
Iacocca received options on 120,000 shares; Greenwald, 75,000;
Bidwell and Lutz, 60,000 each; and Miller, 45,000.
   Chrysler common stock was trading at about $24.13 a share at
midday Friday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Chrysler was the first of the Big Three automakers to release
its proxy statement. Ford Motor Co.'s is expected to be released
next week and General Motors Corp.'s the following week.
</TEXT>
