<DOCNO> AP890407-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1334EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AtlantisLicense     04-07 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Atlantis License,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>NJ Casino Commission Rejects Atlantis License Renewal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Casino Control Commission voted
unanimously Friday to reject Elsinore's Atlantis Casino Hotel
application for license renewal, the first such denial in New
Jersey's decade-old casino industry.
   Commission Chairman Walter Read said the financially troubled
casino failed to demonstrate the financial resources, business
ability or integrity to merit an extension of its current license.
The Atlantis license expires next Friday.
   ``The conclusion is inescapable,'' Read said. ``The ESA
(Elsinore's Shore Associates) has not demonstrated these. If we
were to grant relicensure, these standards would be rendered
meaningless.''
   Elsinore Shore Associates is Atlantis' parent company.
   The commission now has to decide what to do next with the
Atlantis _ close it down or appoint a conservator.
   Elsinore lawyer Harry Levin had asked the commissioners Thursday
to grant the license with the understanding the company could meet
standards long enough to find a buyer. The casino says any chance
of fetching a fair price would be spoiled by a closing or
appointment of a conservator.
   Levin cited the owners' ``obligations'' to stockholders,
employees and creditors _ who are owed an estimated $2 million in
overdue payments.
   ``It occurs to all of us that the one certain way to make
certain all of these entities are made whole and all constituents
are served is to allow us to dispose of this property in a normal,
orderly fashion,'' Levin said.
   Elsinore president Jeanne Hood testified earlier in the week
that several prospective buyers have surfaced and that a sale
likely can be completed in coming months.
   But state lawyer David Arrajj told commissioners Thursday that
state gaming regulators have already given the Atlantis more than
enough leeway in allowing the company to stay in business while it
worked through bankruptcy reorganization over the last three years.
   He said Elsinore merely has posted more big losses and fallen
deeper into debt. He also cited the casino's admission in testimony
that it failed on occasion to maintain the state-required minimum
reserve, aimed at ensuring payoff on a gambler's big winnings.
   ``This is not the mark of an applicant possessed with sufficient
ability to justify licensure,'' Arrajj said.
   He said allowing the Atlantis to stay open on shaky financial
ground would heighten the risk of organized crime and other dangers
the state Casino Control Act was designed to prevent.
   Levin took offense and said the Atlantis owners and management
have always demonstrated exemplary conduct regardless of their
financial struggle.
   ``Anytime you have a business that goes out of business _
anytime a book gets burned _ it's bad for everybody,'' Levin told
reporters after Thursday's hearing.
   In movement on its other front, Elsinore argued before the
bankruptcy court Wednesday that ``chaos'' would reign if the gaming
hall lost its license.
   Closing arguments came less than 24 hours after the Atlantis
owners went before federal court to seek protection from state
action to close down the casino or appoint a conservator.
   The judge denied the owners' bid for immediate protection but
did not rule out action after the commission made its decision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
