<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0044,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout with closing figures.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed lower Friday on the London
Stock Exchange, but some bargain-hunting lifted prices above the
day's lows.
   Shares opened sharply lower with the Financial Times-Stock
Exchange 100-share index dropping nearly 25 points in the first few
minutes of trading.
   The 100-share index closed 6.8 points, or 0.3 percent, lower at
2,045.7, near the day's high of 2,045.9 which came shortly before
the close.
   Volume was 475.7 million shares, down from 758.3 million shares
Thursday.
   Some bearish British economic forecasts by two major British
brokerage firms helped depress the market for most of Friday's
trading session.
   But those lower prices encouraged some selective buying by the
major British institutions, lifting stocks off their session lows.
Some dealers said the institutions were merely waiting for the
market to reach these lower levels before they returned to purchase
stock on a large scale.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 1.2 points lower at
1,683.0. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 5.58 points to
close at 1,162.26.
</TEXT>
