<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most futures prices for soybeans and grains were
lower at the close Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analyst Barney Janecki of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. said most of
the pressure was in the wheat pit where traders were concerned
about a reduction in the U.S. export bonus offers to the Soviet
Union as the result of the pact reached by 100 nations meeting at
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade talks in Geneva.
   The accord calls for an overall cap on farm supports and import
barriers through 1990, officials reported.
   Wheat prices slipped as much as 6{ cents for the May contract.
   Profit-taking was reported in new crop soybeans after they had
gained some ground in recent days, said Janecki.
   He said weather in the U.S. Midwest and South America was not a
significant factor on the market.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 6{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.94 a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to { cent higher, with May at $2.66 a bushel; oats were }
cent lower to \ cent higher, with May at $1.86; and soybeans were {
cent to 3{ cents lower, with May at $7.13{ a bushel.
