<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MilkenBjt     04-07 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Milken Bjt,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milken, Brother Plead Innocent To Racketeering, Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Milken, former head of Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.'s high-yield junk bond department, pleaded innocent
Friday to a wide-ranging federal indictment that charged him with
turning the investment banking house into a racketeering enterprise.
   Milken, dressed in a navy blue, pinstriped suit entered his plea
in a courtroom packed with more than 200 reporters, lawyers and the
curious.
   Also entering innocent pleas before U.S. District Judge Kimba
Wood at federal court in Manhattan was Milken's brother, Lowell,
40. A third defendant, former Drexel trader Bruce L. Newberg was
absent due to a skiing accident and will be arraigned at a later
date.
   All three were named in a 98-count federal securities fraud and
racketeering indictment handed up by a grand jury March 29.
   Michael Milken entered the courtroom smiling and when Ms. Wood
asked him how he felt, replied: ``O.K., your honor,'' prompting
laughter from the standing-room-only crowd.
   Both Milkens were released without having to post bail after
Assistant U.S. Attorney John Carroll said prosecutors and defense
lawyers had ``made substantial progress'' during talks to reach an
acceptable bond for the defendants and their assets.
   The charges seek $1.8 billion in forfeitures from each of the
three defendants, or their total combined earnings from 1984 to
1987. The government reportedly had asked the three defendants each
to post a $1 billion bond to avoid pretrial restraints on their
assets.
   Under the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations
act, assets found to be the result of racketeering activities are
subject to forfeiture and prosecutors could ask the judge to freeze
the Milkens' assets to guarantee their availability in the event of
conviction.
   If convicted, each of the three also face maximum fines of $3.7
billion if convicted on either or both of the racketeering counts.
   Those fines represent the highest possible amounts under federal
racketeering law _ that is, double the gains made from the
allegedly illegal enterprise _ that a judge may impose.
   Ms. Wood scheduled another court session for Tuesday morning, at
Carroll's request, to finalize bond arrangements. The judge also
scheduled Newberg's arraignment for April 25.
   Milken, 42, following his indictment took a leave of absence
from his job as head of Drexel's Beverly Hills, Calif.-based
high-yield junk bond division, where he reportedly made more than
$1 billion between 1983 and 1987.
   Milken widely is considered a pioneer in making the low-grade
securities a key source of financing for a wide range of corporate
deals.
   The racketeering indictment followed a more than two-year
investigation of Wall Street's fifth-largest investment firm was
triggered by information supplied by convicted stock speculator
Ivan Boesky.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890407-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1517EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AppleShipments     04-07 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apple Shipments,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Apple Shipments Report First Weekly Increase In Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WENATCHEE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipments of Washington state apples
increased slightly last week after losing ground for a month, an
indication consumers may be overcoming fears of a chemical scare
that began in February, an industry official said Friday.
   Total out-of-state shipments last week were 1.196 million
42-pound boxes, compared with 1.191 million the previous week, said
Bill Dewitt, manager of the Wenatchee Valley Traffic Association,
which tracks sales of Washington apples, the largest apple crop in
the nation.
   Washington state shipments represent the first increase in a
month, but the numbers are still below the annual average, Dewitt
said. For the same week last year, more than 1.4 million boxes were
shipped.
   Figures from other big apple-growing states _ New York, Michigan
and Virginia _ were not available Friday, but Dewitt said other
states appear to reflect Washington's upturn.
   ``I do know what they've been doing over the last three weeks is
comparable and I would hope they are leveling out, too,'' he said.
   Included in the Washington state figures is a 10,000-box
increase in the Red Delicious variety, a sign that consumers are
overcoming fears of potential health risks posed by the
growth-regulating chemical Alar, Dewitt said.
   Alar is used primarily on red varieties of apples to enhance
color and keep them on the tree longer, although industry officials
contend the chemical is used on only 5 percent of the crop.
   ``The good news is we had considerably more Red Delicious
shipped last week,'' Dewitt said. ``The shipments have been going
down, especially on Red Delicious, for the past four weeks or so.
This is the first turnaround we've had. We hope it's a sign of
things to come.''
   The national Alar scare has prompted apple growers to consider a
variety of tactics to ease the drop in sales, including destroying
all Alar-treated apples now in storage.
   However, Dewitt attributed the turnaround to an aggressive
marketing campaign by apple marketers and statements by health
officials that the amounts of Alar in the fruit pose no known
health problems.
   ``We think we're beginning to see some results from the good
advertising by retailers,'' he said. ``We're beginning to see the
results of statements by the USDA (Department of Agriculture), the
surgeon general, the EPA (Environmental Protection Agency) and the
FDA (Food and Drug Administration) that there is no problem with
the amount of Alar in some of the apples now.''
   Apple shipments reached record-high levels in the two weeks
following a report in late February by the Natural Resources
Defense Council, which contended Alar was a cancer-causing agent.
Since then, shipments have fallen steadily, reflecting orders made
since the report's release.
   ``We should be doing more. April normally is a good month for
us,'' Dewitt said. ``We need to be up in at least the 1.5-million
box range for the next few weeks to really be able to get our
apples sold.''
   Taiwan, which canceled several orders immediately after the Alar
report, has begun accepting shipments of about 30,000 boxes a week,
which is ``good'' for this time of year, Dewitt said.
   While shipments of the Red Delicious variety fell, shipments of
the state's two other major varieties, non-red Golden Delicious and
Granny Smith, have been extremely good, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
