<DOCNO> AP890407-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Debt     04-07 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Bank to Lend Up to $2 Billion, Official Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Voljc is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank likely will lend Mexico
between $1.5 billion and $2 billion this year, that institution's
Mexico representative said Friday.
   Marco Voljc told reporters the funds will be used to develop
infrastructure and not to bolster Mexico's balance of payments and
foreign reserves. Similar credits could be extended on an annual
basis, he said.
   The credit will help President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's
government press forward with its efforts to cut net outflow of
capital needed to revitalize Mexico's stagnant economy.
   Salinas has sought to reduce foreign debt servicing, which will
cost about $16 billion this year, and to obtain $7 billion through
lower payments and new loans each year for the next six years.
   Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe visited Washington and New York
this week to press for an accord with creditor governments and
banks that would slice Mexico's debt servicing from 6 percent to 2
percent of its gross national product this year.
   Voljc said the World Bank credit would apply to development
projects involving roads and agroindustries, among other projects.
   In a related development, the World Bank will extend a $250
million credit to Mexico for the purchase of industrial equipment,
the government newspaper El Nacional reported Friday.
   Voljc noted that the goverment still must sign a letter of
intent with the International Monetary Fund that pledges additional
economic reforms before Mexico's $107 billion foreign debt can be
restructured.
   Mexico has enacted drastic reforms designed to end decades of
protectionism and force domestic industries to become competitive
internationally. The government dismantled thousands of import
barriers after it joined the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
in 1986.
   Painful austerity highlighted by liquidations of state-owned
industries and federal spending cuts has cost thousands of workers
their jobs. Workers have lost more than half their buying power
since the onset of the foreign debt crisis in 1982.
   Mexico's reserves, which stood at a record high of $16 billion
in April 1988, have plummeted to $7 billion, according to the
Center for Private Sector Economic Studies. Debt servicing and the
need to finance capital and consumer goods imports under the trade
reforms contributed to the drain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
