<DOCNO> AP890407-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Directors'Pay     04-07 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Directors' Pay,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Directors' Pay Continues to Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pay to outside directors of some of the nation's
major coporations rose last year, with the biggest gains reported
in the financial services industry, according to a study released
Friday.
   Of 909 companies surveyed by the Conference Board, 42 percent
increased pay for outside directors last year while only 2 percent
cut back on compensation. The remainder held roughly at 1987 levels.
   According to the survey, the median annual compensation to
directors in the financial services industry jumped 16 percent to
$19,800. The increase followed a year in which virtually no gains
were seen.
   However, it appeared more lucrative to sit on the board of a
manufacturing concern, where the median compensation in cash and
stock grants amounted to $24,000, up 9 percent.
   Manufacturing companies whose annual sales top $5 billion paid
their directors a median $40,000.
   The Conference Board said the median compensation for directors
of service companies like department stores and hotels held at the
1987 median level of $17,600.
   Jeremy Bacon, the board's specialist in directorship practices,
said the increases for manufacturing and financial service concerns
``are large enough to suggest that there is competitive pressure
pushing director compensation higher.''
   He noted that increases are deserved. ``Directors are putting in
longer hours than ever before and making tough calls. There is a
price for that kind of service and commitment.''
   Bacon noted that retirement plans and stock options continue to
gain in popularity as forms of compensation. Last year 28 percent
of the companies polled provided a retirement plan for outside
directors, up from 21 percent in 1987, while 14 percent had stock
options provisions, up from 9 percent in the previous year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
