<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 2334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FederalComputers     04-07 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Federal Computers,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Computer Chiefs Leaving For Private Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The failure of Congress to raise federal
salaries is accelerating a brain drain of computer experts from the
government, according to a report in the forthcoming issue of
Information Week magazine.
   Fourteen computer chiefs have left federal service in the last
three years, most of them for sales and marketing jobs with
companies that do business with federal agencies, the magazine says
in its April 10 issue.
   ``Now that we didn't get pay raises, lots will be looking. I
am,'' Reed Phillips, director of information resources management
at the Commerce Department, told the magazine.
   Pay for computer chiefs is sometimes as little as a third what
people could earn in private business, the magazine said. The pay
raise, which was snagged by controversy over a raise for Congress,
would have lifted the ceiling on senior executive pay to $125,000
from $80,000.
   Vacancies have caused ``serious trouble'' at the Internal
Revenue Service and NASA, according to Patricia Ingraham, a task
force member of Paul Volcker's privately funded National Commission
on the Public Service quoted by the magazine.
   Other departments having trouble with vacancies are the
Department of Health and Human Services and the top-secret National
Security Agency, the magazine said.
   At NASA, spokeswoman Terri Sindelar said Friday the low pay
ceiling and other factors that caused professionals to leave were
hurting the entire agency, not just computer operations. ``This is
undercutting the space program by causing a brain drain,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
