<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1810EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv08-09 1stAdd 04-07 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 08-09, 1st Add,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions April 8-9</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: said Leinweber.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some futures price trends for the past week:
   Futures prices for grains and soybeans tumbled during the period
on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in May settled Friday at $3.91{ a bushel,
down from $4.03} a week ago. May corn fell to $2.66 a bushel from
$2.68{; May oats went from $1.87\ to $1.85{; and May soybeans
plunged to $7.11} from $7.38\.
   Livestock and meat prices were lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Cattle settled Friday at 77.85 cents a pound for the contract
for delivery in April, down from 78.07 cents a week earlier; April
feeder cattle were 77.62 cents, compared to 81.20 cents the
previous week; April live hogs went from 40.25 cents to 39.55 cents
a pound; and April frozen poek bellies slipped to 34.32 cents a
pound from 37.35 cents.
   Precious metals traded steady to lower on the Commodity Exchange
in New York.
   Gold for April settled at $383.40 a troy ounce on Friday, down
from $385.10; and April silver was $5.77 a troy ounce _ just where
it was a week ago.
   Energy futures declined on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   May crude oil went from $20.19 a barrel the previous week to
settle Friday at $20.02; May heating oil was 51.60 cents a gallon,
compared to 53.37 cents a week ago; and May unleaded gasoline fell
from 66.97 cents a gallon to 64.55 cents.
