<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-07 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Week On Rising Note, Gold Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against most major currencies
Friday amid buying inspired by signs of continuing economic
strength in a government employment report and market rumors.
   Gold prices posted modest declines. Republic National Bank of
New York quoted a bid of $383.25 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4
p.m. EDT, 35 cents lower than Thursday's late bid.
   Walter Simon, an assistant vice president at Bank Julius Baer &amp;
Co., said dealers bid up the dollar after judging that, on balance,
the Labor Department figures indicated economic growth persists at
more than just a mediocre pace.
   The ambiguous report, which was open to numerous
interpretations, said the civilian unemployment rate fell to a new
15-year low of 5.0 percent last month from 5.1 percent in February.
   The decline, however, was accompanied by a slowdown in job
creation as nonfarm payrolls expanded by 180,000, down from
February's 280,000.
   Additional details in the report were similarly mixed; some
supported the notion that economic activity has moderated while
others hinted at a buildup in inflationary pressures.
   The dollar also moved ahead on buying sparked by two unconfirmed
reports, one involving the possibility of a $30 billion tax cut in
the United States.
   Rumors of the imminent resignation of a high-ranking Japanese
government official _ said by some accounts to be Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita _ caused dealers to lighten their yen holdings in
favor of the U.S. currency.
   The dollar began its trading day in Tokyo where it fell 0.07 yen
to close at 132.08 yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 132.42
yen and in New York it finished at 132.725 yen, up from 132.275 on
Thursday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound, which
fell to $1.6975 from $1.7035 late Thursday. Sterling fetched
$1.6945 late in New York, compared to $1.7005 Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
late rates, included: 1.8765 West German marks, up from 1.8730;
1.6499 Swiss francs, up from 1.6445; 6.336 French francs, up from
6.3250; 1,376.00 Italian lire, up from 1,373.50; and, 1.19305
Canadian dollars, down from 1.19325.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.8745 West German marks, up from 1.8700;
1.6500 Swiss francs, up from 1.6415; 6.3340 French francs, up from
6.3125; 2.1110 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1090; 1,373.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,371.75; and 1.1928 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1935.
   In New York, a troy ounce of gold for current delivery closed at
$383.40 on the Commodity Exchange, down from Thursday's settlement
of $384.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $381.75 a troy ounce,
compared with $384.75 late Thursday. In Zurich, gold fell to close
at $382.00 an ounce compared with $384.35 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 59 cents to close at $386.15 an
ounce.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid of $5.76 a troy ounce, compared with
Thursday's $5.82.
   Silver for current delivery also declined in New York, falling
to $5.769 an ounce on the Comex from $5.800 on Thursday.
</TEXT>
