<FIRST>u f AM-BigThreeLeaders     04-07 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Big Three Leaders,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Who's In The Drivers Seats in 1990?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers are beginning to set up
the order of succession as the automotive industry heads into the
1990s, and the pictures are clearing up a little.
   But there's still one question: Who is the odds-on favorite to
follow Roger Smith at General Motors Corp.?
   There were reports through the week that Allan Gilmour, now
executive vice president at Ford Motor Co., is on track to be
Chairman Donald Petersen's successor in the fall of 1991, when
Petersen reaches Ford's mandatory retirement age of 65.
   The reports said an announcement could come as early as Monday
of Gilmour becoming a vice chairman. Ford officials decline to
comment.
   Over at Chrysler Corp., Chairman Lee Iacocca's contract runs out
in December 1991, and there's speculation that he would not seek
another. He would be 67 years old then.
   In November, Chrysler shuffled its upper-level management,
leaving Gerald Greenwald as vice chairman and likely successor to
Iacocca.
   So far, no one has emerged as the favorite follower to Smith,
who turns 65 in July of next year, and stands to be the first of
the current chairmen to move aside.
   ``There's no question at GM there's a number of people in the
running,'' said analyst Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. ``It's
just a question of exactly who.''
   Merlis said automotive chief executive officers of the 1990s
will have to have some specific skills.
   ``It's going to be much more international than ever before,''
he said of the industry. ``Managing joint ventures is going to be
important. Running Europe is going to be important.''
   Greenwald and Gilmour each have work in international automotive
operations on their resumes. Gilmour currently is Ford's executive
vice president for international operations.
   Before moving to Chrysler in April 1979, Greenwald served as
president or a director of Ford businesses in France and Venezuela
and at the company's European headquarters.
   ``Certainly the opportunities for the (Ford and GM) CEOs of the
'90s is cross-fertilization between the United States and Europe,''
Merlis said.
   Merlis added that for Chrysler, which doesn't have the same
presence in Europe as do its two larger cousins, ``it is how to
take its beachhead in Europe and turn it into more meaningful
penetration.''
   Along with international operations, Merlis said new CEOs will
have problems in the United States which will require some
experience in the financial end of the car-making business.
   From September 1979 through July of 1983 Greenwald was
Chrysler's executive vice president for finance. Gilmour joined
Ford in 1960 as part of the financial staff and rose to executive
vice president for finance in 1968, a post he held until 1972.
   ``The real challenge will be fixing the (manufacturing)
overcapacity problem,'' Merlis said. ``It's not a problem that will
last long. Clearly plants will have to close and that's a challenge
the CEOs will have to face.''
</TEXT>
