<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-07 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose in light trading Friday
in what analysts called a technical recovery from a decline in the
previous session.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 22
cents to close at $20.02 a barrel. Other contract months also
gained.
   Refined products traded on the exchange also rose. Unleaded
gasoline for May delivery closed .40 cent higher at 64.95 cents a
gallon and May heating oil settled up .38 cent at 51.60 cents.
Other contract months mostly were higher.
   Energy brokers attributed Friday's gains mostly to technical
factors, but said the market got a lift from news that Exxon Corp.
and British Petroleum Inc. would not curtail crude shipments to the
West Coast because of the oil spill off the Alaskan coast.
   In addition, British Petroleum announced the shutdown of an oil
platform in the North Sea for repairs.
   ``That takes production out of the market and impacts prices,''
said Richard Kane, energy broker with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Crude prices also continue to gain strength from investor
confidence that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
is serious about reducing production.
   The International Energy Agency in its monthly oil market report
on Friday estimated OPEC production for March at 19.6 million
barrels a day, 200,000 barrels less than in February. The cartel
has cut its production by about 3 million barrels since last
December in an effort to strengthen world oil prices.
</TEXT>
