<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-07 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Prices Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices tumbled Friday on the Chicago Board of
Trade as a new trading agreement in Switzerland sent shockwaves
across the Atlantic.
   On other futures markets, livestock and meat prices were mostly
lower; precious metals slipped; copper soared and energy prices
advanced.
   Wheat prices slipped as much as 9 cents for the May contract.
   Barney Janecki, a Chicago analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc., said traders were concerned about a reduction in the U.S.
export bonus offers to the Soviet Union as the result of the pact
reached Friday by 100 nations meeting at the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade talks in Geneva.
   The GATT accord calls for an overall cap on farm supports and
import barriers through 1990, officials reported.
   Profit-taking was reported in new crop soybeans after they had
gained some ground in recent days, said Janecki.
   He said weather in the U.S. Midwest and South America was not a
significant factor on the market.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 9 cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in May at $3.91{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cent lower to {
cent higher, with May at $2.66 a bushel; oats were 1\ cent lower to
\ cent higher, with May at $1.85{; and soybeans were 2\ cent to 6
cents lower, with May at $7.11} a bushel.
   Most livestock and meat prices were lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Tom Morgan, president of Sterling Research of Arlington Heights,
Ill., said the pork complex was depressed by the current large hog
slaughter.
   The cattle market sold off early due, which Morgan attributed to
a seasonally low demand period at this time, but prices for live
cattle recovered late in the session.
   Cattle settled .30 cent higher to .30 cent lower, with the
contract for delivery in April at 77.85 cents a pound, feeder
cattle were .20 cent to 1.05 cent lower, with April at 77.62 cents
pound; live hogs were .15 cent higher to .42 cent lower, with April
at 39.55 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to
.90 cent lower, with April at 34.32 cents a pound.
   Copper prices soared and precious metals fell on the Commodity
Exchange in New York.
   Analyst Tony Ellis of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc. said
there was talk of tighter supplies among copper traders, but he
credited the day's rally in copper futures mostly to technical
reasons.
   Gold, which ususally moves in the opposite direction of the U.S.
dollar, was depressed by a firmer dollar, analysts said.
   Gold settled 60 cents to 70 cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in April at $383.40 a troy ounce; silver was 3.1 cents to
3.7 cents lower, with April at $5.77 a troy ounce; and copper was
1.9 cents to 3.15 cents higher, with April at $1.34 a pound.
   Most energy prices were higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Crude oil settled 22 cents to 49 cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in May at $20.02 a barrel; heating oil was .31 cent
lower to .38 cent higher, with May at 51.60 cents a gallon; and
unleaded gasoline was .40 cent to 1.15 cents higher, with May at
64.95 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
