<FIRST>u f AM-Milken-Supporters     04-07 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Milken-Supporters,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dozens of Supporters Pack Milken Arraignment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Milken Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young, trim, well-dressed and earnest, dozens of
friends and self-proclaimed fans of Michael Milken came to a
federal courthouse Friday to see the deposed junk bond king
arraigned.
   Other businessmen and colleagues promised to mount a public
campaign against charges that Milken engineered a series of illegal
deals cited by the government in a landmark 98-count fraud and
racketeering indictment against he and two others.
   ``It's hard for those who know him to square what the
government's alleging against what we see privately,'' said Ralph
Ingersoll, chairman of Ingersoll Publications Co. and a friend of
Milken's.
   Milken, 42, is credited with helping reshape corporate America
in the 1980s from his Beverly Hills, Calif., office of Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. through the sale of high-yield junk bonds that
allowed small- and medium-sized companies to expand rapidly _ and
gave corporate raiders a ready source of financing.
   He has been a target of government prosecutors for more than two
years and is charged with defrauding clients, investors and the
public by violating securities laws. Supporters and defense lawyers
claim he has been unfairly persecuted.
   More than 200 reporters, courtroom artists, lawyers and Milken
friends packed the courtroom to hear Milken and his brother Lowell
plead not guilty to all charges. Another 50 people were kept
outside for lack of space.
   After the arraignment, dozens of supporters cheered and shouted
``Good luck, Michael,'' as he descended the courthouse steps, shook
some hands and was whisked away in a limousine.
   Supporters also rallied for Milken at the Beverly Hilton Hotel,
site of Drexel's annual junk bond conference in Beverly Hills.
   A handful of fans at the Manhattan courthouse wore white
baseball caps saying ``Mike Milken, We Believe In You'' _ the same
message that appeared in full-page ads paid for by friends and
business associates in major newspapers last week.
   Supporters questioned by an Associated Press reporter refused to
say whether they worked for Drexel, which has reached a plea deal
with the government to settle securities fraud charges.
   Drexel denied reports that the government told it to bar a
planned rally by Drexel employees at the court in support of Milken.
</TEXT>
