<DOCNO> AP890407-0314 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1903EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     04-07 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Bond Prices End Lower On Employment Figures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished lower Friday, retreating
quickly after an early spurt in a confused reaction to the Labor
Department's employment report, which contained both good and bad
news for traders.
   The good news that caused a brief rally was that the non-farm
payroll rose less than expected in March. The bad news was that the
civilian jobless rate fell to 5 percent, the lowest in more than 15
years.
   Strong economic growth chills the bond market by raising fears
of higher inflation, which erodes fixed-income securities.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond, up nearly a point in the
first half-hour after the report's 8:30 a.m. EDT release, ended the
day with a decline of 11-16 point, or $6.88 per $1,000 face amount.
   The bond's yield, which rises when the price falls, climbed to
9.11 percent from 9.01 percent late Thursday.
   Trading was light despite confusion over the figures and the
widespread expectation that they would have a powerful effect on
the market. Some traders said the market had already begun looking
ahead to next week's wholesale price report for guidance.
   ``Life on Wall Street, expecially in fixed-income securities, is
spent waiting for the next number,'' said Anthony Naylor, a senior
vice president at Rodman &amp; Renshaw Inc.
   Besides the drop in the jobless rate, traders were concerned
about a 0.4 percent increase in average hourly earnings, which
indicated inflation continues to rise, said William V. Sullivan,
director of money market research for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Prices of short-term governments fell 1-16 point to 9-32 point,
intermediate maturities were off about 5-16 point and long-term
issues fell about 11-16 point, according to Telerate Inc., a
financial data service.
   The movement of a point equals a $10 change in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 3.32 to 1,121.07.
   In corporate trading, industrials fell. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, slipped
1.19 to 299.09.
   Prices of municipal bonds also fell. The Bond Buyer index was
not available late Friday.
   The pessimism about inflation did not carry over to the Treasury
bill market.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 9.11 percent as the
discount dropped 5 basis points to 8.80 percent. Yields on
six-month bills rose to 9.27 percent as the discount rose 2 basis
points to 8.75 percent. Yields on the one-year bills issued on
Thursday rose to 9.50 percent as the discount rose 1 basis point to
8.75 percent from the level at auction.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 9} percent, down from 913-16 percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
