<FIRST>u f AM-Bilzerian     04-07 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bilzerian,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Plans To Keep Fraud Case in New York</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said Friday he plans to deny a
request to dismiss securities fraud charges against Singer Co.
chairman and takeover specialist Paul A. Bilzerian.
   U.S. District Judge Robert J. Ward also said at a hearing that
he would refuse to move the case, scheduled for a trial beginning
May 1, to federal court in Tampa, Fla., where Bilzerian lives.
   The judge indicated he would drop one of 12 counts in an
indictment handed up by a federal grand jury last December, but
said he would not make a formal ruling on any of the matters until
Tuesday.
   Bilzerian, 38, is accused of violating securities and tax laws,
conspiracy and making false statements to the government in
connection with four securities transactions in 1985 and 1986.
   The government contends that Bilzerian made millions of dollars
by accumulating stock in takeover targets, concealing ownership of
the stocks in secret accounts and then selling his holdings after
the stock price had risen.
   Much of the government's case is derived from information
supplied to the government by Los Angeles broker Boyd L. Jefferies,
who has admitted to two felonies for violating federal securities
laws.
   Jefferies also supplied information for the government's stock
manipulation case against GAF Corp., which ended in a second
mistrial last month.
   Bilzerian faces a maximum penalty of five years in jail and a
$250,000 fine on each count.
</TEXT>
