<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest 1stLd-Writethru f0264 04-07 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0264,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest's Board Rejects Takeover Bid, Davis Vows To Continue Pursuit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with comments from Davis, analysts, governor; ADDS byline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede MINNEAPOLIS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NWA Inc., parent company of Northwest
Airlines, on Friday rejected a $2.62 billion bid by Los Angeles
billionaire Marvin Davis to acquire the airline concern, but Davis
vowed to continue his efforts.
   The NWA board based its decision on advice from its financial
adviser that Davis' $90-a-share offer was inadequate. The board
reaffirmed its intention to maintain the airline as an independent
entity.
   ``Our board has carefully considered Mr. Davis' proposal as well
as numerous other financial and strategic alternatives available to
NWA. It is clear that Mr. Davis' proposal does not fully reflect
the value of NWA,'' said Steve Rothmeier, chairman and chief
executive officer of NWA.
   Davis, whose bid was set to expire April 21, has insisted his
bid is friendly and that he would not sell off parts of the company.
   ``We have a strong, serious interest in owning NWA. In that
regard, we are in the process of completing financing arrangements
for the acquisition and expect to be in a position to describe them
shortly,'' a spokesman for Davis, Jim Fingeroth, said after the NWA
board rejected Davis' bid.
   The board's decision was announced after the stock market
closed. In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, NWA fell 50
cents a share to close at $88.75 on Friday.
   Davis announced his bid about a week ago, several days after NWA
disclosed that an investor group whose identity has still not been
revealed had a 4.9 percent stake in the company.
   In the NWA statement, Rothmeier said Northwest's value is
demonstrated by recent federal airline performance statistics and
the company's expectations for earnings growth.
   ``First, according to U.S. Department of Transportation
statistics, our airline achieved excellent on-time and customer
satisfaction during the last quarter. Second, we expect NWA's
first-quarter earnings to be at record levels,'' Rothmeier said in
a statement.
   ``Our confidence in NWA's potential is combined with a
realization that our shareholders, employees and customers are just
beginning to see the benefits of our acquisition of Republic,'' he
said. ``In light of these considerations, the board has concluded
that it is not appropriate to seek a sale of NWA.''
   Kurt Rivard, an analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc. in Minneapolis,
said NWA's anticipated record first-quarter earnings would make a
$90 a share offer inadequate and will figure significantly in
future takeover discussions.
   ``This sets a basis for a re-evaluation of earnings estimates up
and given that it would make the premium that would someone would
have to pay to acquire the company higher,'' Rivard said.
   ``Northwest has not made money in the first quarter since 1985
and the reason for that is the airline business, especially for an
international carrier, is very seasonal. Yields are also weak
during that period,'' he said.
   Davis intends to proceed aggressively, said Fingeroth, who is
with the New York public relations firm of Kekst and Co.
   ``We are disappointed that the board has rejected this very
generous offer without even exploring it with us especially in view
of our expressed willingness to consider a higher price if
additional value can be demonstrated,'' he said.
   In Washington, Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn., told reporters that
in a meeting he held earlier Friday with Davis, the would-be
purchaser described his financial plan to him and that he believed
the suitor's proposal was ``a very attractive offer.''
   The lawmaker said despite the rejection by the NWA board, the
proposal was one that ``would not burden the airline with an
unacceptable debt load.''
   Oberstar said Davis had told him it would be ``financial folly''
to sell any of the carrier's assets, that he would not seek salary
or benefit concessions from employees, and that he would establish
a major maintenance facility in Minnesota for the European-made
Airbus aircraft Northwest is purchasing.
   The maintenance base would provide 1,000 to 1,500 jobs, the
legislator said.
   According to Oberstar, Davis will meet soon with Northwest union
leaders.
   Oberstar said Davis would reveal the details of his financial
plan to the public next Wednesday. The lawmaker said making the
plan public might help Davis because NWA board had not yet seen the
specifics of his financing.
   The congressman said he was not endorsing Davis' offer, but he
added, ``This is a very attractive offer and we ought to think
about it very seriously.''
   Oberstar, chairman of the House aviation subcommittee, said he
met with the NWA suitor aboard Davis' Boeing 727 jet at the airport
in Nashville, Tenn. Oberstar, who said he inititated the meeting,
had traveled to Nashville to address a convention.
</TEXT>
