<FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-89 0340EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-MineStrike     04-07 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mine Strike,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pittston Says Mines Are Operating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pittston Co. said it continued to
operate most of its Virginia and West Virginia coal mines Thursday,
the first full day of a strike by 1,400 members of the United Mine
Workers union.
   Pittston Co. spokeswoman Susan Copeland said that the company
would not release details about which facilities were working.
   ``We are operating most of them,'' Copeland said. ``They're not
all up to par, but they will be. But we won't be outlining which
operations we are operating and which we are not.''
   The UMW said members of 22 local unions were called out on
strike at 4 p.m. Wednesday. Pittston operations in Kentucky and
some small operations in Virginia and West Virginia were not
included in the work stoppage. UMW spokesman Joe Corcoran said that
may change.
   Some 1,700 miners in the three states have been working without
a contract for 14 months, since the 1984 national agreement expired
on Jan. 31, 1988.
   Corcoran said the union would like Pittston to reconsider its
plan to bring in replacements for the strikers. He said he was not
hopeful that they would.
   ``It's very easy to take advantage of the unemployment in
Appalachia,'' Corcoran said. ``It seems they'd just as soon pit an
unemployed miner against another miner on strike. They don't care.''
   Negotiations are due to resume in Washington next week,
according to Corcoran. Talks that had been scheduled for Thursday
and Friday of this week were postponed at the company's request, he
said.
</TEXT>
